<HEADLINE>Ashbourne is making strong progress as income hits #6.5m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159343</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROBLEMS with local authority funding of Community Care have caused
difficulties for many private nursing home operators seeking to fill their
homes. Ashbourne is no exception despite the fact that it concentrates on the
top end of the market.
Typically, it charges around #50 more than rival competitors, equivalent to
about #350 per week for a single room. Recently, there have been signs of
stability returning to the market. In any case, demographic trends suggest a
need for the industry to provide an extra 50,000 beds by the end of the decade.
Last year, Ashbourne's occupancy level slipped to 82% from 86%. Chief executive
Tom Hamilton said he was ``quite pleased'' given the toughness of the market.
However, he sees scope to increase the overall occupancy level to 90%.
Oversupply in certain geographic areas, particularly north-west England,
dragged down the overall occupancy level.
Part of the drop in occupancy level was down to the opening of three new homes
and the commencement of developments on a further six sites in south-east
England at a cost of #14m. In addition, four purpose built homes were acquired
during the year for #8m. It takes about a year before a home is mature and
fully contributing to the profit and loss account.
In the 52 weeks to October 1, Ashbourne increased profits from #1.2m to #6.5m,
helped by a sharp fall in interest payments following last year's market
flotation. Year-end gearing was 23% and is expected to rise to around 45% by
the end of next year.
The company has a strong balance sheet as a result of the #50m raised at the
time of flotation. There is a final dividend of 2.2p net. For the full year,
City analysts are forecasting pre-tax profits of #7m to #7.3m as contributions
roll in from new homes.
South-east England is the focus of Ashbourne's expansion plan given the
relatively low bed density in that part of the UK. However, that does not
preclude openings elsewhere. Indeed, the group has recently received planning
permission to open a third home in Edinburgh.
Mr Hamilton is confident that for the foreseeable future 10 new homes can be
opened a year without any strain on existing managerial capacity. The group is
looking into the possibility of lease financing future development.
The 20% stake held by Sun Healthcare of the US provides some speculative
interest. Andrew Turner, chairman and chief executive of Sun Healthcare, has
joined Asbourne's board.
Some analysts believe that Sun will eventually want to consolidate the holding
with its Exceler UK nursing homes acquired last year. Ashbourne shares are
likely to remain underpinned by bid speculation.
Yesterday, the shares gained 1p to 140p.
</TEXT>
