<HEADLINE>Ashdown tells of knife attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159344</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown yesterday described how a knife was held
to his throat as he walked the streets of Yeovil, Somerset.
Mr Ashdown, a former marine commando, brushed off suggestions that his military
background had been any advantage in fighting off his attacker.
``I should think my military training was about as relevant as the Rev Mark
Ellis's training in the Church of England,'' he said, referring to the local
minister who was present when the attack took place.
The incident happened as the Liberal Democrat leader walked around the town
centre at 11.30pm on Sunday night.
``Suddenly we were ap-proached and accosted by a group of three youths in their
early twenties.
``There was a good deal of taunting and abuse.''
The youths were joined by an older man who was drunk.
``I said to him, `Would you like to come for a walk with me?', so we went for a
walk together through the streets. He kept on saying to me he wanted to stop. I
hoped I would be able to get him a bit more sober.
``Quite suddenly, he turned very aggressive and tried to knee me in the groin.
He was very drunk, so I saw it coming, and I moved out of the way, taking the
blow just on my inside left thigh.
``Then he pulled a flick knife out of his pocket and opened it.''
Mr Ashdown said the knife was held at the left side of his throat.
``That I decided was just a little bit too far so I pushed it away rather
forcibly.''
The police arrived and took a man into custody.
``Frankly, if it was not for the knife, it was the kind of incident that
happens in towns like Yeovil up and down the country which police have to cope
with.''
Mr Ashdown had launched a local initiative to combat racist attacks before
going on his tour of the area.
He escaped Sunday's incident shaken but unscathed.
q  A 51-year-old man was remanded in custody for eight days by magistrates at
Yeovil yesterday on two charges in connection with alleged offences involving
Mr Ashdown. He was accused of possessing an offensive weapon, a knife, and with
threatening unlawful violence.
</TEXT>
