<TEXT>
IF you're starting to feel the first pangs of Christmas fatigue, give yourself
a relaxing and refreshing break from the festive flurry with a seaweed body
mask treatment from one of the city's newest therapy centres. It will only mean
stealing a couple of hours from your schedule, and will work wonders for your
feelgood factor.
Thalossotherapy, derived from the Greek word thalassa, meaning sea, is one of
the treatments on offer at the McAlpine Centre, in McAlpine Street, Glasgow.
After an intense and invigorating body scrub, which is intended to promote cell
renewal, a body mask rich in algae, minerals, vitamins, amino acids and trace
elements is applied. Special thermal bandages fix it firmly round the body, and
while you lie down and relax for an hour, the treatment takes effect.
These sea-based preparations are a development of the Victorians' belief in the
beneficial properties of hot and cold baths of sea water baths.
The centre offers several different treatments, largely based on a holistic
approach to problems. Massage is used to relieve stiffness and soreness and to
dispel tension along with aromatherapy, which uses the restorative powers of
oils from plants, flowers and seeds. In this way, anxiety, migraine and stress
problems can be tackled, and some skin conditions, such as eczema, can be
relieved.
And if you really want the pay-off without the pain, try Eurowave, a
computerised slimming and cellulite treatment. This programme, says the
McAlpine, is based on the use of faradic current to work out the muscle and
give the effect of isometric exercise, but without the effort and in a fraction
of the time. Eurowave programmes for treating sports injuries, stress, PMT and
fluid retention are available.
So at this time of the year, don't ignore the one person who probably needs a
Christmas present more than most - you. And it will help you get into shape for
the season.
</TEXT>
