<HEADLINE>Parkhead club are hot on the trail of Aberdeen strike. Booth at the top of Celtic's wanted list</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159347</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN tasted success with their Coca-Cola Cup victory over Dundee on Sunday,
and yesterday they found themselves facing the first predatory raid on their
young players.
There is little doubt that Celtic would like to add striker Scott Booth to
their squad, but I understand that Celtic manager Tommy Burns has made no bid
for the Scottish internationalist.
He has, however, asked Aberdeen if Booth would be available for transfer and
appears to have been told to wait until after the cup final before renewing
interest.
Celtic need a striker and I believe that Burns has now been given the promised
cash to buy one, or even two, players.
There is close to #3m in the Parkhead kitty at present and Burns will be
allowed that amount to spend in a bid to win the premier division title.
Booth has replaced John McGinlay as the preferred target after Bolton Wanderers
decided that they could not do without the Scottish striker as they fight to
stave off relegation.
At the moment Booth - likened to Gary Lineker by Scotland manager Craig Brown
because of his regular scoring rate with the national side - still has 18
months of his contract to run.
However, Aberdeen do have other strikers and if they have not rejected Celtic's
interest out of hand it suggests that their manager, Roy Aitken, may be keeping
his options open.
If he was to sell Booth and collect in the region of #2m then he would be free
to spend that sum plus other money promised to him by chairman Ian Donald.
He could also argue that he won the trophy without Booth with both goals coming
from the strikers used on the day, Billy Dodds and Duncan Shearer.
It is a situation which Aitken must look at, and consider, even although he
tried to dismiss any transfer speculation yesterday.
He has been told by his directors that he can go out and spend money on players
he may want.
But, as always, there are limitations on the amount he can splash out. However,
if he was to sell shrewdly, then that money could be added to the cash he
already has available.
That was the way Alex Ferguson took the club to their glory years, selling
Steve Archibald to Spurs for #900,000 to give financial stability then
producing a side which brought more glory to Pittodrie than any other.
Yesterday, Aitken insisted that he would spend again and Donald announced that
all the money from the cup success - around #500,000 - plus the residue of the
share issue money was there for the manager to bring in new players.
Said Donald: ``We have cleared the #2.5m debt we incurred over the rebuilding
of the stadium and are now in a very strong position.
``The money from the cup success will go to the manager and there is more
available which he can spend as he wishes.
``He knows what he has available but the real future for this club is its
home-produced players - Stephen Glass proved that again in the cup final.''
Aitken, meanwhile, wants to resurrect his team's premier division challenge,
which appears to have been put on hold during the cup run. They have drifted 16
points off the pace set by Rangers, and that has to be attended to.
At the moment Aitken's side sit in fifth place, but they are closer to the
bottom of the table than the top if you examine the points totals.
Aberdeen suffered relegation torments last season when they could not string
results together with any consistency.
They have had the same problems this year in the league and Aitken knows he
cannot afford to have his team drop their standards.
Enjoying a cup success is fine, looking forward to a UEFA Cup place is even
better, but the league cannot be sidelined, and that is what Aitken will preach
to his players this week.
Meanwhile, he must also look to the future and wonder whether that will contain
the young men brought up at Pittodrie, such as Booth and Eoin Jess.
Midfielder Jess, rated at #3m, is one of seven top players out of contract at
the end of the season, and Aitken said: ``I will now be looking into
negotiations with those players to start sorting things out.
``Everybody seems to be happy with things at the moment, but there are several
out of contract and I want to know what their intentions are.''
A cup win brings immediate champagne and then, inevitably, for any manager he
headaches follow, especially when they must try to keep their star players out
of the clutches of more powerful rivals.
</TEXT>
