<HEADLINE>British boxer flees gunman during fight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRENDAN BOYLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159348</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Cape Town
A TOP South African official said today that the murder of a cashier during a
botched robbery attempt at an international boxing bout involving British
fighter Warren Stowe in Cape Town would not harm the country's bid for the 2004
Olympics.
However, the city's tourism chief Gordon Oliver said that yesterday's shooting
was a body blow to Cape Town's drive to become a major international tourism
venue. And another official said it was a major setback to the redevelopment of
black areas.
``This is very bad news for us. We are getting an international reputation for
violence that is not deserved but it will get worse if we don't do something
about it,'' said Oliver.
Describing the murder as a ``terrible isolated incident'', Chris Ball, chief
executive of Cape Town's Olympic bid committee, said that it would not impair
the city's ability to bid for the 2004 Games.
``Security has always been a necessary ongoing priority in the preparation of
Cape Town's bid,'' he said.
Stowe and his South African opponent Simon Maseko dived from the ring when
shots rang out during their middleweight clash at Guguletu township.
The bout was being screened live and television viewers watched in horror as
frightened broadcasters huddled under ringside tables, with fighters, fans and
officials seeking cover behind plastic chairs and overturned tables.
Cashier Wynand Bothma, who was counting the takings near the main entrance, was
killed during the shooting. His bloodstained body lay next to the table.
Today Stowe said that he thought he was going to die. ``I didn't know there was
a robbery going on. I thought they were shooting at me . . . I was terrified, I
thought I was going to die at that time,'' he said.
President Nelson Mandela, who is guiding South Africa from apartheid to
majority rule, said he had discussed the incident with Safety and Security
Minister Sydney Mufamadi but had no immediate comment.
Cape Town police spokesman Raymond Dowd said detectives had firm leads and
expected to make an arrest soon. He said a reward of 50,000 rand #9000 had been
offered.
Dowd said that security at indoor sports events was usually the responsibility
of organisers, adding: ``Obviously, the police can't be everywhere.''
Phumzile Mlambo-Ngcuka, the African National Congress member of parliament for
Guguletu, said the incident was a major setback to the redevelopment of black
areas.
``We are stunned and outraged. We are trying so hard to build the image and
morale of the area and this is absolutely the last thing we need,'' she said.
q A fan was killed in Pietersburg at a soccer match involving the country's
most popular team, Kaizer Chiefs. Security officials also confiscated more than
40 handguns from spectators entering the ground. In Johannesburg a security
officer shot himself in the foot as he celebrated a goal.-Reuter
</TEXT>
