<HEADLINE>Budget break in Brussels</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159349</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor took a break from Budget preparations yesterday for the slightly
wider issue of a single European currency.
Mr Kenneth Clarke was in Brussels meeting other EU finance ministers to discuss
technical moves towards monetary union.
The talks were dominated by a suggestion from Germany's finance minister Theo
Waigel that there should be a stability pact among EU states opting to join
monetary union, leading to a single currency by 1999, and those in the pact
would enforce budgetary discipline, including the possible use of fines for
states who did not obey the rules.
Mr Clarke said he did not believe the suggestions were a great threat to
national sovereignty.
``Theo Waigel has always been as clear as I have that the setting of tax is for
national governments, the setting of public expenditures is for national
governments. The kind of Budget I have tomorrow will always continue,'' he said.
Meanwhile, a rift in the European Commission over the proposed single currency
was exposed last night by former Labour leader and now Commissioner, Mr Neil
Kinnock.
He said monetary union in 1999 was ``unrealistic''. Commissioners in Brussels
have spent months denying they have serious doubts.
q Tesco is freezing petrol prices for a week to delay any bad news for
motorists in the Budget.
</TEXT>
