<HEADLINE>Railway buff stole to get toy engines</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159350</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MODEL-railway fanatic who used stolen credit cards to fraudulently purchase
99 toy locomotives has been jailed for 21 months.
Irishman Andrew Skally, 48, was dubbed ``the great little train robber'' after
he stole credit cards from people staying in religious retreats and used them
to buy the models, worth #3000, from shops across Britain.
He went to nunneries and monasteries and stole credit cards which were then
used to buy the top-of-the-range toys at Beatties stores - including ones in
East Kilbride, Glasgow, Kilmarnock, and Dumfries.
During his spree, which began in October 1992, he visited 35 branches of the
toy chain.
Police believe Skally travelled on British Rail Inter City routes visiting toy
shops on the way.
On his travels, he also stole model trains from Carlisle, Manchester, Leeds,
Harrogate, Sheffield, Kettering, Northampton, London, Reading, Bristol,
Watford, Luton, Winchester, Eastleigh, Southampton, and Bournemouth.
Fraud squad officer Will Wright, who picked up Skally's trail in Southampton,
Hampshire, said: ``This has been a very challenging case - the most bizarre I
have ever investigated.
``Even the credit card companies say they had never heard of anything like it.
``Just to buy nothing but locomotives is very strange.''
A spokeswoman for Beatties said: ``People who buy trains like this are usually
collectors who buy them to look at rather than run on a model railway track.''
At Southampton Crown Court, Hampshire, Skally, from Cork, admitted four charges
of obtaining property by deception.
He also pleaded guilty to four charges of burglary, two of theft, and one of
using a false instrument.
He asked for a further 129 offences to be taken into consideration.
</TEXT>
