<HEADLINE>Cantona spot on</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159351</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nottingham Forest 1,
Manchester United 1
ERIC Cantona refound his scoring boots last night against Nottingham Forest to
salvage a point for Manchester United at a frenzied City Ground.
Frank Clark's men looked to be hanging on for three points after Paul McGregor
marked his full debut with a goal after 19 minutes.
United had wasted a catalogue of chances, with Andy Cole and Ryan Giggs - who
hit the post when clean through - the most culpable.
But after 67 minutes, Cantona, who had gone six games without scoring - the
worst spell of his United career - since returning after his enforced
nine-month absence with a spot-kick equaliser against Liverpool, repeated the
dose.
It was the Frenchman who was felled from behind by Steve Chettle after he
seemed to have lost control of a pass by substitute Paul Scholes.
Forest protested furiously when referee Keith Cooper instantly pointed to the
spot, but the defender had undoubtedly made contact and Cantona ignored the
jeers to stroke confidently home.
Right at the death, Forest could have snatched victory but Richard Irving
headed wide when it looked easier to score.
</TEXT>
