<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cellmate tells inquiry of suicide prisoner's final hours</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159352</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAILED Arlene Elliot danced round her cell less than three hours before she
hanged herself with a makeshift noose.
A joint fatal accident inquiry heard yesterday that she had begged prison
doctors to take her off a powerful tranquilliser which was making her depressed.
Miss Elliot, a 17-year-old paranoid schizophrenic, was being dosed with the
tranquilliser Largactil every six hours at Cornton Vale jail near Stirling.
Her former cellmate, Anne McCann, sobbed as she told the inquiry at Stirling
Sheriff Court about Miss Elliot's last hours.
Miss McCann, 27, of Tormore Street, Govan, Glasgow, said: ``Arlene had written
a dirty letter to her boyfriend the night it happened. We laughed all the way
through it.
``I went to sleep on the top bunk but woke up to find her dancing about the
room. She was a dead happy wee lassie.''
When asked if she knew of anything that was bothering Miss Elliot, Miss McCann,
who is still a prisoner, blamed the strong tranquilliser.
She said: ``Arelene didn't need it and had asked to be taken off it because it
was making her depressed. In the morning before taking her medication she was
all right. After she got it she was pure depressed, pure down.''
Earlier, the inquiry heard that a third prisoner at Cornton Vale had tried to
hang herself in the same block less than a week after Miss Elliot's death, and
nine days after the death of Kelly Holland, also 17.
Prison staff had been alerted after finding a note in the the cell of
mother-of-three Esther Dale, 24.
Prison officer Margaret Horne, 39, said she had spent nearly an hour in Mrs
Dale's cell discussing her personal problems and trying to assist her.
Later, while prisoners were being locked up for the night, Mrs Dale, of Kerr
Street, Bridgeton, Glasgow, ran into an empty sitting room, tied a curtain
round her neck, and jumped off a radiator.
Mrs Horne said she ran to the room after hearing screams and she and another
two officers managed to get Mrs Dale down.
Mrs Dale escaped with only a bruised neck.
The inquiry heard that the prison had no system to check whether warders who
were supposed to be carrying out regular observations of suicide-risk prisoners
were actually doing so.
Investigating officer Detective Sergeant Andy Price said Miss Holland should
have been checked every 15 minutes by remand block officer John McFadyen, 32,
who had been on active service for only two months.
But there was no way of being certain that the checks were carried out on time
every time.
Mr Price said: ``I asked if there was a record of the observations, whereby an
officer ticked a box on a timesheet or used a key in a time clock.
``But I was told that he didn't write anything down, nor was there any
electronic means of recording when he carried out a particular check.''
Two seasoned prison officers broke down in the witness box as they recalled
finding Miss Elliot's body.
Moira Grattan, 32, a prison officer for four years, said she would have checked
on the prisoner in her cell after noticing that she had left a communal
recreation area.
She fought back tears as she recalled that she had been diverted by a request
to take some other prisoners for medication.
She returned in time to hear shouts, and rushed into Miss Elliot's cell to find
her hanging.
Avril McMurtie, 31, a prison officer for seven years, wept openly as she told
how she gave Miss Elliot the kiss of life.
The inquiry continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
