<HEADLINE>British soldiers set to guard border stronghold under Nato peace plan. Clinton plea for Bosnia force</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159353</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
PREPARING for his biggest foreign military mission, President Bill Clinton told
the American people tonight that US troops must go to Bosnia to secure the
peace but would ``fight fire with fire, and then some'' if attacked.
``We cannot stop all war for all time,'' Clinton said in a television speech
from the Oval Office. ``But we can stop some wars.
``We cannot save all women and all children. But we can save many. We cannot do
everything. But we must do what we can do.
``The people of Bosnia, our Nato allies and people around the world are looking
to America for leadership. Let us lead. That is our responsibility as
Americans.''
In an address as important as any in his presidency, Clinton laid out stark
reasons for sending 20,000 American troops as part of a Nato peacekeeping force
of 60,000 that is to enforce a Bosnian accord reached last week in Dayton, Ohio.
``If we're not there, Nato will not be there. The peace will collapse. The war
will re-ignite. The slaughter of innocents will begin again. A conflict that
already has claimed so many victims could spread like poison,'' he said.
Clinton was trying to convince a wary public and a sceptical Congress to back
him on what would be the biggest military deployment of his presidency.
He said the final Nato plan for the operation is to be sent to him later this
week and if it meets his approval he will immediately send it to Congress and
request its support.
While Congress debates it, Clinton said he would allow a small number of US
troops in a Nato advance mission that will establish headquarters and set up
communications. The full force would begin deploying in Bosnia in the days
following the formal signature of the peace agreement in Paris in mid-December,
Clinton said.
``Let me say at the outset: America's role will not be about fighting a war. It
will be about helping the people of Bosnia to secure their own peace.''
He said risks to the troops would be minimised because they will be heavily
armed and thoroughly trained. Making an overwhelming show of force will lessen
the need to use force.
Clinton cautioned that no deployment of US troops is risk-free and that ``this
one may well involve casualties''.
He took full responsibility for any harm that might befall the troops, but
issued a strong warning: ``Anyone contemplating any action that would endanger
our troops should know this: America protects its own. Anyone who takes on our
troops will suffer the consequences. We will fight fire with fire, and then
some.''
A key objective of the Democratic president was to convince enough members of
the Republican-led Congress to approve a non-binding resolution authorising the
mission.
Like all recent US presidents, Clinton maintains the Constitution gives him all
the authority he needs to send US troops. But it could be political suicide to
do so without explicit congressional support, especially on the verge of a
presidential election year.
Republican leaders are backing away from confrontation with the president on
the issue. A few days before the Dayton agreement was reached, Congress voted
to refuse to allow American troops to keep the peace there. Now it appears that
they will be allowed to         do so.
Senator Bob Dole, the Republican leader in the Senate, said today: ``I want to
be in a position to support the president. It seems to me, when it comes to
foreign policy, if we speak with one voice we're better off.''
The president will brief Congressional leaders in detail on the Bosnian plan
before leaving for London tomorrow.
Meanwhile, British troops are expected to be allocated the confrontation line
around the Serb stronghold of Banja Luka when the Nato peace force moves into
Bosnia next month. The area was the scene of some of the most ferocious
fighting of the three-year civil war in the run-up to the peace agreement, with
Croat and Muslim forces routing the Bosnian Serbs.
Tensions in and around Banja Luka remain high and military commanders have no
illusions about the difficulty of their task.
Bosnia is being divided into three sectors - British, American and French - for
the 60,000-strong Nato peace implementation force.
The overall operation will be run on the ground by the British-led HQ of Nato's
Allied Rapid Reaction Corps (ARRC) commanded by Lieutenant General Sir Michael
Walker.
Defence Secretary Michael Portillo said Britain's contribution would amount to
13,000 troops plus the 3000 Royal Navy and RAF forces already in         the
region.
</TEXT>
