<HEADLINE>The Higher Road to College</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Dick Louden</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>education</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159354</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
At the moment
it's voluntary.
But what if the
use of college
facilities for
school pupils
comes under
new financial
pressures?
Dick Louden
examines the
implications of
a forthcoming
report on the
`overlap' question
THE Scottish Office is funding a new research project to analyse the costs of
post-16 provision in schools and further education colleges. In financial terms
it is scarcely a major investment - the contract for #45,000 has been awarded
to KPMG Management Consulting and it is due for completion by the end of next
month - but there are already suspicions about how the information gleaned from
the project will be used.
Raymond Robertson, the Scottish Office Minister for Education, says the
objectives of the study are ``to compare the costs of comparable provision for
16-to 19-year-olds and to identify and explore the factors which may account
for differences within and between the sectors''.
He links the study to the implementation of Higher Still in 1998, saying that
``we are moving towards closer integration of the academic and vocational
strands and there is a need to look at the increasing overlap of provision in
the two sectors''.
There is nothing new in the linkage between the sectors. As long ago as 1963
the Scottish Office, in its document Half Our Future, suggested that ``there
could be a positive advantage, where conditions and facilities are suitable,
for some pupils in attending a college of further education for some part of
their course and thereby having a ready-made link with the future''.
Similar statements have been made over the years in other official publications
up to, and including, Higher Still. What is different is the new emphasis on
comparative costs.
This is sure to concern many schools. The experience gleaned from the current
Government is that, when it initiates financial studies, it uses the findings
to achieve cost-cutting measures.
Even at this early stage, it may not be too fanciful to suppose that, in the
wake of the KPMG report, the Scottish Office may exhort wider use by schools of
college facilities and expertise. This already happens, but on a voluntary
basis. It will not be welcomed if pressure is universally applied.
Recent events south of the Border are being observed with great wariness. As
colleges there feel ever tighter financial pressures, they have launched into
the business of recruiting new students under a funding formula which rewards
them for higher numbers.
Schools have become so alarmed that the Secondary Heads' Association has issued
a code of practice designed to control over-zealous marketing. Among other
things, it stipulates that publicity should not criticise other institutions,
that highly selective or misleading quotations from inspection reports should
not be used, and that the careers service should be enabled to offer balanced
and accurate advice. Last year English colleges increased their numbers 7% and
this year they are being asked to achieve further growth of 6%.
In Scotland there has been a history of closer co-operation, with schools and
colleges often entering into ``consortium'' arrangements and small schools in
particular finding real benefit in harnessing the expertise of local colleges.
Higher Still envisages the expansion of such links; but will it happen?
Running parallel to major educational changes are political trends which on the
whole promote competition rather than co-operation. Colleges are now
free-standing and schools have entered the era of devolved school management.
These developments may not favour closer working relationships. Indeed, some
schools are already suspicious of initiatives which they see as designed to
increase the number of pupils enrolling in colleges rather than staying on for
a further year.
Such initiatives include the appointment by colleges of marketing officers and
the use of press, radio and TV advertising campaigns to promote college
recruitment.
The impact of the loss of pupils at fifth and sixth years could be to undermine
the viability of courses currently on offer. In turn, this would be certain to
affect the curriculum further down the school, since it would be unreasonable
to invite pupils to embark on courses in third and fourth years if such courses
could not be continued thereafter.
In addition, the structure of DSM means that any loss of pupils to colleges
would result in a reduction in resources, since funding follows the pupils.
Already there is animated debate over the breadth of curriculum which any
school should be in a position to offer under Higher Still. Some schools will
not be able to create viable groupings in some of the new cognate areas like
travel and tourism, care, and construction. It seems likely that colleges could
become directly involved in the provision. This could, in some cases, even take
the form of franchising. In the Midlands and North of England some franchising
arrangements are already in place.
The valuable contribution which colleges can make, in collaboration with
schools, is not in question. Most people would accept that increased
co-operation between the sectors in the wake of Higher Still is perfectly
natural and healthy. For example, in the last few years, the development of
National Certificate clusters and group awards like General Scottish Vocational
Qualifications has brought schools and colleges closer and given schools access
to both the skills of college lecturers and the use of specialised equipment.
If Higher Still is to be the catalyst for closer interaction between the two
sectors, joint planning mechanisms will need to be set up to ensure that staff
collaborate in the design of courses and assessments and that more refined
guidance systems are designed to assist students to select suitable pathways
through the complex range of courses available.
If such an infrastructure is established and cross-sector co-operation is
allowed to blossom naturally, the aims of Higher Still could be advanced. If
financial resources take over, it will be quite another matter. Already some
headteachers are apprehensive that present arrangements - whereby pupils can
join college classes free of charge - may be under threat.
A national research project to analyse comparative costs will do little for
their peace of mind. They may yet feel that the concept of flexibility, so
intrinsic to everything that Higher Still stands for, is not meant to apply to
them.
</TEXT>
