<TEXT>
NOTHING better illustrates our confusion over manners, these days, than that
historic but selectively candid interview last week. In the done thing context
it raises two questions: at what point does frankness about intimacy on
peaktime television become bad form? And, are those who settle themselves into
the lucrative role of critics too often the merchants of cheap sneers?
We used to believe that it was only Americans who possessed no social
reticence, their noisy frankness in personal matters making Europeans, with
their complex discretion, seem emotionally retarded, even shifty in the panting
skill of Telling All. But the fact is that in Britain today the Royal Saga of
Splitsville has created the age of staged confessions, a shrewd and not
unstylish trick whereby the figures in question, by announcing their own
frailties, aim to blunt the razor of other people's hostile disclosures.
The justification, of course, is that once one side has reneged on joint
custody of a secret, the other side has the right to do the same. Such is the
modern view of equality, but in strict etiquette terms a secret is a secret
between two people only, and whoever breaks it is tarnished with dishonour. As
for critics, the worst operate from a hidden agenda, outwardly livid at
``manipulative disclosure'' but earning fat cheques from stoking prurient
furies, all the same.
But if anything did for good manners it was national hypocrisy, and today our
relish of scandals is the revenge of those who know now that they were being
conned. It is the relish of seeing someone ``up there'' who has been caught
out. As a result, short of flossing your gnashers at the table, there is not
much these days which is howled down as a preposterous breach of courtesy.
Cut-and-dried rules on correct behaviour died with the overthrow of debutantes
and calling cards, and the gliding servility of ``may I replenish the teapot,
Milady?'' Today if a man holds a door open for a womam, it is either because
she is his mother, or he is a bellhop with an upturned hand.
But the everyday decline in social graces is not the fault of one sex more than
the other. Men have been thrown off balance in their attitudes to women because
of certain loud-mouthed female chauvinists who always choose to confuse
civility with condescension. In fact, anyone who tells you good manners are
automatically sexist and psychologically crippling is very often nothing but an
absolute swine.
So, just what are the concerns of contemporary politesse? Well, in an age when
even bureaucracy's literature refers to partner rather than spouse, no-one need
agonise any longer over the correct wording for a wedding invitation. Indeed,
in the pages of the more authoritative etiquette books, the most pressing
dilemma will go something like this; Question: Should a woman carry a
toothbrush on a first date? Answer: Only discreetly.
Out in the business world, however, protocol is still uncharted territory for
women, and even the most talented among them are sometimes unsure about the
club rules of corporate behaviour. Should women remain seated when male
colleagues leap to their feet when the chairman enters the room?
The simplest solution seems to be to rise with the rest of them. Indeed, this
is not so much reversed gallantry as strategical: the woman board director who
remains demurely in her chair at the conference table will probably be mistaken
by the chairman for the person taking that meeting's minutes, which then means
she will also be the one expected to pour the coffee.
Curiously protocol is actually far higher up the worry list in America than it
is in today's spivvy Britain. There the searching issue of the moment revolves
around: what to do when someone is askew? Advice and correspondence columns of
magazines and newspapers tremble with anxiety for the woman with lipstick on
her teeth and, worse still, for the man with the unzipped zipper. Do men tell
men? Or, more challengingly, do women tell men?
The general consensus is that friends will gently alert each other when they
observe smudged cosmetics, an open fly, or a squidge of spinach locked
resolutely on to the front tooth. Acquaintances, although they might not feel
the same obligation, will probably do the same, but enemies will calculate
which action will cause the most chagrin: telling or not telling. And really
malicious folk, the ones much practised in cruelty, will lean forward and
ostentatiously correct the victim's wretched little handicap themselves.
</TEXT>
