<HEADLINE>Cosla sets terms for teamwork with Tories</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159356</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Convention of Scottish Local Authorities yesterday published its own terms
for establishing a new partnership between central and local government.
Council leaders acted in advance of the much-publicised speech on the future
government of Scotland, due to be delivered by Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth in Glasgow on Thursday.
Labour-lead Cosla claimed the past 20 years under the Tories had been a history
of ``continuous tinkering coupled with the centralisation of power''.
The outcome had been a relationship defined exclusively by central Government
rather than a relationship based on partnership, it said.
The convention, in a written statement, said there must be agreement on where
the boundaries of central and local government begin and end.
Within the overall framework established by central Government, councils should
have the freedom to decide on their own internal structures, operation and
service delivery arrangements, it says.
On this basis, the recent attacks by Government Ministers on the committee
structures of some of the new councils, and the number of officials they are
employing, were not only inaccurate but also unjustified.
``Who is best placed to decide how many committees or officers a council needs,
the Scottish Office or local councils?'' asks Cosla.
``To whom should a council be accountable for the decisions it makes about its
committee or management structures - its own community through the ballot box
or the Scottish Office?''
It says that finance was at the root of most of the difficulties which now
bedevil the relationship between central and local government.
Councils must be allowed to raise more than 51% of their revenue locally,
compared with the present 15%, to encourage citizens to understand that their
votes are critical in determining the spending decisions of their council.
To try to achieve this aim, the Government should set up an independent
commission to review the financing of local government in Scotland, says Cosla.
Cosla also calls for a period of stability in the relationship between central
and local government to give the new organisational structures of the unitary
councils the chance to bed down.
</TEXT>
