<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>City counting on rate cut</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975159357</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST night the City was backing its hunch that Chancellor of the Exchequer
Kenneth Clarke will introduce a fiscally sound Budget this afternoon with
reductions in planned Government spending and extra indirect taxes largely
offsetting cuts in income and capital taxes, worth a few billion pounds.
Gilts and equities were in record-breaking territory yesterday as the City
sensed that the Budget would be tight enough to please financial markets and
permit a half-point cut in interest rates before Christmas. The FTSE-100 Share
index jumped 25 points to close at a record 3649.0.
Sterling scored good gains against the mark amid mounting speculation that the
Bundesbank would deliver a cut in German rates this week. Its trade weighted
index added 0.2 to 83.2, well clear of last week's low of 82.5.
For the financial markets the key figure in the Budget will be the size of next
year's Public Sector Borrowing Requirement. The City knows this year's PSBR
will be substantially higher than the Treasury's estimate a year ago of #21.5bn
and is reconciled to it being revised upwards to around #28bn.
The economy has slowed down and tax takes have lagged behind the original
estimates, but Government spending has been tightly controlled. That much is
history. Had this year's public finances turned out in the way the Treasury
forecast, the PSBR would be dropping to around 3% of gross domestic product,
the target enshrined in the Maastricht Treaty. The outcome is likely to be
closer to 4%.
In his last Budget the Chancellor of the Exchequer forecast a PSBR for 1996-7
of #13bn, equal to 1.75% of GDP, but in the summer this was revised up to
#16bn. No-one expects him to match either of these figures this time round. The
consensus in the City is for a PSBR of around #20bn. More optimistic
projections at James Capel suggest #18bn.
A figure of #20bn or less would result in next year's PSBR falling below the
psychologically important 3% mark and indicate that Mr Clarke's fiscal strategy
was back on course to deliver a continuing decline in public borrowing, albeit
a little behind schedule.
But if the City thinks the Chancellor's tax cuts are being financed out of
public borrowing the gilts market would be likely to take the strain and with
it sterling. A cut in rates would become much more problematic. Mr Clarke
cannot afford renewed weakness in the pound, which would threaten a further
deterioration in the nation's inflation profile, or a hostile gilts market
which would raise the Government's borrowing costs.
The Budget will also contain the Government's economic forecasts upon which
most of the spending and revenue projections are based. A year ago the
Chancellor thought the economy would grow 3.25% this year, but activity has
slowed down much more than the Treasury mandarins anticipated. James Capel is
forecasting 2.5% growth in GDP this year, but it could easily be less.
Capel economists expect the Treasury to stick with its forecast of underlying
inflation of 2.5% in the final quarter of next year, in line with the
Government's own target. Activity will be sluggish in the first half of next
year, but should pick up later on. Capel's Adam Cole expects GDP growth of 2.5%
in 1996, perhaps even 2.75%.
The award-winning economics team at investment bank Goldman Sachs are much more
pessimistic. They expect the economy to slow down to a snail's pace in the next
two quarters as companies work their way through the stock overhang. A pick-up
is envisaged in the second half of next year, but overall David Walton and
Martin Brookes are forecasting below trend growth of just 1.75% next year.
Because of this they have become increasingly confident that the Government
will meet its inflation target. ``We are now leaning strongly to the view that
base rates could be cut by up to 1% over the next six to nine months,'' they
said. The Goldman Sachs team also sees scope for tax cuts of #4000m to #5000m
in the Budget, a bit more than the City consensus and well above its own
earlier forecast.
If the City considers that Mr Clarke has been too optimistic about the
prospects for growth then it would be wary of the Treasury's PSBR forecasts.
Another shortfall in revenues due to lower than expected growth could play
havoc with the projections.
One aid the Chancellor has in pruning public spending is the contingency
reserve. Next year's reserve was fixed at #6000m, and there is a widespread
expectation that he can safely reduce this to #3000m, in line with the figure
fixed for the current year. But the City will want to see evidence of real cuts
in planned public spending before it will be convinced the Budget arithmetic
adds up.
The Chancellor and the Governor of the Bank of England next meet on December 13
to decide monetary policy. If the Budget is well received by the financial
markets, the betting is that Mr Clarke will talk Eddie George into a rate cut
and justify it with the growing indications that the economy has slowed down to
below its trend rate of growth of 2.25% per annum.
In Germany inflation is below 2% and continuing to fall. The money supply poses
no inflationary threats and the economy has slowed down sharply. All of this
suggests that the Bundesbank will oblige the rest of the world with a
half-point cut in its discount rate to 3% when its council meets on Thursday.
This would make it much easier for Mr Clarke to force through a rate cut
without damaging sterling's long-term prospects. There is also a lot of clever
money backing the US Federal Reserve to trim short-term money market rates by a
quarter point after the FOMC meeting on December 19.
But Kenneth Clarke needs to turn in a convincing performance today before he
can hope to exploit the apparent trend towards lower rates on both sides of the
Atlantic. He has a much wider constituency to satisfy than the army of
backbenchers behind him hungry for a tax-cutting bonanza.
</TEXT>
