<HEADLINE>Companies join forces to combat business crimes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159358</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BID to bring together efforts by Scottish businesses to beat crime was
launched yesterday.
The planned business-crime centre will provide security advice and training
across the entire spectrum, from tiny firms to large corporations.
It has the support of CBI Scotland, the Scottish clearing banks, police forces,
local authorities, and the Government.
Launching the scheme, Home Affairs Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton said
there were 35,000 break-ins at non-domestic premises every year and small
businesses alone lost #1m a week as a result of crime.
``Crime against business affects everyone in Scotland, because we all have a
stake in the well-being of commercial enterprise. It threatens jobs because it
reduces profits and increases prices for the law-abiding majority in the
community,'' he said.
The proposed centre will deal with all aspects of crime, from shoplifting,
staff theft, and fraud to fire raising, violence, and break-ins.
The idea came from an action group set up by the Scottish Crime Prevention
Council. The Scottish Office will share the #100,000 annual running cost with
industry.
``We intend it to be a centre for excellence at the forefront of thinking on
crime prevention, geared up to communicate knowledge to businesses, support
organisations, and others who need it. Information on best practice will be
delivered through a helpline service, briefing sessions, and training
courses,'' Lord James said.
It was supported yesterday by a crime victim, Mr John Russell, chairman of John
G Russell Transport, a member of the action group and CBI Scotland
representative on the council.
His firm had a #250,000 shipment of whisky stolen earlier this year. It was
recovered. He said police were extremely helpful but could not recommend
specific equipment and sales people were only interested in selling their own
products.
The centre will also draw on the successful experience of the Gyle Shopping
Centre in Edinburgh. Since opening in October 1993, it has had 18 million
visitors but only 438 recorded crimes, the result of successful partnerships
between retailers, local authorities, and police.
Similarly, effective security measures by Scottish banks, like the use of red
dye on notes, have cut armed robberies from a peak of 84 in 1992 to just six in
the first half of this year.
Mr Mike Todd, of the Bank of Scotland, who represented the Scottish clearing
banks on the action group, said: ``When we started off, we found there were a
lot of good ideas and individual initiatives but no forum to make these
available to the wider business community. This is what the business crime
centre can achieve.'
</TEXT>
