<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In the belly of the crocodile</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE were in Vaasa, the largest town (55,000 population) in the main
Swedish-speaking province of Finland. Across the Gulf of Bothnia lay Sweden
itself. Here, reflecting the six centuries until 1809 during which the Swedish
crown controlled Finland, nearly a quarter of the province's 450,000 people
still claim Swedish as their native tongue.
The provincial governor, Tom Westergard, gave up his day to show us his
intriguing patch. He first took us to a local factory, where Wartsila Diesel
employs nearly 1300 people making medium-speed engines for marine propulsion
and power generation, mostly for export.
The diversified (and state-supported) local economy ranges from Wartsila's
heavy engineering to fur farming, carpet weaving, and the production of wooden
summer house kits. Yet provincial unemployment soared in the 1990s, in line
with the national Finnish trend, to a peak of 18%.
After a lunch of mushroom soup and white fish at a remote, windswept restaurant
on one of the islands in the archipelago, the governor took us, by coastguard
cutter, out into the gulf. Velvet scoters rose in flocks. A sea eagle quartered
the launch. Within half an hour we were halfway to Sweden. It's that close.
Back on dry land, we made our way to the offices of the local liberal Swedish
language newspaper, the Vasabladet, part-funded by the small Swedish People's
Party.
Given the unprecedented levels of unemployment across Finland in recent years,
the inevitable provincial suspicion of Helsinki as the main metropolitan
honeypot for investment, and Vaasa's minority Swedish cultural heritage, I
asked the editor-in-chief Dennis Rundt whether secessionist tendencies ever
broke surface in the province.
``No, absolutely not,'' he replied. ``We know too much about Sweden in this
part of Finland.'' In fact the Swedish People's Party, which has the allegiance
of around 85% of the native Swedish speakers in Finland, is part of the present
coalition government in Helsinki, boasting two Ministers from a parliamentary
group of just 11.
That left-led coalition is struggling with burgeoning state debt and the
consequences of a welfare system designed for the days when unemployment was
3%, not 18%. Back in Helsinki, Marja Kaisa Aula, a vice-chairman of the
opposition centre party, the KESK, which had been in continuous power for 40
years until 1987, was up to a familiar political ploy. She was accusing the
other side of pinching her party's policies.
The KESK's traditional coalition partners, the conservative KOK, are now in bed
with the Finnish Social Democratic Party and three smaller parties, including
the Swedish People's Party, in the present rainbow coalition which governs
Finland.
``When we were in government the SDP used to say: don't cut, spend more, to
cope with the recession,'' she recalled. ``It's interesting to see how rapidly
opinions can change. The general line of the Lipponen government now is not so
far away from what we were proposing in the election campaign, although they
are proposing to cut those with the weakest voices most.'' That will cause
particular problems in northern Finland, she warned. Needless to say Ms Aula's
centre party - with its agrarian traditions and, its opponents allege, an
attachment to farming subsidies surpassed only by the Swiss - is strongest in
north and central Finland.
I was reminded of these recent Nordic encounters when I heard Michael Forsyth,
at Scottish questions in the Commons last week, again lambasting proposals for
home rule here. He picked the recent referendum in Quebec as a lesson for us
all in Scotland. ``If you feed the crocodile,'' he warned MPs ``you end up
getting eaten.''
Apart from the fact that that analogy is a highly idiosyncratic reading of
Canada's complex confederal constitutional history, the Scottish Secretary's
choice of words, on the eve of his St Andrew's Day revelations, is instructive.
Any people's desire for a greater democratic say over the decisions which most
affect their lives is, Mr Forsyth appears to imply, as insatiable and
indiscriminate as a large reptile's appetite. And precisely who is that you,
the hapless victim who ends up in the beast's belly when all available food is
exhausted?
Maybe the Scottish Secretary was simply indulging in a bit of sensational
headline grabbing, coming up with a Jurassic Park reworking of the old slippery
slope argument about home rule. But, as the example of Finland's Vaasa
province, Catalonia in Spain and many other local situations testify, the slope
isn't always precipitous and the crocodile does sometimes learn fresh tricks.
The real danger lies in ignoring the legitimate appetite for home rule
altogether. Down that road lies a future where regional hostilities fester and
multiply. The Scots are feather-bedded subsidy junkies, claims one side.
Greater London and the South-east has its snout deepest in the trough, counters
the other. Down that road we all end up in the crocodile's belly.
In purely economic terms, Scotland's is now as diverse an economy as the UK as
a whole. For example, the Government's most recent detailed regional accounts,
for 1992, show that household disposable income per capita in Lothian (112.8 on
a scale which places the UK as a whole at 100) was almost on a par with Greater
London (113.7).
Tayside (106.5) and Grampian (106.4) outdid Oxfordshire (105) and Berkshire
(105.6). Borders (at 101.3) was doing nearly as well as Devon (102.3). It's
only when you get to Strathclyde (96.3) and Highlands and Islands (95.8) that
Scottish household disposable income per head falls well below the UK average.
But even at that level, they are in line with East Midlands (95.9) and ahead of
the Isle of Wight (94.5).
You wouldn't know that if your only diet was the yah-boo claim and counterclaim
of Scotland versus the rest. But to get beyond the sterility of Scotland versus
the rest we need a new focus. That focus, in my view, can come only from giving
Scots a greater measure of responsibility for their own future. If we did, I
suspect we might find that the crocodiles are outnumbered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cockerels' crowing is silenced in court</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DISTRICT court magistrate yesterday made a gagging order on a flock of noisy
cockerels whose crowing has driven neighbours to distraction.
The order on Royal Naval Commander Kenneth Ayres and his wife Julie followed a
rare legal move launched last week by the couple's neighbours, Michael and
Marie Bateman, who claimed the constant dawn-till-dusk din was ruining their
lives.
Dumbarton District Court Justice of the Peace Richard Dickson ruled that Mr and
Mrs Ayres, both 53, must:
q Get rid of three of their four cockerels.
q Contain the remaining one and any hens in a single flock.
q Lock them up in total darkness between dusk or 7pm (whichever is earlier) and
9am throughout the year.
q Build a new hen-house further away from the Batemans' home.
q Feed and water them in the one area, to encourage them to remain in that area.
q Erect an 8ft high fence around their entire back garden, with the top two
feet being angled at 45 degrees.
Mr Dickson ordered that the measures must be in place by Christmas Day and
added that getting rid of the three cockerels was not a destruction order.
Mrs Ayres shouted at Mr Dickson: ``I demand to know how you came to such a
harsh and unreasonable judgment. Do you hate cockerels?''
He replied: ``I considered all the evidence and I came to my findings on the
balance of probabilities. I reached my conclusion mainly on what I heard in
court and, to a lesser degree, on what I saw and heard when I visited the
properties.''
Outside the courtroom, Commander Ayres, who is based at the Clyde Submarine
Base at Faslane, said: ``This fence is going to turn our place into a
concentration camp. The judgment will severely restrict our personal freedom of
movement and our ability to enjoy our life.''
Mrs Ayres said: ``How do I possibly choose which cockerel to keep? I love them
all. If you had four children and were told to get rid of three, how would you
choose? I don't have children, my animals are my family.''
Mr Bateman, 67, a retired merchant navy captain, used to own and live in a
former farmhouse in secluded Glen Fruin, near Helensburgh, Dunbartonshire.
When his family grew up and moved out, he and his wife converted a barn into a
retirement cottage - and sold the main house three years ago to Mr Ayres. He
and his wife introduced a variety of farmyard poultry and fowls, including
several cockerels.
The Batemans claimed the birds have made their life a misery by screeching
every day of the year for an average of seven hours.
In an unusual move, Mr Dickson made the 30-mile round trip from Dumbarton to
Glen Fruin with Mr Bateman and Mr Ayres to see and hear the cockerels for
himself.
Mr Bateman raised the action under the Civic Government Act (Annoying Creatures
Provisions), which empowers the court to take any measure to curb the noise,
short of destroying the birds.
He said last night: ``We feel we were fully justified in bringing the action.
Our only reason for doing so was to establish our right to live in peace in our
own home.''
Asked what he intended to do with the three cockerels, Mr Ayres replied: ``Send
them in a box to Mr Bateman.''
He added: ``The magistrate expressed a wish last week that whatever judgment he
came to might mend any rift between neighbours. I would say the prospect of
that is now impossible.''
</TEXT>
