<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major and Bruton deadlocked</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER , Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159362</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Northern Ireland peace process stalled badly last night after Mr John Major
rejected a suggestion from Irish Prime Minister John Bruton that British
security forces' weapons should be treated in the same way as terrorist arms.
A 30-minute telephone conversation failed to agree a way forward which could
see the decommissioning of illegal arms and the start of talks between all the
province's political parties.
The main stumbling block was the terms of reference for an international
commission which would supervise the handing in of guns and bombs. Downing
Street said that it had been ``a useful discussion of issues'' and the leaders
had agreed to be in touch again ``in due course'' but declined to specify when.
The implication was that both Governments had run out of ideas for resolving
the deadlock.
Mr Bruton wanted the commission to be able to consider if Army and RUC weapons
should be scaled down as well as those held by the IRA and loyalist groups.
Mr Major sharply rejected the idea of ``equivalence'' between arms held by the
security forces and those held illegally, ready for use if terrorism breaks out
again.
The conversation killed hopes of a breakthrough before the arrival of President
Clinton in Britain tomorrow for talks at Downing Street before going on to tour
the province on Thursday and visit the Republic on Friday.
The Prime Ministers were unable to find a way round the decommissioning
problem. The British Government says that, once the commission is set up, Sinn
Fein could not be prevented from raising the question of security force arms.
However, Mr Major would not agree terms of reference for the commission which
could have given it the right to recommend reductions in the Army presence in
Northern Ireland and changes to policing arrangements. That, he said, was
entirely a matter for Westminster.
Downing Street sources insisted that the peace process has not broken down but
it seems clear that, unless President Clinton has a rabbit to pull out of the
hat, it is in trouble.
Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams argues that decommissioning should come after a
Northern Ireland settlement has been agreed, while the Unionist party leaders
have made it clear that they will not sit at the negotiating table until at
least some weaponry has been handed over.
Sinn Fein is making menacing noises about a resumption of violence unless talks
begin soon and, while the effects of a year of peace on their own supporters
may make them cautious about being the first to break the ceasefire, the
possibility cannot be ruled out.
The failure is a bitter disappointment for Mr Major, who last Friday seemed to
believe a deal could be struck. However, there was disappointment when Mr
Bruton's revised proposals were examined over the weekend.
His only concession was that setting up an elected assembly in the province
should be considered along with decommissioning and beginning preliminary talks
with all the political parties.
Glasgow Hillhead MP George Galloway was one of the signatories to a letter to
The Herald endorsing a Scottish Committee for Peace in Ireland demand that the
Prime Minister set a date for the start of all-party talks without precondition.
He said: ``We are on the brink of the whole Irish peace deal collapsing and I
can't undertand why the Prime Minister could let this pass. It could be his
crowning glory, but it has been sacrificed on the altar for a few Tory
backwoodsmen.''
Mr Galloway said that support for Mr Major's stance had waned. He added: ``The
bulldog mentality of digging your heels in at all costs is risking everything,
and more people are recognising that.''
</TEXT>
