<HEADLINE>London base for Delta</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE economy yesterday received a #20m boost with a decision by the world's
biggest airline, Delta, to base its European reservations sales centre in
London.
The move will create 200 new jobs and was praised by Industry and Energy
Minister Tim Eggar.
``This confirms Britain's position as the preferred location for international
investment,'' he said.
The new telephone centre brings together the American carrier's reservation
offices throughout Europe. It will be based at Park Royal in west London and
will open in the middle of January.
The centre will handle reservations and sales for 11 European countries. The
decision to locate in the UK follows months of work between the airline and
various British agencies including the Government-sponsored London First Centre.
John Cox, the centre's chief executive, said yesterday: ``London won because it
is the only European city able to offer Delta the skilled, flexible
multi-lingual workforce it requires.''
Delta's move follows that of another giant US carrier, American Airlines, which
last week decided to base its            European sales operation in Dublin.
n Deutsche Lufthansa yesterday announced flat earnings in the first nine months
of the year, saying costs resulting from the strength of the mark prevented it
from posting higher earnings.
Pre-tax profit before special items rose by DM4m or 0.8% to DM506m, the airline
said in a statement. It said the strong mark cost it DM440m in lost revenues
and writedowns.
``If the currency results had not spoiled our business performance, the higher
output we achieved would have been reflected in a super result,'' said
Lufthansa chief executive Juergen Weber.
Revenue rose by 4.7% to DM14.2bn despite the mark's strength.
Lufthansa's shares rose by 4% or DM7.50 to DM195 after the results were
announced, outpacing a 1.40% rise in the index of 30 leading German shares.
</TEXT>
