<HEADLINE>Banker has `no time' for devolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159364</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIR Bruce Pattullo, Governor of the Bank of Scotland, yesterday told business
leaders in Glasgow that he had ``no time whatsoever'' for devolution.
Expressing his personal views, rather than the bank's, at a members-only
meeting of Glasgow Chamber of Commerce, Sir Bruce said support for devolution
was primarily associated with a ``romantic notion''.
It would be an added complication and additional burden for Scottish business,
Sir Bruce said.
``My personal position about devolution is that I have no time for it
whatsoever.
``It will be an on-cost to all our businesses. There is no doubt it will raise
costs in due course.''
However, Mr George Robertson, the Shadow Scottish Secretary, dismissed the
outspoken views of Sir Bruce.
He said: ``I would not pretend for a minute that there are not individuals who
do not share our enthusiasm but the most important message from the Scottish
Chambers of Commerce survey, published last week, is that Scottish business is
no longer blindly accepting Tory scare stories.''
Sir Bruce, who steered a diplomatic line on devolution in the bank's latest
annual report, acknowledged that he had refrained from expressing his personal
point of view in public.
He told his audience: ``I think a number of business people, certainly
including myself, are reluctant to be seen to be taking too political a stance
because of what the opinion polls are showing.''
He said that what he thought, personally, was not important.
The Edinburgh-based Bank of Scotland has had discussions with Mr Robertson, who
has allayed one of its major fears by giving an assurance that there would be
no difference in the rates of corporation tax north and south of the Border, if
a Scottish parliament were established.
If Scotland had a higher rate of corporation tax, companies might move
operations south of the Border. A greater tax burden might also discourage
further inward investment.
Sir Bruce acknowledged that companies considered countries' corporation and
personal tax rates when making investment decisions. However, responding to a
question from the floor, he refused to comment on whether a higher rate of
income tax might discourage investment in Scotland.
The Scottish Constitutional Convention, of which Labour and the Liberal
Democrats are members, proposes a Scottish parliament with the power to levy
income tax at 3p in the pound above or below the UK rate.
Sir Bruce, who was knighted earlier this year, said the bank had received
``total confirmation'' from pro-devolution politicians that supervision of all
UK banks would remain the responsibility of the Bank of England.
It had also been assured that financial regulation generally would remain
unchanged.
He advised Scottish business leaders to raise their specific concerns with
those devising devolution proposals.
Touching on the bank's own talks with Labour, Sir Bruce said: ``I don't think
we fulfil our responsibility as business leaders if we don't think of how we
are going to cope past the next election.''
Sir Bruce said Labour needed to be specific about the powers of any Scottish
assembly and had to be strong enough to say what powers would be withheld from
it. The greater the uncertainty which could be removed, the less devolution
would be anathema to the financial markets.
</TEXT>
