<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ideas which make a difference</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159365</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DISPIRITED Santa us not an appealing festive idea. But it is tempting to
think that poor old St Nicholas, flying high through the skies with his
sleighful of goodies, must secretly bemoan the fact that a lot of the designer
label packages weighing down the reindeer contain nothing more exciting than a
utilitarian pair of socks, or some underwear.
The thrifty Scot must take a large part of the blame here. We generally tend to
play safe and buy something mainstream which we know the other person will
like. We really hate handing over hard-earned cash on anything less than a safe
bet. But isn't this the one time of the year to go that little bit extra and
buy something even slightly different? We don't need to throw common sense
completely out of the window, but let's live a little off the straight and
narrow for a change, and give Santa a break.
One of the more daring gift ideas is the helicopter trip, which is increasing
in popularity, and no wonder, for it can be a really exciting experience. The
transparent shell of the helicopter gives a bird's eye view of the landscape
below, and all sorts of services, from city tours to corporate hospitality
trips, can be fixed up.
For those who like the unexpected, the unpredictability of balloon trips is
ideal. These rely heavily on weather conditions, you can't choose where you
want to go but are mostly at the mercy of the wind direction. If you strike
lucky, a sunny afternoon or evening drifting high in the skye above the Clyde
Valley really is a gift to remember, especially if you can see your nearest and
dearest hairing around below in their cars, trying not to lose sight of the
balloon and wondering where it will finally choose to land. Then what better
way to finish the day than with a champagne toast to your first
lighter-than-air experience.
Or if you want to introduce an educational element, how about a first flying
lesson. But be warned. Only start this if you're sure you won't have to pay for
any further trips which might result from the passion you provoke.
For the less adventurous, splash out on a few drinks with a difference. If you
usually buy bottles of spirits for friends, instead of choosing their usual
brand, try going one over the eight. Take a look at liqueurs, for instance,
which are ofen temptingly packaged with chocolates to match. Cocktails have
become extremely fashionable, so if you know an enthusiastic host, a recipe
book and a bottle of one of the more unusual ingredients, such as blue curacao,
may go down well. There are also lots of eye-catching glasses made specially to
suit particular cocktails, as well as some of the new kinds of lagers and beers.
Alcohol in the very different forms of perfumes and aftershaves must be one the
most popular gifts, and along with makeup, accounts for a large porportion of
most people's present-buying budgets. This is one area where the otherwise
fairly run-of-the mill gift vouchers can really win. If you know someone who
could do with an expensive haircut, but who never seems to be able to find the
time to arrange one, give them a voucher for it. The thrift which often works
against us will come into play, and they'll make sure they don't let the
voucher lapse and miss the treat. The same goes for any other kind of beauty
treatment, such as facials or manicures. Most salons and beauty clinics also
have treatments suitable for men.
Children are generally easy to buy for at this time of the year, because
there's so much advertising on television and in the press that most can rhyme
off a 65-item list of essential gifts. Even it they're not interested in
clothes, toys and sweets still leave plenty of scope.
Animal magic seems to have entered the realms of gifts for little girls, with
one store offering a range of unusual rucksacks in the shape of furry cows,
pigs, rabbits and monkeys. There are purses to match, and although they don't
have a clip to fasten them to a waistband, they should be difficult to lose
simply because they are so large and eye-catching. There's also a range of bum
bags for lighter days.
Stephanie Davis
</TEXT>
