<DOCNO>GH951128-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call to cut drink-drive limi. Police plea to halve legal level as Christmas campaign begins</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Graph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159366</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE yesterday called for the legal drink-driving limit to be almost halved.
The move came at the official launch in Paisley of the Scottish forces' 10th
annual festive season campaign.
The move would cut the limit from 80 milligrammes of alcohol per 100
millilitres of blood to 50 milligrammes per 100 millilitres, the equivalent,
for a male of average weight and build, of consuming one pint of ordinary
lager, two glasses of wine, or one large whisky.
The reduction would be the first since breath tests were introduced in 1967 and
would be set at the minimum level which police estimate would allow for the
presence of alcohol through natural processes or because the driver had taken
medication.
In Scotland, 2250 people were killed or seriously injured as a result of
alcohol-related road accidents in the five-year period to 1993.
Proposing the change, Mr William Spence, traffic chairman of the Association of
Police Officers in Scotland (Apcos), said: ``Police see a clear link between
the consumption of alcohol by motorists, no matter how small a quantity, and
the greatly increased risk of becoming involved in an accident.''
He said Glasgow University research in 1994 showed that driver reactions were
impaired by up to 20% for two hours after drinking, even though their
bloodstream levels were below the current legal limit.
Mr Spence added: ``Even a small amount of alcohol can have a detrimental effect
on drivers and serves to re-inforce the clear policy of Scottish police that
drinking and driving do not mix and there is no such thing as a safe limit as
far as consuming alcohol is concerned.
``Apart from the saving of human misery and grief by reducing the death toll in
drink-related incidents, there is the considerable financial incentive, bearing
in mind that the overall average cost to the taxpayer of a fatal accident in
Scotland is in the region of #860,000.''
Mr Spence, who is also the Chief Constable of Tayside Police, recommended that
the reduced limit be introduced hand-in-hand with a programme to educate
motorists about the effects of alcohol on their driving ability.
However, Scottish Roads and Transport Minister Lord James Doulgas Hamilton, who
was present at the launch, said that although drink-driving legislation was
under review, the Government had no current plans to change the legal limit.
He added: ``The present limit is set at the level above which drivers' chances
of an accident rise significantly. Most of those convicted are found to be two
times the legal limit or above, so our priority is too enforce that.''
The Scottish Campaign against Irresponsible Drivers (Scid) welcomed the police
initiative but called for drink-driving limits to be enforced through the
random testing of motorists. Co-chairwoman Isobel Brydie said: ``The vast
majority of people now see drink driving as socially unacceptable and are aware
of its consequences. We are now down to the hard core of drinkers who are
prepared to take the risk of not being caught. With random testing, they might
think twice.''
Police announced the first results of their festive drink-drive campaign, which
began on Friday and will be one of the longest yet, lasting 41 days.
Since the first campaign in 1986, the proportion of drivers stopped who failed
or refused an alcohol test has fallen from 18.8% to 2.3% in 1995.
However, during the first weekend of this year's campaign, the number of drink
drivers in Scotland was 133, a slight rise on the same period last year.
Strathclyde police reported a ``disappointing'' rise from 42 negative or
refused tests in 1994, to 53 this year.
The theme of the 1995 crackdown, ``Don't Drive - Dial'', will be featured on
20,000 posters and seven million business-style cards distributed across
Scotland.
Backing the campaign, Formula One racing driver David Coulthard said: ``As a
racing driver, I am more than aware of the dangers of when my mind isn't fully
alert and working.
``Because of drink driving, I feel more at risk on the open road than in the
controlled environment of a race circuit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Likely lads boost Duffy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159367</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNDEE manager Jim Duffy last night urged his defeated Coca-Cola Cup finalists:
``Learn from Hampden, and you can be winners next time.'' Player-manager Duffy
was bitterly disappointed when his first cup final appearance at the age of 36
ended in a 2-0 defeat by Aberdeen on Sunday.
But Duffy was determined to dwell only on the positive side as he reflected on
the aftermath of Dundee's first major occasion in 15 years.
He said: ``One thing we can all focus on is the fact that Iain Anderson was
involved in a cup final at 18, and Jim Hamilton at 19. Neil McCann and Paul
Tosh were also there at an early age, and even Morten Wieghorst is only 24.
``There is no doubt in my mind that these players, and others, will take part
in occasions like that because they have many years ahead of them - and because
Sunday's disappointment does not hide the fact that they are good players.
``What they must make certain of is that Hampden really does become part of the
learning process for them. A similar thing happened to me when I was a young
Celtic player.
``I had been doing well in reserve games for a while, but the manager had not
seen me because he had been with the first team on match days.
``But I knew Billy McNeill was going to be at a midweek Glasgow Cup-tie, and I
knew his assistant, Frank Connor, had been telling him how well I'd been doing.
``I let nerves get to me because of all that, and I          was hopeless in
the match. I couldn't play at all and ended up getting a roasting from the
manager.
``From that day on I made sure nerves would never get to me again, and I hope
my young players will go the same way after what happened to them against
Aberdeen.
``If it works for them, they will certainly go into their next final - whether
they are with Dundee or somewhere else - with a far better chance of winning.''
In the build-up to Hampden, Duffy had been confident his youngsters would not
take stage fright, but he admitted: ``Everything was fine in our camp until two
o'clock.
``It was when our bus drove down towards Hampden through all our own fans that
it suddenly got to the players just what responsibility they were carrying.''
Dundee's next final appearance could be some time away, but Duffy knows the
next stage of their learning process comes against St Mirren at Love Street on
Saturday when they try to recapture their form in the first division promotion
race.
They will go top of they beat Saints and follow it up with another three points
against Dumbarton at Dens next Tuesday. Their manager intends to give them a
vote of confidence, but will have to leave the rest to them.
He said: ``I won't be pushing to bring in new players basically because those
already here have proved they have the talent and are good professionals.
``But going to Paisley will be another test for them because for the first time
in two weeks they are not going to be the centre of attention for Scottish
football.
``We had a televised derby against Dundee United followed by all the media
involvement surrounding the final against Aberdeen. It is important that we
cope with that because of what's at stake for the club.''
</TEXT>
