<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Where to find the feel-good factor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Eric Kennedy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>training &amp; development my job</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lynda Thomson's approach to stress is refreshingly different, says Eric Kennedy
IN these stressful days it's nice to meet someone with an alternative to
pill-popping. Aches and pains, whether physical or mental, are the speciality
of Lynda Thomson, and she has never given anyone a bottle of pills in her life.
Not that she would actively encourage people to give up painkillers. It's just
that she offers a different approach - via the increasingly popular method of
aromatherapy.
There is no doubt that large numbers of people are turning to alternative
methods of healing these days. Aromatherapy, or the use of essential oils and
massage in the treatment of the whole person as a unique individual, is one of
them.
These oils come from plants, leaves, petals, wood, bark and resins and are used
to treat a variety of ailments. These include headaches, rheumatism, arthritis,
anxiety, muscular and sinus problems, insomnia, depression, and migraine.
And Lynda, who works at the Health and Stress Clinic in Glasgow's Clarkston
Road, considers she is in a rewarding job, as she can see the difference they
make to her clients.
She wanted to be a TV make-up artist when she left Eastwood High in 1988 with
four 0-Grades. She went to Glasgow College of Commerce for a year to study
hairdressing, then to Clydebank College to do an HND in Beauty Therapy.
This was no lipstick-and-eyeshadow course: It involved the study of anatomy,
biology, chemistry, physics and psychology, as well as the practical aspects of
make-up, aromatherapy and reflexology.
Chemistry taught her about the ingredients of products, and biology about the
muscles, bones and skin. But it was aromatherapy which caught and held her
attention. It was based on methods thousands of years old and she knew it could
make a big difference to people's lives. After working in cosmetics for a time
she secured a job with the Health and Stress Clinic as an aromatherapist and
has since helped a wide variety of people, ranging in age from about 12 to 70.
Essential oils such as sandalwood, neroli and marjoram can have a powerful
effect on body and mind. These and other oils are made up of tiny molecules and
can penetrate as far as the bloodstream via massage. Other oils are highly
invigorating and the ``feel-good'' factor can be achieved through the use of
the proper substances in the proper way.
Lynda and the other staff can advise on this, after checking the patient's
medical records to ensure there is no blood-pressure or other problem. The oils
used at the clinic are undiluted and used with care. Some of them help
concentration, women's problems, and asthma.
Lynda has seen many people cut down on painkillers, sometimes abandoning them
completely, thanks to aromatherapy. The combination of essential oils and
massage makes use of two important senses - smell and touch - and she finds
that many cynics have been won over to it.
Lynda Thomson really enjoys her job. ``I like helping people,'' she says simply.
Courses for would-be aromatherapists and reflexologists are available at a
variety of colleges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000027</DOCNO>
