<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Faithful daughter of Mother Church</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Macleod</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159369</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE confessional state begins to reel. In 1937, assembling a new constitution
for the Irish Sovereign State, Eamonn de Valera not only inserted a specific
prohibition of divorce but confirmed the ``special position of the Holy
Catholic Apostolic and Roman Church as the guardian of the Faith professed by
the great majority of the citizens''.
The clause was dropped in 1972, as a sop to northern Unionists, but the reality
remained. The Irish had an establishment of religion, a national profession of
the Roman Church that the Italians deemed risible and the Spanish would have
thought distinctly over the top. To this day, the election of a Protestant MP
to the Dail is a novelty. Abortion is expressly outlawed in the constitution;
so - for the moment - is divorce.
It is typical of the fanaticism of a certain type of Roman Catholic that,
despite a recount confirming last week's referendum vote for divorce law
provision, legal challenges are to be mounted in the Dublin courts against the
reform. And it speaks volumes for Ireland's unique enthusiasm for Roman
Catholicism that the Pope himself took time out from being infallible to appeal
for a No vote in the referendum.
The Italians know how to keep him in his place. In Latin America, thousands are
deserting the old faith for evangelicalism. Ireland, poor and boggy as it is,
is by far the most faithful of all daughters of Mother Church.
The Roman Catholic Church runs most of Ireland's hospitals and virtually all
its teacher-training colleges. Over 90% of her citizens are Roman Catholic
adherents (a much higher proportion than at partition in 1922; but then,
hundreds of Protestants were bombed, burned, or frightened out of the Emerald
Isle). Such a position does not breed humility.
Only last week a bishop dramatically declared that Romanists who dared to
divorce or remarry, under reformed civil law, would not be entitled to the
sacraments of the Church. This must have given Father Brendan Smyth a good
laugh. Currently doing time in an Irish prison for multiple sex offences
against young boys, Smyth has not been excommunicated and still enjoys all
church privileges.
The trouble is that, in the Roman Church, marriage is exalted as a sacrament; a
holy and indissoluble bond, which cannot be broken without making a mockery of
the infallibility of the Church. Hence the traditional Roman solution to
marriage breakdown is not to sever the marital bond; it is the process of
annulment - to deny that a true marriage ever existed in the first place.
As all Roman sacraments are immensely complicated, it is remarkably easy to
annul a marriage, granted motivation. If the priest made one mistake; if one of
the partners subsequently admits to ``mental reservation'' - well, the thing
was void from the start, and the marriage never wrought in Heaven in the first
place.
The moral logic of this is odd. It declares the children of that annulled
marriage bastards and is a humiliation of the first order for a defending
party. Nevertheless, hundreds of Irish couples every year went by the annulment
road, for want of an alternative; under civil law in Ireland, this measure
meant nothing and, in strict letter, any subsequent marriages were bigamous.
But the state turned a blind eye. There were no prosecutions.
In typical ignorance, some officers of the American Christian right weighed in
to the Irish debate, lending funds and guidance to campaigners for a No vote.
In this they flew against common sense and reason - the intolerance of the
Irish divorce laws was a civil oppression on citizens not adhering to the Roman
Catholic faith and against Scripture itself. Divorce is an evil, but on
occasion a necessary one.
It is justified in a case of adultery, or desertion, and of brutality. The
victim of such outrage is the innocent party with an absolute right to divorce
from the covenant-breaking spouse, if only to safeguard her property rights or
physical safety. Even in Protestant circles, however, there is great debate
over this. Some evangelical sects, expecially those Dispensationalist bodies
who discount much of the Old Testament moral code, regard divorce as always and
absolutely wicked.
On the other hand, the Free Presbyterian Church of Scotland - at least in the
earlier part of this century - seems to have regarded the divorce of an
adulterous partner as obligatory. I know of two instances, many years ago, of
male members suspended from communion because they had refused to ``put away''
wives caught in open scandal.
Divorce is too readily confused with separation. No law of Church and State can
compel a man and woman to live together when their relationship has
irretrievably collapsed and domestic life reduced to bitterness, recrimination,
heartache, and malice. The provision of divorce law is to enable subsequent
remarriage, while guarding against frivolous quitting of a relationship that
may be salvageable, and protecting the interests of innocent parties.
The present state of divorce law in Britain is regrettable - the need to prove
fault has gone, and with it the necessary protection of an innocent party. How
many men have been abandoned by an unfaithful woman, who then sets up home with
a toy-boy and proceeds to sue the wretched husband for all he has built? But
some divorce law is essential and, in its absence, as in modern Ireland, great
evil results, especially to women trapped in brutal and improvident marriages.
From the confessional state to the confessional Princess. I hesitate to add to
acres of newsprint spent on the Princess of Wales and her slick, self-pitying,
maudlin soulbaring on television last week. Perhaps the most unpleasant aspect
of the performance was her utter disregard for the feelings of her sons, whom
she hauled into the tale of woe at every opportunity, if only to flaunt her
prime political card. But I will tell you this for nothing; I will not again
call her a fool. And it was not she, it appears, who was first unfaithful nor
she who first hit the screens to bare the secrets of her marriage to the nation.
In this I agree with her. She does not want a divorce and in that her instincts
are sound. While the royal marriage has collapsed beyond any hope of
reconciliation, neither of these two beauties is likely to want - or, indeed,
be able - to marry again. For good or ill, Chuck and Di are business-partners
for life. And with their several houses, complete with domestic staff and
multiple bedrooms, it is hard to see any serious hardship. The weans are packed
off to good rigorous schools, with nothing to fear save buggery: mum and dad
remain irredeemably famous, and they can always send notes through the servants.
</TEXT>
