<HEADLINE>Film game could reel in more jobs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159370</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND could be in line for new jobs thanks to a movie-based board game.
The Reel To Reel Picture Show, invented by Scots film buff Sandy Cherry, is
this year's Christmas craze in North America.
The games are pre-sently being manufactured in Toronto but Mr Cherry, 50, and
his son Martin, 27, want to produce them in their home town of Arbroath.
Martin Cherry said: ``We are struggling to keep up with demand and would love
to have some sort of production facility in Arbroath. We have already looked at
sites and hope we can create jobs for local people.''
The game, for adults and children, features more than 12,000 questions on 1000
cards covering subjects from the early days of cinema to the latest Hollywood
stars.
Players have to collect miniature film reels on their way round the board
before they can go for an Oscar and win the game.
</TEXT>
