<HEADLINE>Police put the finger on Turner</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159371</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE forensic experts have used fingerprint analysis to authenticate a
painting as the work of JMW Turner.
When the owners bought Landscape with a Rainbow it was coated in dirt.
Conservation work revealed faint traces of ink, apparently reading ``JM William
Turner'', on the back and the painting's style appeared to resemble Turner's.
However, the evidence was provided by a former supervisor of  the Royal
Canadian Mounted Police's fingerprint laboratory, and Mr John Manners of West
Yorkshire Police fingerprint department.
They compared a print on the work with another on a Turner in the Tate Gallery
and discovered they were identical. The painting goes on sale in London next
month and is expected to fetch up to #120,000.
</TEXT>
