<HEADLINE>Fears for 5000 jobs in fish industry row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159372</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH fish merchants are demanding that the Government steps in to ensure
they have continuity of supplies, warning of a jobs crisis because of the
catching sector.
They claim some fish quotas are already exhausted and say there has been ``bad
management'' by the producers' organisations.
They demanded that if the organisations cannot manage the situation, the
Government should take the responsibility away from them to safeguard 5000 jobs
in the North-east.
The catching sector retorted by saying that if the merchants stopped taking
``black fish'' - illegally caught over-quota fish - there would be no problem.
The row stepped up yesterday when some producers' organisations were stopped
from fishing for certain species, including cod, because they had caught their
annual quotas.
The merchants believe this action by the Government could be illegal and will
consider taking the issue to the European Court.
Mr Robert Milne, chief executive of the Scottish Fish Merchants' Federation
Ltd, said the situation was totally unacceptable: ``To be told in November that
some producers' organisations have exhausted their supplies of whiting, cod,
and saithe with four or five weeks to go cannot and will not be tolerated.''
He said the Government or EU would have to allow them to draw on some 1996
quota.
Mr Ian MacSween, chief executive of the Scottish Fishermen's Organisation Ltd,
blamed the situation on the merchants for being prepared to buy ``black fish''.
The Scottish Office Fisheries Minister, Mr Raymond Robertson, refused to be
drawn into the row, saying individual organisations had responsibility for
managing their own quotas.
</TEXT>
