<HEADLINE>People at risk told to get flu jabs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159373</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VULNERABLE Scots yesterday were urged to have their annual flu jab as fears
grew that England and Wales could soon face an epidemic of cases.
The advice came from Dr Iain Stewart, a consultant in public health medicine
for Greater Glasgow Health Board, who said vaccinations were important for the
elderly and those with chronic diseases.
Dr Stewart said there was no evidence of a Scottish epidemic, although a large
number of people had bad colds, flu-like illnesses, and gastric flu.
``We are not at a worrying level yet. But the worst time for real influenza is
mid-December, so time is running out for people who should have a jab.''
He said anyone suffering from a common cold should keep warm and drink plenty
of liquids. The doctor should be called only if a patient's temperature did not
stabilise after a few days, or if there was evidence of chest pains or
shortness of breath.
South of the Border, the Royal College of General Practitioners has reported a
sudden surge in flu cases, which last week reached 90 per 100,000 population.
The normal rate for this time of year is about 50.
Epidemic levels are not reached until 250 per 100,000 are ill with the virus.
