<HEADLINE>Greek premier's condition worsens</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN WEEKS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159375</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Athens
GREEK Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, in hospital with pneumonia, took a
turn for the worse today and his health problems spread to his kidneys, a
hospital spokesman said.
Papandreou, 76, who spent most of last week on a respirator, was hooked up to a
dialysis machine yesterday, government sources said.
They said it would take two to three hours to know how he was responding to the
dialysis, which takes over the function of the kidneys to remove impurities
from the blood.
A hospital spokesman told reporters Papandreou's condition had deteriorated in
the afternoon and his kidneys were affected.
``In the afternoon hours, the prime minister has shown a worsening in his
breathing, which has affected his kidneys,'' the spokesman said.
A succession of socialist ministers visited the hospital after the announcement
and were awaiting more news after Papandreou's doctors finish their
consultations.
Dozens of reporters have camped outside the Onassis Centre, near the Athenian
coast, for the past week since Papandreou was admitted to the intensive care
unit last Monday with pneumonia.
He was put on a respirator on Tuesday but his condition improved slowly and he
was taken off the machine last Friday.
Doctors expressed their first real optimism at the weekend and by this morning
were predicting that Papandreou could resume his full duties in time.
They reported that he was able to sit up over the weekend and talk to his wife,
Dimitra Liani-Papandreou, 40, who has been living at the hospital.
A team of 13 doctors has been attending Papandreou, who has appeared frail
since his Panhellenic Socialist Movement (Pasok) won elections in October 1993.
He has been unable to put in a full day's work and has kept his travel to a
minimum.
Two specialists from the United States and Switzerland were arrived at the
weekend to join the medical team.
Even before his condition worsened, it was clear Papandreou would play no role
in the final preparation of the 1996 budget and he would be unable to represent
Greece at the European Union summit in Madrid in December.--Reuter
</TEXT>
