<HEADLINE>Demonstration as headmaster returns to school</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159376</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANGRY mothers and fathers staged a demonstration yesterday as a headmaster went
back to school after being convicted of assaulting a pupil by gagging him with
sticky tape.
Parents and their children sealed off the two gates at the Falkirk school on
head teacher Alex Christie's first day back. Protesters brandished placards
saying ``Christie out'' and ``Christie is a criminal''.
However, the 47-year-old head teacher avoided a confrontation by slipping into
the school long before the parents arrived. He said later: ``It's good to be
back.''
Mr Christie said he was aware that there had been a ``small group of parents at
the gates'', adding: ``The janitor told me about it.''
He refused to comment further but, in a statement through his lawyers, said he
deeply regretted the incident and fully accepted that what he had done was
wrong. The statement added: ``He is grateful that he has been given the
opportunity to put this whole matter behind him.'' It said he was looking
forward to returning to the school, ``where he will continue to promote the
best interests of both the pupils and the school.
``He would like to thank his family, friends, and colleagues for the support
they have given him over the past nine months.''
Mr Christie was fined #350 at Falkirk Sheriff Court in June when he admitted
gagging a 10-year-old chatterbox boy in the classroom. He was later put on
probation by the General Teaching Council and last week education officials at
Central Regional Council found him guilty of ``gross misconduct''. However,
they let him keep his job.
Yesterday, one parent in the protest said: ``A lot of parents have put in to
have their children transferred from the school. The children don't want to go
back to school because of him. We don't see why our kids should have to move
school just because of him. He's the one who should go.''
The boy at the centre of the row was kept at home by his parents yesterday. His
mother, who cannot be named for legal reasons, said: ``I knew nothing about
this demonstration.''
However, she admitted she kept her son from school on Mr Christie's first day
back in charge after nine months' suspension on full pay.
q A lot of the boy's school friends got an unexpected day off. A power failure
hit the school's heating system, forcing the head teacher to bring in portable
heaters. Mr Christie admitted: ``It's still pretty cold in here. Some of the
children have been allowed to leave.''
</TEXT>
