<TEXT>
UPDATE
BLACKBURN pair Graeme Le Saux and David Batty were yesterday let off the hook
by UEFA after Italian referee Luigi Pairetto's official report. UEFA's observer
at the European Champions' League game against Spartak last Wednesday made only
a passing mention of it in his report. But UEFA disciplinary committee
spokesman Peter Limacher said: ``We will respect the referee's opinion that it
is not worthy of further action.
``The disagreement between the two players was mentioned by our delegate at the
match but we do not ask them to make recommendations.''
Blackburn confirmed that they have fined Le Saux and Batty for the incident and
hoped that it would close the door on the matter.
q.RANGERS, still savouring their victory over Hibernian at the weekend, are
looking forward to a double success in the capital when they travel to
Tynecastle on Saturday, writes Ken Gallacher.
And they look sure to move into that clash with Hearts with David Robertson,
Brian Laudrup, and Stuart McCall all fit again after having missed the match at
Easter Road.
Yesterday, manager Walter Smith still ruled out Ian Ferguson and Trevor Steven,
but said: ``Stuart McCall, who was injured, is likely to be okay again. And the
other two who missed out at Easter Road, Laudrup and Robertson, were out of
that game only because they needed to be spelled a little.
``They had both been out for a while, and then returned in major matches. It
was always going to be too much to ask them to play three games in six days.''
At Ibrox yesterday the club's former captain and manager, and now PRO, John
Greig, launched his video, and the producers announced that it was already set
to be one of the biggest sellers they had produced.
Advance orders have already hit 32,000 copies for the double issue production.
