<HEADLINE>Jardel centre of attention World stage before joining Rangers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159378</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE man Rangers hope to have a say in their future goal-scoring exploits early
in the New Year is preparing to take centre stage at the Olympic Stadium in
Tokyo today.
Jardel, of Brazilian side Gremio, lines up against Ajax of Amsterdam. And it is
no surprise that the Dutchmen are favourities to win the World Club Cup. They
are unbeaten in their previous 65 matches.
Jardel, whose club have agreed a #2.5m deal with Rangers, impressed Ibrox
manager Walter Smith when he watched him against Sao Paulo. He has plundered 45
goals so far this year in all competitions.
Now he should join Rangers within the next month or so and it looks certain
that work permit problems won't affect the giant striker, who apparently has
dual nationality, like so many of his countrymen.
Only last week, Porto played five Brazilians against the French champions
Nantes in the Champions' League. All of them had Portuguese passports, and if
that also applies to Jardel, as seems certain, then he is a Common Market
resident and can play in Scotland without a work permit being necessary.
Gremio, tough and physical, rely on high crosses to Jardel, who, with strike
partner Paulo Nunes, has unlocked a few defences with neat one-twos.
Only defender Arilson, goalkeeper Darnlei, and midfielder Dinho, have any
Brazil caps although right-back Francisco Arce and central defender Catalino
Rivarola have numerous caps for Paraguay.
But what about Ajax?
They won this battle between the European and South American champions in 1972,
and start as clear favourites against the Brazilians, who lifted the cup in
1983.
Ajax arrive with widespread praises ringing in their ears after their
outstanding 2-0 demolition of Real Madrid in the Champions' League last
Wednesday.
Real's manager Jorge Valdano said afterwards: ``Ajax are not just the team of
the 90s, they are approaching football's Utopia.
``Their concept of the game is exquisite, yet they have a physical superiority
as well. They are Beauty and the Beast.''
Only one player over the age of 25 - defender Danny Blind - is likely to play
for Ajax today, and their strike force, which has already scored 55 goals in
only 15 league games, could give the Brazilian defence a torrid time.
Ajax evoke memories of the Netherlands' ``total football'' philosophy of the
1970s, with attackers, midfielders, and defenders all ready to move into any
position, making runs and space for each other.
And with players like teenager Patrick Kluivert, who scored the European
Cup-winning goal against Milan, Marc Overmars, Nigerian Finidi George, and
lethal Finn Jari Litmanen spearheading the attack, Ajax can create and score
goals from anywhere.
There's also a different approach to this final from each team.
While Ajax have mixed light training with cultural visits in the Japanese
capital, Gremio have been moaning to the Brazilian press about Ajax having
better training facilities.
But that will not bother Louis Van Gaal's youngsters who have swept all before
them in Europe this season, culminating in their Champions' Cup victory over AC
Milan in Vienna in May.
Van Gaal has few injury worries, but the signs of a strenuous fixture-list are
beginning to tell on his relatively small squad, with international defender
Frank de Boer a doubt.
Van Gaal is aware that Gremio have a reputation as a tough, physical side, but
is not expected to change his team's style of play.
``We cannot afford to let them upset our rhythm. They are a tough side that
always attacks the opposition. They'll be very hard to break down,'' he said.
Gremio are not worried that Ajax are hot favourites. ``Barcelona and Milan also
turned their noses up at us, thinking they had everything won,'' Dinho said
referring to when he played for Sao Paulo.
Jardel said: ``You win football on the field.''
</TEXT>
