<HEADLINE>No cruise for Jodami</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159379</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RACING:
JODAMI, the 1993 Cheltenham Gold Cup winner, preserved his 100% record at Kelso
yesterday, when he landed the Hinchliffe Champion Chase, but it was no easy
victory for the 2-9 favourite.
It was Jodami's fourth visit to the Borders track, and his fourth success, but
Pink Gin, a 25-1 outsider, put in a tremendous challenge on the long, uphill
climb to the post and went down by only three-quarters of a length.
Patiently ridden in third place by Mark Dwyer, Jodami hit the front at the last
fence and appeared to be cruising to an easy victory until the last two hundred
yards.
Trainer Peter Beamont, who took Jodami out of Saturday's Hennessy Gold Cup in
favour of the Kelso race, admitted it had been ``a very close thing. It's a
long run to the line and he tends to idle when in front.''
Jodami will now probably go to Haydock for the Tommy Whittle Chase before
turning out on Boxing Day in the Rowland Meyrick at Wetherby.
Rocket Run (7-1) gave Lucinda Russell her fifth winner in her first season when
the former Welsh point-to-point champion was successful in the Jack Britton
Memorial Novices Chase.
Island Chief, the 1-3 favourite, held a commanding lead when he blundered and
fell at the fence in front of the stands on the second circuit.
Rocket Run, a #26,000 purchase by the trainer's father, Peter Russell, was left
in the lead and ran on well to beat Banntown Bill (9-1), trained by Martin Pipe
in Somerset.
The success ended a frustrating run without a winner for Russell, who trains at
Kinross. She is now in second place in The Herald Scottish Trainers'
Championship behind Peter Monteith, who leads on 12.
Penny-a-Day, the 1-5 favourite in the second division of the John Hogg Novices
Hurdle, made several mistakes and blundered badly at the last flight, but he
was still too fast for Supreme Soviet, who was beaten by seven lengths.
q MANDARINA had to settle for third place behind 226-10 outsider Passionnee and
Ludgate in the Prix Isola Bella at Saint Cloud yesterday.
Luca Cumani's filly attempted to make all, under Frankie Dettori, in the one
mile event, but was beaten a neck and half a length by the duo.
</TEXT>
