<HEADLINE>European Court of Human Rights faces Guinness affair showdown Judges reject plotters' appeal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159380</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Guinness affair is heading for a final showdown in the European Court of
Human Rights after a Court of Appeal ruled yesterday that Ernest Saunders and
his three co-defendants were rightly convicted five years ago of taking part in
an illegal share support operation.
Saunders has already won a preliminary decision from the Human Rights
Commission which states that the way the case was investigated deprived him of
fundamental safeguards against self-incrimination.
The former Guinness chairman confirmed after yesterday's crushing defeat that
the case would go to Strasbourg early next year ``where I am confident I will
obtain the fair hearing I seek''.
Heron International chief Gerald Ronson, stockbroker Anthony Parnes, and
management consultant Jack Lyons may follow suit if they fail to obtain
permission to take the case to the House of Lords.
The European court is to consider argument that Saunders was robbed of his
criminal law ``right to silence'' by being subjected to a ``draconian'' civil
law inquisition at the hands of Department of Trade and Industry inspectors
over a prolonged period before the police were finally brought in.
The inspectors can require suspects, on pain of sanctions including
imprisonment, to make potentially self-incriminating statements.
However, that argument found no favour with the Court of Appeal.
The three appeal judges, headed by the Lord Chief Justice, Lord Taylor, said
the UK Parliament had overriden such rights in the case of complex company
fraud and it was ``contrary to common sense'' to suggest that the prosecuting
authorities should not make proper use of the inspectors' investigative powers.
The judges said that, if Saunders won in the European Court, consideration
would have to be given to the effect of the decision in the UK. ``But our duty
at present is to apply our domestic law, which is unambiguous.''
The four men were convicted by an Old Bailey jury after a 112-day trial of
unlawfully creating a false market in Guinness shares during the company's
ultimately successful takeover battle with Argyll for the Scottish drinks group
Distillers.
Sir Jack Lyons was fined #3m and later stripped of his knighthood. He was the
only one of the four to gain anything out of yesterday's judgment - one of the
conspiracy convictions against him was quashed, entitling him to a #500,000
refund on his fine.
The other three defendants have served sentences at Ford open prison in Sussex.
Rejecting argument that the use of the DTI inspectors was unfair, the judges
said: ``The suggestion that these astute men, advised by experienced lawyers,
were, to use counsels' phrases, lulled into a false sense of security or
unaware of the peril of their position, is in our view fanciful.''
The court also dismissed a claim that the four were prejudiced by the
prosecution's non-disclosure of evidence which, it was argued, went to show
that what they did was not dishonest and was accepted City practice at the time.
At the end of their judgment, which took three hours to deliver, the judges
said: ``The combination of indemnities paid by Guinness to purchasers of its
own shares, the false invoices, the huge success fees, and the failure to
disclose either indemnities or success fees even to the Guinness board,
provided ample evidence of a dishonest scheme in which all the appellants
played their parts.
``In our view, the jury was well justified in finding them all to have acted
dishonestly.''
