<HEADLINE>Juppe faces new trade union strife</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN FOLLAIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159381</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
STRIKING railway workers crippled French train travel for the fourth day today
as Prime Minister Alain Juppe faced a new wave of stoppages over his austerity
plans.
Rail workers announced their strike, over restructuring and pension plans,
would go on into tomorrow after the failure of latest talks with the government.
Two big unions have also called a general strike for tomorrow over state
welfare reforms, while striking students demanding more funds for education
plan a protest on Thursday.
France's industrial turmoil was widely seen as the price the Juppe government
must pay for six months of reluctance to take sensitive decisions.
Rail workers' leaders said in meeting Labour Minister Jacques Barrot today they
had received no guarantee that pension schemes allowing them to retire early
would be safeguarded.
``Another meeting for nothing,'' said CFDT rail union leader Bruno Dalberto
after the talks.
Tomorrow, the state rail network SNCF is due to announce a carrot-and-stick
restructuring plan.
SNCF said the strike would halt all commuter trains in the Paris region and
severely disrupt traffic on high-speed main lines and regional services.
Only one in six main-line trains ran today.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
