<HEADLINE>Return visit of 11 Lewis chessmen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159382</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE 11 Lewis chess pieces in Scottish possession are expected to be shown in
Stornoway again next year.
At a meeting in Edinburgh yesterday, the trustees of the National Museums of
Scotland told a delegation from Western Isles Islands Council they intended to
make a further loan of the 11 pieces, which they own, to the new Western Isles
Museum in Lewis in 1996.
The likelihood of this happening was reported by The Herald on October 12. All
67 Lewis chess pieces, the British Museum owns the other 56, are on exhibition
at the Royal Scottish Museum until January 12.
At yesterday's meeting, which was described in a statement as ``very useful'',
the trustees said the initial loan of the chess pieces to the Western Isles
Museum during last summer had been a great success and they intended to build
on this positive outcome.
They intended to loan other archaeological pieces with Western Isles origins to
the Stornoway museum.
The arts and leisure committee of the islands council has said that the Lewis
chess pieces should be displayed permanently in the Western Isles.
The trustees of the British Museum are considering their attitude to their 56
pieces and have not reached a final decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
