<DOCNO>GH951128-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council bars bottled beer slot machines</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159384</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PLAN to dispense ``designer beers'' from vending machines in public bars was
rejected unanimously yesterday by Edinburgh District Council's licensing board.
Tennent Caledonian Breweries wanted to operate the scheme for a trial period in
four city centre pubs.
Branded products, such as Gold Bier, would be on sale in 33cl bottles. The
company claimed the idea was meant to reduce waiting time at bars and said the
machines were in operation in England.
Lothian and Borders Police said there had been no difficulties down south but
emphasised they were situated in member-only clubs, such as bingo clubs, which
operated an over-18 policy.
The police added that a machine dispensing bottled beer in a licensed disco in
Bathgate had to be removed because of under-age drinking and attempts to steal
money.
The Campaign for Real Ale also told the board the machines would be potential
trouble points which could reduce pubs to the      level of amusement arcades.
Mr Andrew Wilson, solicitor for the brewery, said it was prepared to instal the
machine in only one outlet for a trial period - La Belle Angele in the Cowgate.
Moving rejection, Councillor Michael Pringle, said that on a recent visit to
the Emergency Unit at the Royal Infirmary he had been told that admissions
could be reduced by 50% if bottle and glasses could be done away with.
Introducing these machines would be a ``retrograde step'' and he described the
idea as ``absolutely crazy'' and said it would lead to ``people wandering about
with bottles in their hands to use as weapons''.
</TEXT>
