<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McGraw back in the hot seat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159386</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORTON manager Allan McGraw surprised his players yesterday when he walked back
into Cappielow. But McGraw smiled and said: ``I`m fit and well. In fact, when I
went into the paper shop this morning on the way here, the assistant stared at
me. I said: `It's all right, I'm not a ghost.'''
McGraw was rushed to hospital on Saturday during the two-goal win over
Dunfermline complaining of chest pains. He remained in hospital until late
Sunday.
The Morton manager added: ``I must admit I thought I was having a heart attack,
and I am relieved the cardiograph readings have shown that was not the case.
The medical experts have also told me if I had been suffering from stress that
would have shown up as well. But there was no sign of that, and I know I am not
suffering from it.
``I had trouble with my stomach last week, and that's what it was.''
McGraw did not put in his usual long hours at the park yesterday, but his aim
is quickly to return to his normal work routine even though he will have
further tests carried out .
q.THE SFA will take another major step today to give the green light for TV
evidence to be heard in disciplinary cases.
The Executive Committee, headed by SFA president Bill Dickie, which decides on
major policy changes, will meet in Glasgow this morning.
And the committee will have in front of it a recommendation from the
Disciplinary Committee that the present policy should be altered.
The move for change was started two weeks ago by the premier division
representatives on the Scottish League Management Committee.
FOOTBALL ROUND-UP
</TEXT>
