<HEADLINE>Where women mean business</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Geraldine Abrahams</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>appointments and education</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159387</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Geraldine Abrahams looks at an innovative programme that offers new steps up
the ladder for middle-management females
DESPITE the fact that they make up more than half of the workforce in Scotland
today, research shows that women in industry receive less training and
development than their male counterparts.
While so much is written and discussed about the Glass Ceiling and how women
have great difficulty in reaching the higher echelons of senior management, the
problem is not isolated to that level alone.
When Motherwell District Council decided to support and jointly fund - with
Lanarkshire Development Agency - the ``Women Mean Business'' programme earlier
this year, it was clear from the start that it was aiming at a level which was
likely to be more effective in the local business environment.
``As a funder, the council believes it is important to create more women in
middle management as role models for the working women of the District,''
explains Maureen McConachie of Motherwell District Council's Business
Development Unit. ``And it's felt that this programme will achieve that in the
longer term. It adopts an innovative approach to developing women in the
workplace.''
The five-month-long programme was first developed by Yvonne Brown, projects
manager for Abrach Associates, in response to a request by Strathclyde Regional
Council to create a programme for women in business.
The pilot programme was run by the Gorbals Initiative and targeted local
companies. It was designed to develop the skills of key female members of staff
through projects which would relate to and benefit those companies.
Following its success, Yvonne Brown approached Motherwell District Council and
the programme was launched in March of this year and completed in August. A
third programme is already underway at East Kilbride.
Eleven women took part in the Motherwell programme, representing companies of
varying size, established and new, from the retailing, manufacturing and
service industries. Those companies participating in the programme were invited
to identify where development work in their organisation would make a
significant positive impact on performance - and to propose female staff
members with the greatest development potential to carry out a project, under
direct supervision.
``It was a question of matching my skills with those of the women involved to
produce something of value not only to them but to the companies for which they
work'' says Yvonne Brown. ``I worked on a one-to-one basis, setting tasks each
week, working towards an end-goal, and this was punctuated with workshops where
there was a sharing of information. At the end of the programme, the women all
produced written or verbal presentations.''
Apart from the obvious benefits to the companies in terms of the project work
tackled and their employees' improved performance, the personal development of
the women themselves has been most noticeable.
Jane Pow first heard about the Women Mean Business programme when the company
for which she works, BOC Gases, was approached and invited to become involved.
As an administrator, Jane's project was to expand the database on which she was
working, focusing on the medical sector, from which the company's draws its
most valueable customers.
These range from the manufacturing giants to small independent users. BOC Gases
is the leading supplier of medical gases to the NHS, pharmacists, the emergency
services, and domiciliary patients.
The project involved contacting 12 hospitals in Lanarkshire as well as some of
the larger Glasgow hospitals. While she had experience in compiling the
database, she had no face-to-face experience.
``By the time I had completed the exercise, I had conversed face-to-face for
half-an-hour with the chief pharmacists at 12 hospitals,'' she says. ``I took
along a questionnaire which I had compiled with Yvonne's help, and asked
questions that would indicate the levels of satisfaction of service from BOC
Gases.
``I also brought a contact sheet and various promotional/ information materials
from the company. There was plenty of feedback, most of it positive, and I took
my findings back to the company.''
Several meetings followed, at which she reported on her findings - and the
recommendations have since been implemented.
Jane was surprised and impressed with the results. She found, after two months,
that she was able to respond more quickly and efficiently and, as she gained
confidence and experience, became better prepared for each interview. She is
now more aware of what the company is about and feels she is a more valuable
member of staff as a result of her exercise.
Her employers have been delighted with the work she has done in gathering the
information and liaising with the clients - so much so that she received a #100
cheque as a reward for her excellent work on the report.
Jacqueline Brown is also an administrator, although with a much smaller
locally-based company - Uppermost Shoes of Motherwell which has 25 shops, a
number of which are franchised to former employees. She carries out
administration for all the shops in the group and compiles statistical reports
on sales for the company as a whole.
She decided to do her project on marketing since it was an area of which she
had no knowledge, but one which she felt would be relevant to the business. She
focused on three shops and, with Yvonne's help, made out customer survey
reports for each.
This was the first time she had actually worked at the front edge of the
business - where sales were carried out - and she had feedback which she
subsequently analysed.
Although she was apprehensive at first, her employer, Brian McKeown, was very
keen. ``We all get caught in the treadmill of doing our own jobs and very
seldom get the chance to do anything different,'' he says, ``so it was a great
opportunity for Jacqueline to become involved in a marketing exercise.
`It has broadened her whole perspective, increased her ability and confidence.
Jacqueline was a highly competent administrator anyway, but she didn't see the
sharp end of the business, the decision processes. This gave her the chance to
develop new skills.
``This has been good for the business and good for Jacqueline's own
self-esteem. When something new is introduced to the company, she is now
prepared to put forward ideas - that came directly from doing the report - and
has also managed to make sense of all the information stored on the computer,
understanding its implications.''
Both Motherwell District Council and Lanarkshire Development Agency have been
delighted with the positive response from the 11 locally-based companies. Andy
McNab, enterprise development manager, says: ``It is important that women are
encouraged to take up management positions within local businesses and we
believe that this programme, which we have funded with Motherwell District,
gives women excellent training and business assistance which will not only help
them further their own skills but also help the firms for which they work.''
</TEXT>
