<DOCNO>GH951128-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Valuing what we can measure, not measuring what we value</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN BOYD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>education</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159388</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONCE again the annual orgy of the publication of exam results has produced
acres of copy in all of the Scottish papers, tabloids as well as broadsheets.
Of course, The Herald tries to do things in a civilised way. It refuses to
order the schools into ``league tables'' and it makes sure that the comment
which accompanies the figures is balanced. The headteachers - usually of the
``successful'' schools - are quick to point to the deficiencies of the figures;
the ``experts'' remind us of the need to try to measure ``added value'' rather
than raw results; and we are reminded of the impact of socio-economic factors.
But, nevertheless, the figures invite conparision, and uninformed comparisons
in this case are certainly odious.
If these figures are geniunely part of the Scottish Office Education and
Industry Department's drive for a ``quality culture'' then surely they must,
above all else, avoid misleading the very public at whom they are aimed?
The Standard Grade examations have been with us for a decade and a half, and
the Government has spent considerable time and effort to educate the public
about the meanings of Foundation, General and Credit. What can be the possible
justification, therefore, for the press concentrating only on Grades 1-4? Do
grades 5 and 6 not matter? Is the impression to be given that they represent
``failure'' - a word we were told had disappeared from the examination
vocabulary at Standard Grade.
Theoretically, all young people are able to achieve at their own level. But, it
seems, some achievements are more valued than others. Indeed, this culture of
failure has permeated the way the young people themselves, and even some
teachers, view Standard Grade.
If achievement of a 5 or 6 does not even merit a mention in the press, will
``parity of esteem'' - the claim which underpins the Government's Higher Still
proposals - ever be anything other than a pipe dream? And it is not enough to
blame the press for this distortion. The very basis of the publication of these
results must be seriously questioned.
And what of the young people in many of our inner-city schools who, faced with
the prospect of unemployment, nevertheless complete their course work and turn
up for their Foundation and General examinations?
One school in Strathclyde, after a concerted push, halved the number of No
Awards at Standard Grade last year. Why doesn't that fact merit a mention?
Many such schools have introduced initiatives such s Supported Study to tackle
under-achievement, and yet none of these contextual factors appear. We seem
intent of valuing what we can measure rather than measuring what we value.
No-one doubts that exam results are important for pupils, and that for some
they may provide a passport for success in later life. But does success in
exams equal learning, and should we not be trying to reward a wide range of
achievements by young people in our schools?
Should it not be incumbent upon those who produce these figures to set them in
a context, to include factors which are known to influence examination results?
It is surely important for parents to know if they are comparing like with like
as they peruse these figures, if indeed that is what they do, in preparation
for the choice they will make of the school to which to send their children.
Many years ago when the-then Glasgow Herald ran its own version of exam league
tables, there appeared an article citing advice from a right-wing think-tank to
parents. They were advised to read the schools' handbooks and count the number
of times the word ``caring'' appeared - it would be in inverse proportion to
the academic excellence of the school! If we are not prepared to include
contextual factors, we may be in danger of giving credence to such a limited
view of schools.
If socio-economic status - or ``class'' - is a key determinant of success, as
the research in Scotland and in other parts of the world suggests, why is there
no indication in these figures of the balance of the schools' intake?
It can be done. Strathclyde Region has done it for a number of years now, and
there is evidence that south of the Border a similar approach is being
considered. Using this approach it is possible to predict, using indicators
such as free school meals, clothing grants and other factors, the likely
attainments of young people - and it can help determine if schools are
achieving more or less well than expected.
If the aim of publishing examination results is to help improve schools, then
surely an approach which leads to their conversion into league tables is not
the way to do it. Instead, we need to look at the factors which seem to be
associated with the progress that pupils make.
The things which schools do, day in and day out, to create an ethos of
achievement, to raise pupils' self-esteem, to challenge negative peer-group
pressure and to break the cycle of disadvantage should be published, celebrated
and made accessible to the public. The big stick of published examination
results will not, in itself, make schools better.
What is needed is a commitment from the Government to ensure that
accountability is a positive force, enabling schools to self-evaluate and to
learn from good practice elsewhere. Indeed, it is a tribute to schools and
local authorities that they have rejected the Government's competition message
and tried to use more sophisticated analyses of exam results to help them
improve practice at classroom level.
I remember being in a school in November, 1994, just after the publication of
results, when a pupil asked the headteacher in a corridor: ``Sir, is our school
rubbish?'' It certainly wasn't - but you couldn't have told that from its exam
results.
If we could agree nationally that the commitment to raising levels of
achievement should not be an ideological football, and that allegiance to the
market and competition needs to be balanced by investment in positive action
and collaborative approaches, then we might spare ourselves this annual flurry
and get on with the real task of promoting achievement for all.
q Dr Boyd is associate director of the Quality in Education research centre at
Strathclyde University, Glasgow.
Without contextual factors, exam tables are worthless, writes BRIAN BOYD
</TEXT>
