<HEADLINE>Caledonian Media plans a hi-tech network to rival BT</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159389</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CALEDONIAN Media Communications is buying equipment from Israel to set up a
hi-tech radio telephone network in Glasgow that will compete with British
Telecom.
The Aberdeen-based cable television and telecommunications company yesterday
signed a contract to buy #800,000 of equipment for setting up local transmitter
bases from Israel's Tadiran Communications.
Tadiran will also supply digital radio equipment for installation at client
sites for a guaranteed period of five years.
Chief executive Graham Duncan said a further contract for several million
pounds worth of telephone switching gear would be signed ``within a few
weeks'', but he declined to identify the supplier.
Caledonian has received several approaches from investors keen to buy into the
telecommunications venture, which will cost between #5m and #10m to set up. But
it is putting off talks with selected investors until the first quarter of 1996.
Last June Caledonian completed the #850,000 purchase of Atlantic
Telecommunications after that company gained a public telecommunications
licence for Strathclyde.
Caledonian plans to use this licence to set up a fixed-link radio telephone
network covering 1.3 million people in the greater Glasgow area early next
year. This will use radio links between client sites and a series of local
transmitter stations instead of fixed wires.
Caledonian's radio technology is based on systems designed for military use and
is much more secure than that used by mobile phones, which often suffer from
eavesdropping and interference.
``Our main targets are small and medium-sized businesses, but the network will
have domestic subscribers in it as well,'' Mr Duncan said.
Caledonian hopes the telecommunications venture will show a return within three
years, much less than the seven to nine-year period associated with its
investments in cable television in Aberdeen and Coventry.
Its telephones will be linked to a small flat aerial, the size of an A4 sheet
of paper. These will interface with a Caledonian local transmitter.
It plans to start pilot commissioning the system in the first quarter of next
year.
</TEXT>
