<DOCNO>GH951128-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Head acts to allay meningitis fears</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159390</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HEADTEACHER yesterday sought to allay the fears of concerned parents after a
15-year-old girl pupil at his school was found to have meningitis.
Mr George Bone, head of Marr College in Troon, wrote to the parents of almost
1500 pupils informing them of the details of the illness affecting the
teenager, whose condition is now stable and who is recovering at home.
He wrote that ``rumours had been spreading like wildfire'' since two other
pupils displayed symptoms associated with the infection. A hospital check-up
astablished that both had colds.
The original case has been diagnosed as meningococcal septicaemia which - while
common - can be serious and can in certain circumstances spread quickly through
the patient's peer group.
The fourth-year pupil was treated at Ayrshire Central Hospital and released
after a number of days to recuperate at home.
Symptoms of the infection include headaches, vomiting, stiff neck, tiredness,
irritability, and sensitivity to bright light.
Dr Paul McKee, public health consultant with Ayrshire and Arran Health Board,
said: ``I can confirm one case at Marr College. All the proper procedures have
been followed by the school in consultation with ourselves. There have been no
subsequent cases discovered.''
Mr Bone has told parents: ``I fully understand the anxiety shown by parents and
I wish to reassure all concerned that the situation is being monitored closely
and appropriate action will be taken as necessary.
``In the unlikely event of further developments, parents will be kept fully
informed.''
Mr Christopher Scott, 18, from Falkirk, a first-year student at Stirling
University, was still critically ill last night after contracting meningitis
last week.
</TEXT>
