<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why the milk round is no longer the way to the cream</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARAH URQUHART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>education</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159391</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the run-up to the festive season, many final-year students and recent
graduates have more on their minds than gift-filled stockings and Christmas
puddings. The search for a job when they finish their degree is now on. For
them it is also the season of careers fairs, the milk round and application
forms.
Although employment opportunities for graduate are beginning to improve after
five years of decline, there has been no return to the recruitment measures of
the late 1980s.
In the past, the milk round was the main source of graduate recruitment. This
was the annual autumn and spring tours by companies to campuses across the
country which focused on presentations outlining the opportunities they had.
During the rounds they also held interviews for potential employees.
But things are different now. The milk round is proving ideal for neither
employers nor students. The increase in the number of universities has meant
that the milk round has become time-consuming and expensive for employers.
Changes in course timetabling mean that it has also become inconvenient for
some students.
Jennifer Anderson, 22, graduated from Strathclyde University last summer.
During her final year she hardly had time to hunt for jobs. ``My dissertation
was due at the same time as the milk round was happening,'' she remembers. ``I
didn't have time to commit myself to filling out application forms properly.''
According to Lochart Madden at the careers service at Aberdeen University:
``Companies are active but in different ways.'' One of these ways is careers
fairs which have grown in prominence in recent years. At these events employers
hold stalls where students can come and get information on a wide range of
companies. They are also a way for employers to reach a vast number of students.
Barbara Graham is director of Strathclyde University's careers service, which
organises the annual Scottish Careers Fair. ``This fair is the only one in
Scotland open to all students, and employers have tended to be very helpful in
their response,'' she says.
Telecommunications giant AT&amp;T has been attending the Scottish Careers Fair for
many years. For the company, Alex Cowe says: ``Fairs are important as they
allow students to profile themselves and they give us the opportunity to catch
special people.''
One of the more popular stalls at this year's fair was the retailer Next. Its
graduate recruitment officer is 23-year-old Harry Harpur. He got his job
through a year's placement with the company, which he had to do as part of his
degree.
This is the first year that Next has gone to graduate fairs and it will be
attending five or six careers fairs throughout the UK. ``This is a brand new
approach,'' says Harry. ``Previously, as a desirable company, Next received
lots of speculative applications. We were not interested in that at all this
year.''
Scott Mathieson, 23, is a final year student at Glasgow University. ``The fair
has been very useful,'' he says. However, he isn't going to put all his eggs in
one basket. Aside from paying it a visit, he also plans to send off his CV to
many smaller companies not represented at the fair. His attitude is one that
Barbara Graham would like to cultivate among other job hunters. ``The
philosophy that tells graduates that they have to join a big corporation has
got to change.
``Smaller companies may only need a graduate once in a blue moon. Through
building links with them we can educate these employers so that when this
opportunity comes up, the first people they come to is us.''
Careers services are also training students to promote themselves more
effectively. At Aberdeen, Lochart Madden is working in a very different way
than three years ago. ``One of the things we now do is run workshops in areas
of common interest such as interview techniques.''
Alex Cowe has definitely noticed a change in student attitudes in recent times.
``They are much more focused in giving a quick precis of what they think you
need. It wasn't so in the past. They have obviously been well prepared by their
careers services.''
Carol Adam, 22, graduated from Strathclyde with a degree in Marketing and
Business Law last summer. She now works for PA Consulting Group in London as a
consultant analyst. ``I fancied consultancy work and thought I'd concentrate on
applying for work in that area first. I went to the careers office and they
helped me work out a strategy for finding a job.
``A lot of people think that they can't get a job without using the milk round.
I didn't use it at all.''
Times have changed, says student SARAH URQUHART (below).Now there are more ways
for graduate talent to be noticed than through big firms' annual campus tours
</TEXT>
