<HEADLINE>BTR hives off Tilcon to Minorco in #330m deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159392</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BTR is pulling out of UK aggregates with the sale of its Tilcon subsidiary to
mining finance house Minorco for #330m. The deal involves 180 sites around the
country, of which 45 are in the Scottish central belt, producing sand and
gravel, drystone, coated stone, mortar, ready mixed concrete and other quarry
products. The business employs 2300 people.
The deal reflects BTR's policy of concentrating on industrial manufacturing.
The proceeds will be used to reduce debt. In 1994, Tilcon made profits of #24m
and assets were worth #180m. It expects to earn #29m this year.
BTR chief executive Alan Jackson commented: ``We believe that the sale to
Minorco, an international natural resources group with operations in Europe,
North America and South America, will form a strong basis for the Tilcon
business going forward.''
The company operates mainly in the West Midlands, the north of England and
Scotland where, in each region, it is market leader. It produces 14.5 million
tonnes of aggregates annually and this will about double Minorco's existing UK
production capacity. There is little overlap with Minorco's existing operations
which consist of the Buxton Lime ``superquarry'' and the Nash Rocks quarry on
the Welsh border.
Minorco chief executive Hank Slack explained the company had been eyeing Tilcon
for some time in the context of expanding its European aggregates operation.
With purchases in Germany and Spain, it has now spent #640m in developing this
business to help offset the cyclical nature of other parts of the group.
The latest deal ``achieves our objective for expanding the division to an
appropriate size, given the current and planned developments within our mining
divisions,'' said Mr Slack.
Minorco remains on the lookout for further purchases, mainly in the countries
where it is already operating.
</TEXT>
