<HEADLINE>Dial M for mobile</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159393</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a business tool the mobile phone has long since proved its worth, no van
delivery business would be without one, and it is now perceived as more of an
essential than an expensive or unnecessary toy for the businessman. But the
swing has since moved from the business consumer to the private consumer
perhaps fuelled by lower tariffs and the vast range of choice and price of
mobiles available.
In an emergency a mobile phone could clearly be a lifesaver. In a less extreme
situation it could provide a vital link for help. And for the woman driver
whose car has broken down the mobile can be a comforting device as well as
providing assurance that isolation is likely to be short-lived.
Mobile phones are small and light enough to be carried in the pocket or
handbag. Most have a memory function where names and numbers can be programmed
into the phones. And many can scroll through the last 20 or so numbers dialled.
Other features include a timer funtion that lets you see precisely the number
of units you have used and a lock facility to prevent unauthorised users making
calls unless in an emergency 999 call.
Before you buy make sure you study the contract thoroughly and that you
understand the basis on which charging is made. The phone you buy may be cheap
but the calls you make could be expensive and you may also be tied into a
contract.
Basic points that are also worth considering before you go mobile are whether
the phone has a hands-free car kit available, clear audibility, good fringe
performance and good battery capacity.
</TEXT>
