<HEADLINE>Murals artist draws little response from city council</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159394</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU will recall the stooshie at the Glasgow concert hall when city boss Pat
Lally decided that the murals by Ian McCulloch should be removed.
McCulloch, just as cussed a bloke as Mr Lally, continues his rearguard action
to have his art restored to the concert hall walls.
Glasgow City Council has embarked on its Festival of Visual Arts '96 and
invited artists to apply for funding for works and events. Mr McCulloch thought
it would be entirely appropriate for the city to rescind Mr Lally's unilateral
consignment (or should that be consignation - so difficult this English
language) of his two huge paintings from the concert hall to a storeroom at the
Tramway gallery in the south side of the city.
Being used to municipal bureaucracy, Mr McCulloch submitted a proper prospectus
for his project detailing a budget of #450 to restore his paintings to the
locus as selected by the committee originally set up to choose the art for the
concert hall. This includes an element of refurbishment since the basic and
damp accommodation at the Tramway has not done the paintings much good in the
interim.
In his application, Mr McCulloch describes as the aim of his project: ``To
redress a brutal act of censorship and by so doing, go some way to re-establish
the good name of the City of Glasgow in cultural affairs.''
Despite the paltry sum of money involved, Mr McCulloch has not had a very
encouraging response to his application. This may or may not have anything to
do with the fact that, until April next year when a new unitary authority takes
over, Glasgow remains under the fiefdom of that well-known art critic and city
boss, Patrick J Lally.
Show of hands
LORD James Douglas-Hamilton, Scottish Office Minister in charge of crime, among
other duties, is renowned for the slow but sure delivery of his speeches.
Usually done with a finger following the text in the best traditions of a
primary three pupil in a reading test.
Thus it was that those in attendance at a Scottish Office ``Business Crime
Reduction Strategy Launch'' were issued with a speech by Lord James with
instructions to check against delivery. We will not tire you with the details
but the assembled journalists were surprised to read in the news release: ``We
will be engaging many more groups and individuals in carrying forward the
strategy. An important part of that process has been publication of the booklet
and leaflet which you will have found on your seats. These are Reducing
Business Crime (hold up booklet) and Reducing Crime in Your Business (hold up
leaflet).''
Lord James, being a member of the Faculty of Advocates, is fully trained in
following a brief. He managed nae bother to hold aloft both booklet and leaflet
as instructed by his Scottish Office minders.
Trial and error
READERS with extraordinarily long memories may recall a story we had about
Donald MacPherson, a cattle breeder of Appin, Argyll, who named one of his
prize beasts after Mark Walters of Rangers. Like the player, it was black, a
rare specimen, and won many prizes.
The MacPhersons have now entered a beast in this week's big cattle show at
Smithfield with an equally intriguing name. The coo (steer, heifer, bullock, or
whatever) is called OJ Simpson and has been so called because the owners hoped
it would be as successful as the American accused when it comes to swaying
judges.
Alas, OJ lost out yesterday in the heavyweight steer competition to another
Scottish beast called No-Kan-Do from Carnoustie.
Still, on the steer name front, at the Perth Winter Fair, a steer had a very
successful kick through the show-ring bars at the spectators. Its name, we are
told, was Eric Cantona.
No thanks
DEPT of We Think We Know What They Mean: A publication called Strathclyde
Insider has a recipe for marzipan delight. (Very Christmassy, dare we say it?)
It includes the instructions: ``Lift balls with cocktail stick and dip bottom
into white chocolate.'' Perhaps, we'll stick with the stilton.
q.In the same vein, we hear of instructions left for the cook at an outdoor
centre on the island of Arran: ``The vegetarian family won't eat fish or
anything that was alive except for the little girl.''
Paws for thought
IN the pets for sale column of the Dunfermline Press we find: ``Persian
Sealpoint, three years old, neutered Tom cat, with accessories......'' Surely a
contradiction in terms, here.
Survival course
A TALE of how tough it is these days for your average student to survive on the
meagre grants doled out by this Government. A young lad at Robert Gordon
University in Aberdeen managed to blow his grant within the first few weeks of
term. Recalling the traditional story of the Scots lad o' pairts who survived
at university on a sack of oatmeal from home, the student duly invested in a
large quantity of same.
Following the recipe, he made a large batch of porridge and left it to set in a
greaseproofed chest of drawers. He duly ate his way through this simple but
honest fare. We would like to tell you that this has a happy ending but the
word is that the lad now has scurvy.
</TEXT>
