<HEADLINE>Murdered Libyan knew of warning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159395</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLITICAL dissident from Libya found murdered in his shop in London had been
warned of a plot to kill him weeks before his death.
Police said Ali Mehmed Abuzeid, 54, suffered a number of stab wounds to the
upper body in his grocer's shop at the weekend.
Mr Abuzeid was a co-founder of the National Front for the Salvation of Libya,
one of the most influential groups opposed to Colonel Muammar Gaddafi.
In 1984, he helped launch a failed attack on Gaddafi's headquarters in Tripoli,
for which it is believed he was sentenced to death. He was imprisoned for 20
months in the 1970s.
The policeman leading the murder hunt, Detective Superintendent Dick Bell,
played down speculation about a Libyan hit squad. He said: ``I think it is
unlikely that a Libyan agent carried this out, although I cannot rule out a
political connection at this stage.
``I am aware from neighbours that Mr Abuzeid had gone to them saying he had
been threatened but exactly who by and what for I don't know.''
He said police were aware of Mr Abuzeid's connections with the Libyan
opposition but were keeping an open mind about the motive.
Mr Bell said a knife had been found but it had not yet been confirmed as the
murder weapon. It might simply be from the shop.
A shopowner two doors from Mr Abuzeid in Westbourne Grove, west London, said:
``Somebody had advised him to be careful and look out because someone was going
to kill him. He was confused.
``It was a friendly call, not a threat, but the caller did not say who he was.
He said: `I am doing you a favour because someone is coming to kill you'.''
Shopkeepers agreed Mr Abuzeid was a genial and hard-working family man and they
believed he had retired from active political life.
However, Mohammed Fayez Jibril, spokesman for the NFSL, said: ``There is
nothing that makes us doubt it is a political assassination. Gaddafi has a long
history of political assassinations. We are sure it is Gaddafi.''
</TEXT>
