<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Think before it's all over</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Black</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>training &amp; development</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159396</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Too soon after being over the moon, age can make footballers parrot-sick at the
prospect of no prospects. Ian Black meets a man with a mission to change that,
and a message for beginners......
TONY HIGGINS is a man with a mission. He is the secretary of the Scottish
Professional Footballers Association, and he has his mind set on training and
education. He says: ``People tend to forget that for every Tommy Burns or Paul
Sturrock, there are a hundred guys, a hundred ex-footballers, who are
struggling to find work, either inside or outside the game. Obviously I
wouldn't like to name names, but I know a lot of guys who have more or less
given up struggling.''
Tony, now 41, played full-time for 12 years and then went part-time to finish
his education, taking a diploma in Youth and Community Studies at Jordanhill.
He is unusual for a professional footballer in that he has Highers and had
considered several universities before choosing to try his luck as a player.
His mission, in his words, is ``to get players to start thinking as early as
possible about alternative careers. When you're 20 you don't think about being
35. You just think about being a player, but as players get older, into their
thirties, then they start to panic, trying to find a career or something in
life that will give them the status they had as a footballer.''
Changes within the game in the last two or three years have meant that many
clubs, even former full-time clubs in the First Division, are now offering
part-time contracts. This means having to think about a career even earlier,
because part-time money is anything from #20 up to a maximum of #100 per week
which, as Tony says, ``doesn't offer you a financial base on which to lead a
normal life''.
Six years ago Tony presented a paper to the Football League and the SFA and,
based on this, he set up the SFPA Educational Trust, which is funded by the
SFA, the Football League, and the Football Trust. The three of these contribute
a yearly sum which totals ``over five figures'', says Tony with some pride. It
is a pride edged with caution, however......
The income of the Football Trust has dropped, thanks to the National Lottery,
and his plans to appoint an Education Officer have had to be shelved -
temporarily, he hopes - as an agreement in principle has already been reached
with the various authorities.
He says: ``The game needs an education department but in the meantime it will
be necessary to have someone to go round to clubs talking to the players and
offering advice to them on a variety of subjects. I believe the ethos of
educating players as much as possible has to be established.''
He might have a bit of bother with the clubs, many of which still appear to
labour under the delusion that Scotland is still bursting at the seams with
raw, under-educated and exploitable talent slavering to play for pennies and
then be consigned to the graveyard of hopes that is being an ex-footballer with
no other skills. There are not many ex-footballers who can become professional
ex-footballers like George Best, and even fewer who go on to become managers,
though one of the liaisons that Tony has set up is with the HNC in Management
Studies at Caledonian University. Pat Bonner of Celtic and Fraser Wishart of
Hearts have already passed this course, so you can look out for them as
successful future managers, though not necessarily in football.
There are around 1000 professional players in Scotland and already over 100 of
them have availed themselves of the services of the Educational Trust.
Awareness is growing and the net of relationships and contacts that has been
set up is widening:  it currently includes courses in accountancy, chiropody
and languages, to name but a few.
The trust pays all fees for players under 21, and for older players they pay
two-thirds, Tony's argument being that if you've put some of your own money
into it then you're likely to appreciate it more and try harder.
Someone who spent 18 years of his life as a professional footballer is Roddy
Georgeson, now 47 and a senior development executive with Scottish Enterprise.
He has spent all his (outside football) working life involved in some branch of
training or other, starting with the DoE, then the Training Agency until the
merger with the SDA. He says: ``Never, not once, when I was playing did I
receive a single word of advice or caution about the future.
``Mind you, if I had, I probably wouldn't have listened. But it is important.''
Roddy also points out the importance of club involvement and the different
degrees of caring, even in clubs of the same city. ``When I went to Dundee
after my first two seasons at Port Vale I was 19. I was what you might call a
free spirit. There we were, four guys in a flat, no supervision, nothing. At
Dundee United, though, the guys were in a club hostel, encouraged to get into
other things.
``In those days, round about '68, there weren't even any tactics. You just
turned up on the day and checked if your name was on the team-sheet. The
manager would say, `This is an important one. Go out there and play your own
game', and that was it.''
Terry Christie, recently triumphant with Stenhousemuir, is the only manager he
ever worked with who taught him tactics. ``I now know where to stand at corners
and free kicks, thanks to Terry,'' laughs Roddy.
Roddy had four O-Levels when he left school but now has a diploma in Management
Studies. He was wiser than most in that he got a job at 21 and switched to
part-time football - though jobs were easier to find in 1970.
Tony has had discussions with Minister for Sport Iain Sproat regarding the
melding of sport and education - something not much practised in Scotland
though the subjects are regarded as indivisible in countries like Germany and
Sweden.
His latest initiative is a sort of Compleat Footballer, now compulsory for all
players under 21. It won't be the last.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000055</DOCNO>
