<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pain and strain mainly for gain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159397</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT the same time as one of football's most popular characters, Morton manager
Allan McGraw, has become the second team leader to be taken ill in the dug-out
this season, following Paul Sturrock's collapse earlier in the year, a new
study has discovered that players themselves suffer from relatively little
stress.
Perhaps that demonstrates that psychologists Dr Howard Khan, and Sarah Hurry of
Herriot Watt University, chose the wrong subjects for their survey, if they
were attempting to unearth some of the causes of sporting strain.
It seems from their findings, which were based on questions put to 512 players
in the premier and first divisions, that the modern Scottish footballer does
not get too uptight about anything.
There are minor pressures to get a good result, to please the fans, and to
avoid a ``bad press,'' but, in general, the lads appear to be a pretty
laid-back bunch.
This does not quite tie in with the characters who are literally sick with
nerves before matches, who stick by ludicrous superstitions before they tackle
any game, and who are so hyped up, they commit uncharacteristic assaults on
opponents before they settle down.
Nevertheless, the exceptions maybe prove the rule, and it hardly comes as a
surprise that in a team game, the pressures on individuals to succeed for their
own sake are not quite as ferocious as they are in sports where the players are
completely self dependent.
Golfers and tennis players survive entirely by their own efforts, which may
explain why it is becoming the custom to carry around a sports psychologist in
the kit-bag on both circuits.
There is another reason why the stresses and strains of modern football, or
rugby for that matter, may be not as demanding as, say, the golf tour.
Footballers and rugby men get the chance, once the game begins, to use real
physical exercise to release any pent-up emotions, unlike the golfer whose
tensions increase as the tournament progresses at a sedate pace.
It may also be why there is a contrast between footballers and managers in the
stress league.
Jock Stein died in Cardiff as Scottish fans and players were celebrating an
important international victory and, while there will be more detailed medical
language to explain his passing, we all are aware that he died because of
excessive demands.
At management level in professional football, the pressures are perhaps the
most immense and unfair in any walk of life. Few comparisons can be made with a
job which, by dint of its competitive nature, cannot be done perfectly by
anyone.
No team wins everything all the time and, therefore, every manager fails at
some time or another. The trick is not being sacked when your turn comes along.
This is the kind of pressure which becomes outrageous unless the manager is
blessed with financial security, a ridiculous ego, and a resilience that Arthur
Scargill would admire.
It does not apply only to those involved at the highest level. The two men who
have caused alarm throughout the game this season, Sturrock and McGraw, are
dealing in the first division where it is claimed there is not quite as much
strain, a claim that clearly does not bear examination.
Psychologically, many players' biggest worry would be how to spell it. Those
who worry and fret rarely reach the highest standard simply because their egos
are not armour plated and immune to self doubt.
Even those individuals, however, become different personalities if they go on
to management where they have to depend entirely on the talents of others.
Management, as it were, is a different ball game. Not one to envy, either.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
