<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prison policy should be about cutting crime, not the need for re-election. Here comes the judge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Freeman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159398</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tomorrow Judge Stephen Tumim visits Scotland. James Freeman considers his views
on penal reform
IN TERMS of the prisons debate in England there have been two ages - before
Judge Stephen Tumim and after him. Few ordinary folk outside politics or the
justice system south of the Border knew much about the state of their jails,
the odd riot apart, prior to Judge Tumim becoming chief inspector of prisons
and fewer gave a damn. That changed when the white-haired Crown Court Judge,
little known outside the rather elitist world of contemporary art in London,
entered the fray.
Quickly identified by the     serious media as a gift, he      embarked on an
eight-year career as a thorn in the side of a Government whose view of
imprisonment is clearly determined by one criterion and one alone - the
desperate need to be re-elected.
At least there is now a debate; people are better informed and Michael Howard
has not walked away from the Derek Lewis sacking unharmed. Healthy scepticism
over the party conference promises on imprisonment by the Tories is everywhere
evident, on both sides of the       Border.
It could be argued that the learning curve for the Scottish public has not been
so steep, the benefit of a smaller society with a healthy indigenous press
which still pays attention to social policy. Judge Tumim will, however, bring
his message north tomorrow when he address the Howard League in Edinburgh, and
the message is deceptively simple.
Prisons, he believes, have only one purpose which is to reduce the crime rate.
The way to achieve that aim is through education.
``I think it is necessary to think again about the whole purpose of prisons,''
he says, ``what prisons are for, who goes there and how you achieve the
objective of reducing the crime rate. Most of the people we send to prisons are
not dangerous. They are mainly young men who suffer two defects - lack of
education and lack of a proper family background. Their crimes are connected
with drink, drugs and motor cars and this is true in England and Scotland and
all round the world.''
Drink plays just as important a role in this universal truth as drugs although
drugs grab the headlines, Judge Tumim says. He steps back from a dogfight with
Michael Howard over how change in these young men is to be achieved but one can
readily observe what makes the Government so uncomfortable with this analysis.
Meaningful education programmes in prisons are difficult to achieve, the
unstated text runs, and do not interest headline writers. The reverse is
probably true, that the tabloids are more likely to scream about soft options
and - as anyone connected with the Scottish prisons experience since the return
of Michael Forsyth knows - the tabloids are a major preoccupation.
There is no choice but to tackle the difficulties, Judge Tumim declares,
starting from the day they enter prison with the three Rs followed by what he
calls moral education, teaching the young prisoners the difference between
right and wrong. They must be taught self-control as well as simple social
skills such as hygiene, budgeting, the problems they create for victims, and
they must learn to work.
The establishment or re-establishment of family links is also vitally important
if young prisoners are not to reoffend, he says, but work breeds self-respect.
Judge Tumim arrives in Scotland at a point when prison industries are under
review so his experience, particularly of one German model, is highly relevant.
While in Bavaria he saw at first hand the idea of a real industrial plant
relocated inside a prison with prisoners learning the industrial process,
earning full wages, paying tax and national insurance and keeping their
families free of state support.
``Of course there would be an outcry here about why should we be helping
prisoners when the law abiding are out of work but there is no good reason why
it should not happen. You get back to the fundamental purpose of reducing the
crime rate and that is what prisons are about,'' he declares. He has raised the
matter in past reports, he remarks drily, and while everyone was very much in
favour no-one has done anything with the idea.
A firm believer in the three-legged school of penal thought - a balance inside
prisons between security, care and order, and justice - Judge Tumim is clearly
unhappy about the present concentration on security at the expense of the other
vital factors.
His fears were confirmed when he recently discovered that one major London jail
had reduced its education programmes by 50% to pay for increased security.
At the same time he will not attack the Government's proposed Supermax prisons,
the vastly-expensive American idea for ensuring that the tiny - 2% or 3% -
proportion of truly dangerous prisoners is kept totally secure.
``Is there not a real threat, however, that in the TV and tabloid age these
will be turned into Devil's Island? It could get all too emotional, out of
proportion. And if you should lose control you lose control of all your most
dangerous prisoners at once,'' he says. He favours keeping the dispersal
prisons in better shape.
What do the prisons do well?
Judge Tumim states: ``What I call the resettlement prisons, where men who have
served very long sentences are resocialised by being given responsibility such
as their own keys and jobs outside, I think are the best thing in the
English prison system. They give men a sense of self worth. This is an
enormously important aspect, possibly the most important if you accept the
definition that prisons are about cutting the crime rate.''
In his eight years as chief inspector he has worked with five Home Secretaries,
constant change which has not helped progress. He believes the debate has taken
a sour turn, particularly over such matters as accountability for policy on the
one hand and operational issues on the other, and that what is really needed is
a lengthy period of stability to let the policy pendulum swing back in the
right direction.
He will find few tomorrow in Scotland who disagree with that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
