<HEADLINE>Up to 1900 on child protection registers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159399</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALMOST 1900 youngsters were placed on child protection registers in Scotland
during the first year of a system of collating information.
Scotland's social work departments were asked to investigate around 7500
possible cases of children requiring care and protection during the 12 months
up to March last year, according to the first statistical bulletin on child
protection management information, published yesterday.
The bulletin shows that nearly 3000 referrals went to case conference stage to
decide on the need for action against unacceptable levels of risk. A total of
1880 children were placed on the protection registers.
Scottish Home Affairs Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton described the
publication as a valuable feature for the effective protection of children.
``I hope that local authorities will use the output of this system in their
management of child-protection services. It should improve management and
thereby improve services,'' he said.
Of the 1880 child protection orders, 45% covered children at risk of physical
injury, 25% were to prevent sexual abuse, 19% for physical neglect, 9% for
emotional abuse, and 2% for ``failure to thrive''.
Forty-one percent of the children lived with their natural parents, 24% with
only the mother, 11% with the mother and partner, and 6% with mother and
stepfather.
Parents were the suspected main perpetrator in 70% of cases, with the father
the suspect in 40% and the mother in 30% of cases.
According to the statistics, 97% of sexual abuse cases involved a man. In 41%
of cases, he was the natural father, in 23% another relative, and in 18% the
mother's partner.
At the end of March 1994, the total number of children registered for
protection stood at 2666, an average of 2.3 per 1000 of youngsters under 18,
which was unchanged from the previous year.
The numbers of children on regional registers ranged from 55, or less than one
per 1000, in Fife, to 744, almost five per 1000, in Lothian. In Strathclyde,
the number was 785 - 1.5 per 1000.
The bulletin shows that referral rates during the year varied from region to
region above and below a national average of 6.7 per 1000 children. The Western
Isles had the lowest rate, at 1.7. Central had the highest referral rate - 14.4.
</TEXT>
