<DOCNO>GH951128-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour warns of investment risk. Railtrack  in line for bargain sell off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159400</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE rail industry fears the Government is so keen to press on with
privatisation before the next General Election that Railtrack will be sold at a
``give away'' price.
Senior Railtrack executives are to visit Scotland next week to try to interest
financial institutions in the investment opportunities offered by the
privatisation due next spring.
However, Labour's front-bench transport spokesman, Mr Brian Wilson, sounded a
note of caution. ``Nobody is going to make a fast buck out of Railtrack,'' he
warned would-be speculators.
``I am giving the clearest possible notice that this would be an extremely high
risk investment given the fact that Railtrack's revenue is over- whelmingly
dependent on political decisions on subsidy. Responsible investors should wait
for the partnership opportunities in expanding the railways which Labour is
very keen on.''
There is also a warning light from the newly privatised rolling stock leasing
companies (Roscos). British Rail management, in the main, believes the rolling
stock was handed over at such advantageous terms that the Roscos could expect
to face similar ``windfall tax'' levies from a Labour Government to those
already faced by the privatised utility companies.
It is argued that if Railtrack were floated on the Stock Exchange in such a way
as to attract handsome profits, those investors could also face a windfall tax
levy.
BR chiefs, who value the industry's infrastructure assets at some #6000m,
believe the Government is prepared to let them go at below #2000m, possibly
below #1500m, just to keep privatisation on course and make it difficult if not
impossible for an incoming Labour Government to reverse the process.
They are also deeply critical of the terms at which the three Roscos were sold
off earlier this month for almost #1800m. They are also unhappy the Roscos have
been guaranteed about #500,000 a year of taxpayers' money, yet they will be
under no obligation to invest it in new rolling stock.
``They could even bid for rail franchises or invest in the National Lottery
such is the total lack of deregulation,'' said one disgruntled BR board member
yesterday.
Labour clearly believes there is a possibility of halting the latest sale but
are clearly concerned about a cut-price deal.
Mr Wilson said: ``I have all along been concerned that a scorched earth policy
would be pursued as a General Election came closer and every effort is being
made to head it off.
``We are already committed to bringing the rolling stock companies under the
regulator so as to force investment and limit profits. The terms of a Railtrack
sell off, which we firmly believe can be prevented, would obviously affect the
potential cost of bringing it back.''
The Government is expected to achieve its declared aim of seeing 51% of
passenger services in the private sector, although perhaps not until April 1997
rather than the original target date of April 1996.
An incoming Labour Government would then be left with the worst of all possible
worlds, with half the industry in private hands. It would then have to decide
whether it should seek to bring the bulk of the industry back into the public
sector, for instance through the renationalisation of all or a majority of
Railtrack, or opt instead for public control of the industry by way of tighter
regulation.
</TEXT>
