<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mandela new refugee patron</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159402</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Nelson Mandela is to be the new patron of the Scottish Refugee
Council.
He will be welcomed at a reception in Edinburgh on Thursday.
The refugee council was set up in 1985 to support refugees arriving in Scotland
and the reception will mark its 10th anniversary.
Canon Kenyon Wright, the present patron, said yesterday that, for 10 years, the
refugee council had been a living witness of all that was best in the character
of Scotland - care for the victim, openness to the poor or powerless, and
readiness to learn from others who were different.
``Nelson Mandela's magnificent gesture in accepting the invitation is, I am
sure, both a tribute to the Scottish Refugee Council itself and a recognition
of the leading role Scotland played in the fight against apartheid and racism.''
Canon Wright said that, in a society increasingly divided and closing its doors
on compassion, the refugee council's work would be even more important in the
next 10 years.
Councillor Keith Geddes, Lothian Regional Council's leader of administration,
said he was keen that the new Edinburgh City Council should continue to support
the Refugee Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ICAS urges need for independent regulator</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159403</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NIALL Lothian, president of the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland
(ICAS), last night emphasised the need for an independent regulator to oversee
ICAS and the UK's other accountancy bodies, writes IAN McCONNELL.
Professor Lothian believes the profession, which has until now regulated
itself, must be answerable to a truly independent body if public confidence is
to be ensured.
He said: ``I think that informed political commentators and informed pockets of
the media are rightly sceptical about whether or not we can be legislator,
judge and jury in our own court.
``It is in addressing that issue, against the background of corporate collapses
in the past decade, that we are really driven to examining our own procedures.''
The initial view of an ICAS working party, which has not yet been finalised, is
that all regulatory activities should be put beyond the perimeter fence of the
profession. Regulatory activities encompass auditing standards, monitoring, and
discipline.
A less radical change is proposed by the English and Welsh institute's working
party, which believes regulatory activities should remain within the
profession's domain. It believes an external body should be formed to comment
publicly on the efficacy of these activities.
Professor Lothian envisages an independent regulatory body appointed by the
profession and users of the audit product such as the Bank of England, the
Stock Exchange, and the Confederation of British Industry. This could report to
Parliament.
Referring to the current self-regulatory regime, Professor Lothian said: ``The
public interest must be protected. It is just a touch too easy what is going on
just now.''
Professor Lothian's comments came in response to those made in Edinburgh by
Stuart Bell, Labour's spokesman on trade and corporate affairs.
Mr Bell said: ``Three years ago we pointed out that the accountancy profession
would have to put its own house in order, otherwise a Labour government would
have to do it for them.
``Since that time, however, we have been satisfied with the way the proposals
on regulation of the profession have developed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Salvesen enjoys a bright day as profit and shares jump</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159404</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of the brightest days for a considerable time for Christian Salvesen saw
its share price jump 14p to 254p after better-than-expected half-time results
and evidence that its long-term strategy is already beginning to pay off.
The best guide to performance is operating profit which showed an improvement
of 5.1% to #45.4m from the continuing activities and will benefit from more
than #100m of investment this year. These exclude the Salvesen brick and Vicoma
oil spill clearance activities which have been sold off and which brought in
#2.9m in the preceding year.
The actual pre-tax total showed an 8.7% improvement to #46.1m but that was
boosted by a #2.1m gain from the sale of currency swaps.
Distribution had a relatively mundane experience as measured by the headline 3%
rise in its contribution to #22.3m. But that conceals deep eddies.
The UK food activities were affected by a shortfall in the availability of
fresh produce thanks to the drought.
That actually hit the separate food services division harder. There profits
tumbled #1.6m to #4.9m as a result of reduced availability of fresh vegetables
and fruit. However, that should be partially recovered in the current half with
the Tendafrost frozen foods subsidiary benefiting from higher frozen pea prices.
Chief executive Dr Chris Masters said yesterday that margins in UK food retail
distribution will remain under pressure as the supermarkets continue to press
to take costs out of their business.
One major example is the seven-year contract with Tesco to create nine
recycling centres which will wash more than 200 million plastic trays a year
and reclaim 160,000 tonnes of packaging - the saving to Tesco will amount to
#12m annually.
In Germany there was a slight loss in retail distribution but elsewhere the
overall picture was much more encouraging. Salvesen has been able to pick up
substantial new contracts in Italy and Holland helped by its information
technology skills which are now available throughout western Europe and,
therefore, are a major selling point when dealing with food manufacturers with
international business. It is one of very few in that position.
To this end and to strengthen its underlying management in Europe, it is
pulling back 16 people from South Africa as it reckons there are more immediate
and better opportunities nearer home.
Industrial customers such as car manufacturers are increasing their load
requirements on Salvesen and that is generally better margin business than food.
Encouragingly, out-sourcing of logistics is rising by 18% annually in the EU
and consumer non-foods - Salvesen's biggest contract here is with Marks &amp;
Spencer - is increasing by 12%, while food distribution is up by only 4% in
Europe implying that it is flat in the more mature British market.
Thanks to a large measure the US, the Aggreko electricity, temperature control
and plant hire operations have resumed growth with profits up 21% to #18.2m.
There the introduction of oil-free compressed air is finding ready buyers in
the chemical sector, where monitoring equipment can be affected by the
traditional compressed air absorbing oil droplets which have then to be
filtered out.
Full-year profits, shorn of the disposals and with the second half being
traditionally the lighter, seem set to increase about #3m to #78m. That points
to the shares being traded at 13 times likely earnings.
The interim dividend has been raised marginally to 3.5p with an 8.8p total
probable for a 4.3% yield.
</TEXT>
