<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Beating the Americans was highlight of year.  Sherry's cup full and running over</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>golf and golfers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159406</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GORDON Sherry, who at a dinner this evening at the Glasgow Golf Club will be
presented with his award as winner of the 1995 J&amp;B Scottish order of merit, is
just beginning to get his breath back at the end of a particularly busy and
eventful last full season as an amateur. He can now take stock of it - and also
look ahead.
In that latter vision Sherry will in January travel to Arizona for three or
four weeks of practice in the sunshine at Desert Mountain, the course near
Phoenix which is one of several developed by the American, Lyle Anderson, among
whose other interests is the Loch Lomond club, of which Sherry is an honorary
life member.
Then in March, in his build-up for the US Masters, Sherry will first practise
at Valderrama, in southern Spain, a course similar in character to Augusta
National, and then have a week in Georgia in advance of the first of the
season's four major championships. After he has competed in that Sherry will
turn professional.
``I've had a great time as an amateur,'' Sherry says. ``I've played in Walker
Cup, Eisenhower Trophy and European championship sides and won the Amateur
Championship. There's little chance of repeating all these achievements and I
just feel the time has come to move on to other things.''
A spring-time declaration of intent does, however, mean there must be something
of a lull in Sherry's career, since he will not be able to play the European
Tour school until next November. However, he hopes he will be able to keep his
game in trim by receiving sponsors' invitations to tournaments.
Since Sherry became only the third Scottish golfer in 50 attempts since the
Second World War to win Britain's foremost title, his victory in the Amateur
last June would occur to most observers to have been the highlight for him. But
Sherry, surprisingly perhaps, takes another view of the priorities.
``Winning at Hoylake was all I ever wanted to do as an individual this season,
particularly as I'd lost in the final last year at Nairn,'' Sherry reflects.
``That opened a lot of doors, such as gaining exemption into the Open
Championship and the Masters.
``But it meant everything to me first to make the Walker Cup team and then to
help Britain and Ireland to beat the United States at Royal Porthcawl,'' he
continues. ``It's more satisfying, I think, to be part of a team success.'' In
a game that is inevitably as self-absorbed as golf, that ranks as a rare
admission.
The other cause for satisfaction in a co-operative venture was the 100% record
Sherry achieved to make a huge contribution towards Scotland's victory in the
European team championship at Royal Antwerp - not least, presumably, because it
concluded with a healthy 6-1 defeat of the Auld Enemy, England, in the final.
Apart from the Walker Cup match the most memorable period extended over three
successive weeks last summer when, after the European victory, Sherry was equal
fourth among a high-class field in the Scottish Open at Carnoustie, (the
highest finish ever by an amateur in a European Tour event), and then made the
cut in the Open at St Andrews.
That extended an exhausting sequence of practice and competition, under the
pressures of the occasion and the scrutiny of both the public and the media,
led to Sherry's decision - controversial at the time and one he shared with
Stephen Gallacher - not to play in the Scottish Amateur championship at
Southerness. But Sherry maintains he did the right thing.
``I'd never won the Scottish,'' Sherry says ``but I felt I had to pull out in
the best interests of preparing for the Walker Cup match. I know I later played
in the Canadian Amateur (in which he reached the semi-final), but that was like
a holiday. There was less pressure and it was an ideal refresher.''
Rubbing shoulders with such luminaries of the game as Jack Nicklaus, Tom
Watson, and Greg Norman has taught Sherry, he himself believes, valuable
lessons on how to manage himself on and off the course.
The achievements he has had thus far suggest he has already successfully served
a considerable part of his apprenticeship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
