<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>80 feared dead as boat sinks in India</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159407</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PASSENGER boat capsized and sank on the Ganges river in the Indian state of
Bihar today but there were conflicting reports on casualties.
Domestic news agencies reported that between 20 and 80 people were feared
drowned. But a police official in Monghyr district, where the vessel went down,
told Reuters by telephone there were no casualties.
``About 60 persons on board swam to safety. By the time the boat reached the
shore, there was a stampede to get off in a rush which caused the mishap. None
have met with a watery grave,'' police Deputy Inspector General Naseem Ahmed
said.
Ahmed said there were about 80 people on board. The police had thrown a huge
net into the river near Mallihar Ghat, where the boat sank, to fish out
survivors, he said.
The United News of India said at least 80 people were feared drowned and quoted
official sources as saying no bodies had yet been recovered. It gave no further
details.
The Press Trust of India (PTI) said at least 25 people were feared drowned when
an overloaded boat capsized in the Ganges in Bihar's Begusarai district today.
Begusarai is adjacent to Monghyr. It was not clear whether the two news
agencies were referring to the same boat.
PTI said the boat, which was built to carry 40 people, was carrying over twice
the number.
The news agency quoted police officials as saying two bodies had been recovered
so far.
q.A rickety boat crowded with Haitians headed to the United States capsized,
and authorities said 47 people may have drowned, independent Radio Metropole
said today.
Local authorities in the northwestern town of Port-de-Paix have already
recovered seven bodies, the report said.
The report said the incident occurred over the weekend. Immigration officials
say Port-de-Paix has served as a popular point of departure in recent months
for clandestine boat trips to the United States.
On Friday, the US Coast Guard intercepted 516 Haitians who departed
Port-de-Paix in a freighter.-Reuter.
Patna, India
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A reprieve for four Sunday sinners</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159408</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR key players who are due to start their suspensions this weekend will still
be able to play on Saturday as a consequence of the trend of playing live TV
matches on Sunday.
Each of the quartet, Celtic's John Hughes and Peter Grant, Rangers' Paul
Gascoigne, and Hibernian's Michael O'Neill, suffered the final card which took
them over the punishment threshold in the derby games a week last Sunday.
Apart from O'Neill's immediate one-game ban for being sent off, the suspensions
which were then imposed do not begin until a fortnight after the offence, which
means all of them are free to play this Saturday.
In Celtic's case, that may not be considered a big advantage, as Grant and
Hughes, who will each miss three games, will be available for the home match
with Kilmarnock.
But on the down side is the fact that they now miss the hazardous journey to
Kirkcaldy to face Raith Rovers on Boxing Day. Before that, the two Parkhead men
will sit out the game against Hibs at Easter Road, and the home meeting with
Falkirk. The delayed ban might be seen as a bonus by Hibs. O'Neill will be
absent for three matches after being free to play in what looks a tough contest
against Motherwell at Fir Park, but he will then be out for the games against
Celtic and Raith Rovers at home before his last enforced day off, against
Partick Thistle at Firhill.
In Rangers' case, the delay will mean that their fans will get the chance to
see if the brilliance of Gascoigne in Edinburgh last week can be repeated in
the capital when they take on Hearts at Tynecastle. Given the choice, it seems
likely that the manager would have preferred to have the Englishman for that
task, rather than the one game he will now miss - the home match with Partick
Thistle on December 9.
Thistle fans might object to that line of thinking, of course, and they might
be even cheekier if their manager, Murdo MacLeod, seals the transfer of Mark
McNally from Celtic this week. The #60,000 deal looks certain to be completed
when the Parkhead defender returns from a visit down south later in the week.
If that happens, then MacLeod would free Steve Welsh to make his move to
Lincoln City, who have been patiently waiting for Thistle to fill the position
before getting their man, also for #60,000.
MacLeod is keen to see McNally in his team. ``The lad has played at the top
level with Celtic after having come through the ranks at Parkhead. He is the
kind we could build the team around, and if we do settle his transfer, it would
give everybody at the club a lift. A new face always does that and especially
one from a big club.''
MacLeod intends to give reserve keeper Mark Cairns his chance, now that Nicky
Walker will be out with a broken jaw for a couple of months. ``The lad is the
reserve keeper, and he deserves his chance,'' said the manager. ``After all, he
is 26, and if he is not good enough now, he never will be.''
Meanwhile Walker, who has been outstanding all season, is determined the injury
will not deflect him from reaching the European Championship finals next
season. ``I'm quite fortunate. In most cases like mine, it takes three months
before you can play agan, but because of my position, the specialist reckons I
should be able to come back after about eight weeks, as long as I'm careful.
``The injury isn't too bad. There's just a constant ache. I can still talk,
even if I can't eat much. Hopefully, I will be back in good time to stake a
claim for a Scotland place at the Euro finals. That would be a great experience.
``There is not an international until March, so that could work in my favour. I
know that they are trying to increase the size of the finals' squads to 22, and
that should secure a place for a third goalkeeper.
``Obviously, Jim Leighton and Andy Goram will be going if they are fit, and I
reckon there are three or four keepers who will fancy their chances of grabbing
the other place. I just want to get back and turn in performances that will
keep me in Craig Brown's thoughts.''-
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sticking to the social web</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Steve Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159409</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alienation is society's biggest concern, argues Steve Bruce
LYNNE Brown, a political activist from South Africa's ANC, believes that Scots
are ``disillusioned with the conventional political process'' and feel
powerless to do anything much about it. She may well be right, but to get some
perspective we need to divide her estimation of the scale of the problem by
half. That is to compensate for the fact professional politicians have an
unhealthy appetite for politics.
Scaled down to the expectations of sensible people, how bad is our
disillusionment? We still vote in healthy numbers for General (if not local)
elections and most of us do that despite having seen our votes at the last four
elections count for nothing. And not all apathy results from unhappiness. Many
Scottish schools are unable to find enough parent representatives to form
school boards because those parents are satisfied with their schools.
However, if Lynne Brown has been talking to those community activists who toil
in our ``sink'' housing schemes, like Aisyphus bravely, endlessly and
fruitlessly rolling the boulder up the hill, it is easy to see why she is
struck by tales of fatalism. There is a large disenfranchised ``lumpen
proletariat'' out there. It cut itself off from the political process to avoid
the poll tax. It is further alienated by the requirement to seek the middle
ground which our first past-the-post electoral structure imposes.
Even if the unemployed all voted, our major parties would direct their appeal
elsewhere.
Should we be concerned? Should we see parallels with Weimar Germany, a mass
ready for recruitment to fascism? There may be some potential for that. Like
blood in the faeces, traces of racist violence might indicate a deeper cancer
but the sad fact is that really desperate hopeless circumstances breed not
revolution but self-destruction.
We must also be careful about seeing as a frighteningly new problem something
which has always been with us. The feudal peasant was hardly an active citizen.
But we do need to recognise a real and worrisome change: the decline in
voluntary associations.
More important than electoral politics for a healthy society are the ties that
bind people in cross-cutting networks, each based around a specific interest:
churches, professional groups, organised leisure activities, educational
groups, social clubs, co-operatives, housing associations, tenants groups,
trades unions, charity groups, and therapeutic communities. Because people
belonged in two or three groups, their overlapping interests bound them
together, neutralised potential for conflict, and made them feel as if they had
a shared stake in their world.
Large holes have been torn in that mesh. Families are less stable and less
extensive, church-going has declined, workers education sounds pass, and
trade unionism is barely a force; we are no longer as connected. The average
employed worker is three times better off than his or her 1945 counter-part but
the large firm has given way to the small, the full-time, long-term job to the
part-time, short-term. The fortunate are better off but physically isolated.
The unfortunate are huddled but hopeless.
As Labour politicians are coming to appreciate, we cannot blame this all on
Thatcher's radical individualism. The welfare state, by promising to provide
for us, undermined traditions of self-help. Increasing freedom has meant
ever-greater cultural diversity and that is probably irreversible, as is the
decline in the faith that made churches such important voluntary institutions.
Globalisation of the world economy has removed from all governments many levers
for economic engineering.
It is sorely tempting to follow Herod into the washroom but there is an
alternative. We can recognise the disappearance of political power upwards to
trans-national entities such as the European Union must be balanced by the
devolution of power downwards to regions and localities.
The lumpen proleteriat will always be with us, as will be its most
self-destructive habits but, and this brings us back to Lynne Brown, we can try
to win some of those people back to civil society by creating genuinely
devolved structures and educating people to operate within them.
That will mean nothing unless we can also create economic opportunities that
return security to the well-off and return hope to the badly-off that they can
some day join the fortunate.
In the end, civil society depends on social security; not the euphemism for
state handouts, but the economic security which allows people to think of a
future which is better than the present. Now how do we do that?
n.Steve Bruce is Professor of Sociology at the University of Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
