<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Banks reject offer to handle student loans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159410</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO of Scotland's leading banks have told the Government that they are not
interested in helping to run the student loans system.
This rejection, plus that of other financial institutions, has raised doubts
about whether the Government will be able to implement a transfer of the loan
system to private finance, and could jeopardise legislation to enable this
currently going through Parliament.
A spokeswoman for the Bank of Scotland said it had been approached, but after
reviewing the draft tender document, had decided not to make a bid. At the
Royal Bank of Scotland, a spokes-man said that at the moment it was not
attracted to the scheme at all.
Building societies were also less than enthusiastic. An Alliance and Leicester
spokesman said ``certainly not'', and the Woolwich said it was not interested.
The Department for Education and Employment wants up to four financial
institutions to become involved in the system from the next financial year,
eventually to provide the majority of student loans.
The four would receive a subsidy for providing low-interest loans, but the
level of subsidy has not been disclosed. If interested, financial institutions
would have to say how much subsidy they would want, and those bidding the
smallest amount of subsidy would win the business.
The Government wishes to leave a margin of between 5% to 10% for bad debt, but
at present the amount expected never to be recovered is running at over 12%,
and is expected to grow.
Banks are also wary of the bad publicity they could attract by chasing students
for bad debt, and the knock-on effect on future business from former students.
It is believed that the education department hopes to pull in building
societies keen to use the loans scheme to develop their banking services -
despite failed attempts to diversify into other markets such as estate agency.
</TEXT>
