<HEADLINE>Cairo summit on Huti-Tutsi conflict</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JONATHAN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159411</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Cairo
FOUR central African leaders meet in Cairo today to try to halt the conflict
between Hutus and Tutsis that has devastated Rwanda and Burundi and left
neighbouring states facing a vast refugee crisis.
Former US president Jimmy Carter and his Atlanta-based centre for conflict
resolution will try to extract an agreement enabling more than three million
Rwandans to go home and paving the way for peaceful coexistence between the two
ethnic groups.
Up to one million Tutsis and Hutus massacred each other in the small central
African state of Rwanda last year and at least 100,000 people have been
slaughtered in two years in a similar conflict which continues in neighbouring
Burundi.
The bloodshed, which has origins dating back many centuries, has dragged in
Zaire, host to most of the refugees, and Uganda, the launching-pad for the
Tutsi-led rebellion which brought the present Rwandan government to power.
Tanzania, which has refugees from both Rwanda and Burundi, is sending to the
summit Abdulrahman Kinana, a special envoy from Tanzania's new president,
Benjamin Mkapa.
Former Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere will help mediate between the
principal parties, along with Carter and Archbishop Desmond Tutu of South
Africa, the Carter Center said.
The level of violence has declined in the Rwanda-Burundi region since last year
but a big gap remains between Hutu leaders in exile and the government in
Kigali, which says it is doing its best to put the bloody past behind it.
In Burundi, the Tutsi-dominated army has stepped up its campaign against
suspected Hutu rebels, using an indiscriminate strategy which diplomats say is
likely to cripple peace prospects in the troubled country.
The weekend brought the exiled Hutus further cause for anxiety. Police in
Kenya, once a haven, arrested scores of Rwandans, possibly in connection with
the future trials.
On the summit agenda for urgent action stand two subsidiary problems - Zaire's
wish to repatriate the refugees from eastern Zaire as soon as possible and the
Rwandan government's reluctance to extend the mandate of UN forces on their
territory, widely seen as essential to security.--Reuter
</TEXT>
