<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Target reached</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159412</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE forestry department of the chartered surveyor Bowlts, based in Pluscarden,
near Elgin in Moray, has planted its three-millionth native tree, at an estate
in Nairnshire.
The achievement is the culmination of almost five years work for a variety of
landowners in the Highlands and west Grampian areas who are keen to conserve
and enhance an essential part of Scotland's native woodland heritage.
The firm, whose forestry department has specialised in planting and
regeneration of native woodlands, reached the milestone while working at Lethen
Estate for Ewen Brodie.
Alastair Lumsden of Bowlts' forestry department said: ``New native pine
planting is generally carried out to help extend and link the fragments of the
existing mature native pinewood in an effort to restore the continuous
ecosystem that once covered Scotland.
``Many of our clients are particularly keen to help maintain and establish
pinewoods and become involved in the conservation of the native pinewood
resource.''
</TEXT>
