<DOCNO>GH951128-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gray's back on tour - after a  25-year break</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUGLAS LOWE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159413</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GORDON Gray, the professional at Dumfries and County for the past 23 years, is
the latest to discover that golfers can be born again in their fifties, having
just earned his card for the PGA European Seniors Tour.
The 51-year-old, who first took up the game at Bearsden along with brother
Martin, a Tartan Tour stalwart, has already competed in 11 seniors event over
the last season and a half, but is approaching 1996 with great vigour in the
knowledge that he will be able to play in up to 15 events, around half in
mainland Europe, without the uncertainties of pre-qualifying.
More golden moments are in prospect then, like the one this year in the Senior
British Open at Royal Portrush, where he found himself rubbing shoulders on the
practice range with Arnold Palmer and Gary Player. ``I could hardly believe I
was standing there with them. It was wonderful,'' he recalled.
Next season will be his first serious campaign for 25 years, since his largely
undistinguished two-year bid as a Bothwell Castle-based assistant on the
embryonic European Tour. He did have a top-100 ranking then, but he explained:
``There were many of us who tried, but we all came off the Tour and took club
jobs, because there was not enough money.''
Gray puts down much of his current rejuvenation to keeping himself in good
shape in the interim as a three times a week gymnasium regular, half an hour of
each session on running and bike work and the other half on weights, which he
plans to step up from light to heavy as a strengthening exercise.
Another factor has been his pleasure in watching the rise of Andrew Coltart. As
mentor to the youngest member of Scotland's first successful Dunhill Cup team
this year, it has obviously helped to give him acceptance as a coach, but it
goes beyond that.
Gray said: ``Andrew's success has been great for golf in the south of Scotland.
Undoubtedly, some of that has rubbed off on me, and now the south has a player
on both the regular and senior tours.''
Along with North Berwick's David Huish he will be one of only two home-based
Scottish regulars on the Seniors Tour next year, and one aspect of his game he
will be working on especially is his putting.
``In the tournaments I have played in so far I won around #8000. From tee to
green I could compete with most of the guys, but I didn't putt very well and
two months ago I switched to the broom-handle putter.''
There were moments in the 54-hole qualifying school at Peralda, Spain, that
made him wonder if it was going to make any difference. There were 38 putts in
an opening three-over-par 75, a score he repeated in the second round with 36
strokes on the greens. In the final round he was well over par to the turn and
his hopes looked forlorn, but suddenly he holed a long one and the broomhandle
turned into a magic wand.
He came back in 31, with six birdies, for a 69 to claim his ticket to a new
life with nothing to spare.
One thing that has not changed over the last 25 years is the high cost of
competing abroad, and Gray will be looking for a sponsor in the coming weeks.
He also hopes to step up his coaching role, his interest in this side of the
game having been encouraged by conversations on tour with the likes of Tommy
Horton and Brian Huggett, both of them established gurus.
From the start of the year onwards though, and in between his ongoing
commitment as a club pro, all will be geared towards May, when he dusts off his
passport and heads for the season opener in Turkey.
q GORDON Dalgleish, a former Scottish youth cap, has won his first national
title at the age of 33 in the fast-developing golfing nation of China.
The Georgia-based Dalgleish, a former member at Helensburgh, carded rounds of
72, 75, 73, and 73 over the 6800-yard, par-72 Jack Nicklaus design at Chung
Shan Hot Spring, just over the border from Macau, to win the tenth China Open
Amateur championship by nine strokes with a five-over-par aggregate.
Dalgleish, younger brother of Colin, captain of the Scottish men's amateur
team, combined the competition with a business trip to Asia to promote the golf
travel business, Perrygolf, which the pair operate.
``It was the first serious competition I have played in since the Scottish
Amateur two and a half years ago,'' said the one-handicapper, who now plays out
of the Reynolds Plantation club, near Atlanta, and plans to return to China
next year to defend.
Among past winners is Walker Cup player Gary Wolstenholme, who won over the
Arnold Palmer-designed course at the same club. This was the first time the
longer and typically heavily bunkered Nicklaus version had been used.
This year there was a field of 110 players, the vast majority of them Asian.
</TEXT>
