<HEADLINE>Touting for cup finals</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159414</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MURRAYFIELD would have been an ideal setting for Sunday's Coca-Cola Cup final,
Scottish Rugby Union chief executive Bill Hogg claimed yesterday.
The 67,500 all-seated stadium, which was completed almost exactly a year ago at
a cost of #41m, is now one of the finest sports stadiums in the world but,
according to the SRU, there is an apparent reluctance on the part of the
footballing authorities to make use of it.
Yesterday, at a Murrayfield media briefing, Hogg said that he was in regular
contact with his counterpart at the Scottish Football Association but, he said:
``We don't seem to have much clout there.
``Sunday's cup final featuring two east coast teams would have been ideal for
Murrayfield. It would have been much handier for Dundee and Aberdeen fans than
Hampden Park.''
Murrayfield is currently under-utilised with Scotland's two home games in the
Five Nations' Championship and a November visit by a touring side being the
only regular games.
The stadium has also been a venue for pop concerts, REM having played there and
Tina Turner scheduled to perform next June.
The Scottish Claymores American football side uses Murrayfield for its home
games, although it emerged yesterday that they would no longer use the stadium
for training.
Hogg added: ``We didn't speak specifically to the SFA about Sunday's game, but
we have mentioned to them the possibility of hosting semi-final or final games
when two east coast clubs were involved. Murrayfield is a very central venue
and easy to access.''
The issue of crowd segregation has cropped up in the past, but Hogg said:
"There is a facility for crowd segregation, so it is all there.''
SFA chief executive Jim Farry pointed out that Hampden is the National Stadium
and as such is the natural venue for all major cup finals. ``Of course, if a
situation arose where Murrayfield could be used in a football context then we
would be more than happy to take advantage of the stadium,'' he said.
``We admire the rugby      stadium, but I have to say that we do not suggest
that a West of Scotland and Kelso match should be played at Broadwood.''
</TEXT>
