<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What's in it for us?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mike Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>book review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Table Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159415</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of this autumn's less edifying television spectacles was to see the head of
Yorkshire Water forced to admit the infrequency of his bathing arrangements as
he faced a media grilling about the water shortages in his area.
I wonder how many of you who saw his predicament felt any sympathy? No, neither
did I. But consider this. If we had been exposed to the glare of publicity,
could we have done any better?
Media awareness training until fairly recently was the province of the upwardly
mobile politician. These days - despite the cynics' view that it teaches one
about how to avoid answering direct questions - such training for managers is
very much in vogue.
With the scales now more equably balanced between reporter and subject, is it
surprising that we have reached the age of the totally bland interview that
evokes the same excitement as watching paint drying on a wall?
Offering some thoughts on the subject today is Mike Shaw (above left) who, as
programme development editor with BBC Radio Scotland, is responsible for
commissioning independent productions for the station.
TRADING places can be a useful, even humbling experience. Doctors, for example,
are reckoned to make the worst patients. Professional broadcasters, to be fair,
sometimes make less than ideal interviewees.
I was recently invited to appear on French radio during Radio Scotland's
extensive coverage of the Lorient Festival Interceltique in Britanny. The
request was actually relayed to me via a third party and I was never actually
informed what was wanted from me or whether the programme was live or recorded.
I wasn't even given the name of the person doing the interview, or, as it
transpired, the fact that he and his production team were several hundred miles
away in another studio. It was also only when I turned up the following morning
that I discovered that they also wanted a 30, not a three-minute discussion.
Then just as the recording started a small regiment of Scotland's finest pipers
and their Breton counterparts began warming up on the quay below our makeshift
studio for the festival championship to be held later that day. In other words,
all the pre-conditions were in place for the radio equivalent of the famous
Blue Peter interview with the elephant!
In his book Face the Press* John Lidstone is very much against doing what I
did. He warns against rushing into interviews and points out the need to
identify in advance precisely what is required of the interviewee. Find out the
likely audience; how will your interview be used - will it stand alone or, for
example, be part of a wider feature?
Nobody could argue with the general principles outlined here, and one would
expect most journalists to clear this territory in advance. On the other hand,
calls taken at home have been known to undermine the innocent, surrounded as
they are by familiar trappings and therefore less vigilant, as perhaps some
royal advisers are now contemplating.
The author also advocates making lists of positives and negatives before
agreeing to take part in an interview. The bottom line is what's in it for us?
His positives include general promotion of the company, enhancing its profile,
informing the community, and staff motivation.
Motivation? I once met an American telecommunications executive who had gone
public on the inadequacy of the service his company were providing, and who
promised to get things right. He calculated that his staff knew the truth of
the present difficulties and would appreciate honesty.
He got it right on both counts, which is doubtless one of the reasons why he
felt able to tell the story. In slightly different circumstances a certain Mr
Ratner got it rather badly wrong, and the rest is history. John Lidstone's
negatives include evaluation of similar risks to the company's name, its share
value and the interviewee's career.
The sum total of all this advice borders, though, on confirmation of a
conspiracy theory of all media relations. The executive who takes on board
every recommendation will be mentally dressed like the proverbial American
footballer. Lines over-rehearsed with corporate affairs can sound pretty
ordinary. Informed comment, delivered in a lively manner, is far superior.
It's not surprising that a small number of people appear so often in the press
and on radio and television. They're good and they're wanted back. There's a
further general moral in this for all organisations, and that's to avoid
getting hung up on status and hierarchy. Offer your best speaker. Apart from
anything else, the electronic media can be terribly cruel to the inadequate
performer.
Fortunately Lidstone avoids a fair amount of this overkill. He advocates
developing good relations with journalists, offers practical advice on how to
deal with what is ``on'' and ``off'' the record, and presents some extremely
useful and well-illustrated text on what to expect when you visit the
television and radio studio. The case studies are interesting and stimulate
thinking. He has obviously had some solid practical experience on which to base
his propositions.
For most people the chance to perform comes on rarely, so it's a good idea to
listen, watch and read as much as possible to get into the mindset of the
practitioners of different sectors of the media. You could do worse than start
with Lidstone.
* Face the Press by John Lidstone
Book Review is compiled and edited by Stuart Paul of the University of Paisley.
