<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Claims for justice in transfers battle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159416</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SMALL football clubs will not suffer if the European Court of Justice accepts
advice to outlaw the player transfer system, claimed Advocate-General Carl Otto
Lenz yesterday in Brussels.
``Nobody is going to disappear,'' said Lenz, a lawyer who has advised the court
considering a case brought by Belgian player Jean-Marc Bosman that it should
declare European football's transfer system and limits on foreign players
illegal.
``The court could decide on a transitional period (to a more open system) of
five years,'' said Lenz, one of the court's chief legal advisers, at the end of
a European Parliament convention on sport. ``An end to clubs organising the
market would be best for everyone,'' he added.
But UEFA, the sport's governing body in Europe, told the convention that Lenz's
recommendations, if accepted by the court, could create a two-tier system of
clubs. Small clubs, which rely heavily on transfer payments, fear they will go
under in a free market.
``Football is not just about the big clubs and the great stars but also about
the thousands of clubs and the hundreds of thousands of players at every level
across the length and breadth of the Continent,'' said the presidents of the 49
national associations in UEFA in a letter read out at the convention.
The letter dismissed Lenz's proposal of safeguarding smaller clubs by
redistributing a percentage of all clubs' income. ``His proposed alternative,
that funds should be redistributed with nothing in return, is simply
unworkable,'' it said.
Yesterday's convention had no legal bearing on the court decision, which is
expected early next year.
Bosman's case began in 1990, when FC Liege of Belgium blocked his proposed
transfer to French club Dunkirk. Liege later suspended Bosman, who is now
seeking damages of about $1m from UEFA and the Belgian football union, claiming
he was unofficially blacklisted after starting the court case.
FIFA has expressed concern that European Union countries would be left out of
step with the rest of the world if the European court accepted Lenz's advice.
</TEXT>
