<DOCNO>GH951128-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Princess faces a strained truce</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159417</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess of Wales arrived home from her Argentina visit yesterday to face
the fall-out from her Panorama TV interview.
She flew into Heathrow on a scheduled British Airways flight from Buenos Aires.
After her high-profile trip to South America, the princess faces strained
relations with other members of the royal family, who are still coping with the
shock waves from her television revelations.
Buckingham Palace officials have offered Diana talks to ``help define her
future role'' in public life ``and continue to support her as a member of the
royal family''.
They are anxious to avoid any vindictive exchange after the no-holds-barred
interview in which the princess confessed to adultery with ex-Life Guards
cavalry captain James Hewitt, cast doubt on her estranged husband's suitability
to be king, and claimed she was the victim of palace plotters.
However, the princess is expected to guard her newly-won independence jealously
and to resist attempts to control her.
For their part, palace officials will want to be seen to be fair and reasonable
when dealing with the mother of Prince William and Prince Harry and a woman who
appears to command strong public support.
The princess's visit to Argentina will inevitably be seen as a test of her
future role.
The so-called charity visit was under intense media scrutiny as Diana
encountered isolated but insistent protests, notably over the Falklands.
Almost every time there was a warm welcome, minority protesters spoilt things
for the princess.
James Hewitt remained in the spotlight yesterday. The Sun newspaper quoted him
as saying it was the princess herself who first urged him to speak out after it
became clear their fling was going to be discovered.
q The princess is to launch a 15-month appeal to raise money for the charity
ChildLine.
Another charity, the Eating Disorders Association, which helps people suffering
from the eating disorder which plagued the Princess of Wales, yesterday
announced that it was getting #32,000 from the National Lottery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wall collapse boy could lose foot</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159418</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN eight-year-old boy may loose a foot after it was crushed in a wall collapse
- more than two years after neighbours first warned it was unsafe.
Lee MacMillan was out playing with a pal in Cranloch housing estate, Nairn,
when the wall fell on him, the impact from large concrete blocks from the 8ft
wall shattering bones and leaving a gaping wound in his left foot.
Doctors warned yesterday that, unless a difficult operation suc- ceeds, they
may have to amputate.
Paramedics took 15 minutes to free Lee from under the rubble before taking him
to Raigmore Hospital, Inverness, with his mother, Lynne.
Residents at Albyn Court, Nairn, where the accident took place, claim they have
been pressing owners, Albyn Housing, for more than two years to take action.
Ms MacMillan said yesterday: ``It is an absolute outrage this should happen to
my wee boy.''
``He is in a terrible condition and I am just praying he will not lose his
foot. He's such an active wee boy and loves playing football.
``I could not believe it when I heard yesterday the housing association had
deemed the wall safe. I believe they refused to take any action despite
warnings. Only now, after something serious like this, have they started
repairs.''
Ms MacMillan, of Seaforth Road, Nairn, added: ``I understand he is likely, at
the very least, to lose his big toe. There is also a real danger he will lose
his foot, especially if infection sets in.''
Mr Ronald Mackenzie, 72, of Albyn Court, who owns the house adjacent to the
collapsed wall, has led a campaign to have the wall repaired.
He said: ``The wall has been shakey for more than two years but, despite my
warnings, Albyn Housing have always maintained it is perfectly safe.
``The first time they came was more than two years ago now. I showed them
cracks in the wall but they said it was fine.''
No-one at Albyn Housing was available for comment yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plan for 6% ceiling. Forsyth to hold down new water charges</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159419</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
SCOTTISH Office Ministers have agreed to an even tougher than expected
crackdown on any increases in water charges to be levied by the three new
public authorities next year.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth is ready to step in and cap the rises at an
average of just 6%.
The new water authorities believed they might be allowed increases of up to 15%
before the Scottish Office intervened. They have not officially been told of
the Scottish Secretary's intentions.
Rises of around 6% would be slightly less than the average increases levied by
the regional councils over the last few years and would destroy Labour's
claims, at least for the time being, that removing the services from local
authority control would send charges soaring.
Yesterday Labour's local government spokesman, Mr John McAllion, was accusing
the Government of lying about the real cost of transferring water and sewerage
services from councils to the new quangos.
Mr McAllion said: ``Every step taken away from direct public control and
towards privatisation is a step which costs consumers dearly. That is the truth
which Scottish Office Ministers dare not own up to.''
Such a tight charging limit, however, will present the new water and sewerage
authorities with enormous problems.
The chairman of the West of Scotland Water Authority, Mr John Jameson, said it
would be ``very difficult'' to make savings of such an order in the authority's
first year of operation.
He said spending would have to rise by around 10% to 15% and it was hard to see
where cutbacks could come. The largest part of the increase was taken up by
paying interest on the capital debt and in paying rates to councils for the
installations inherited by the authority.
Mr Jameson said he believed the board would be very unhappy to see major
reductions in the capital spending programme which could place them in legal
difficulties over meeting deadlines for reaching new Government and European
Union standards.
Ministers are also anxious to encourage the new authorities to enter into
partnerships with the private sector over major new capital projects through
the Private Finance Initiative. The preferred method is through Build Own and
Operate (BOO) schemes.
However, Mr Jameson said no such projects were on the stocks in the Strathclyde
and Dumfries and Galloway area which his board covers and it would take at
least a year to get one set up.
No-one was available to comment at the East of Scotland Authority yesterday. It
is believed however that ESWA faces a serious lack of funding in its first year
and cannot call on any reserves. It is believed to need a rise of around 25% to
meet its requirements although it recognises this increase would not be
acceptable.
The charges proposed by the three new authorities should be known next month
when they will be submitted to the Scottish Water and Sewerage Consumers'
Council chaired by former Labour MP and now SNP member Dick Douglas.
If the Council, which acts as a public watchdog, cannot agree the level of
increases the matter passes to the Scottish Secretary.
</TEXT>
