<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why the Beeb must watch the watershed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Laing</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159420</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HERITAGE Secretary Virginia Bottomley has expressed concern about the BBC's
attitude to the evening watershed. She has made it clear that she is unhappy
about the way family viewing can suddenly become adult viewing at the stroke of
9pm, a time when many children are still watching television.
Instead she wants the corporation to make a slower switch after 9 o'clock, a
period of transition which would prevent youngsters from seeing scenes of sex
and violence.
Mrs Bottomley's opinion, which is aimed more at BBC2 since BBC1 has the Nine
o'Clock News ``buffer zone'' on weekdays, was expressed yesterday as she
announced her detailed proposals for the corporation's new charter. However,
fears that she was preparing to issue stringent and prohibitive new rules on
taste and decency proved to be largely unfounded.
Indeed the BBC management and, more to the point, its programme-makers broadly
welcomed the proposals which, in effect, amounted to a massive vote of
confidence in the corporation.
Broadcasters seemed to accept the more controversial aspects of Mrs Bottomley's
draft. Among the main principles in the Government's proposals for a new
Charter and Agreement will be ``clarification of the BBC's responsibilities for
impartiality and for taste and decency''.
This clause is part of a list of ``basic programme standards'' which merely
places the corporation under the same obligations as its counterparts in the
commercial sector. Until now the BBC has been subject to a voluntary code of
practice; now it will be formally incorporated into the agreement.
Mrs Bottomley also proposes a more explicit role for the Board of Governors
which would ensure that ``the BBC meets its obligations and commitments to
licence-fee payers''. This would include overseeing strategy, supervising on
matters of programme standard and impartiality, ensuring the proper handling of
complaints, and appointing senior staff.
There would also be a requirement for the BBC to publish a ``Statement of
Pledges'' outlining the objectives and the standards which viewers could
expect. It would also be obliged to report on performance and achievement. All
of these things the BBC already does (usually through its annual report) but,
again, these proposals formalise the requirements.
Important to Scotland is a clause which lays down a concrete commitment to
regional broadcasting by providing a greater role for programme makers
throughout the country. There will also be specific responsibilities laid down
for the National Broadcasting Councils for Scotland, Wales, and Northern
Ireland. Behind this is the growing awareness that the BBC has been too
centralised - and unable to look beyond London and the Home Counties.
Once again, Mrs Bottomley is making formal a process which the BBC has been
doing in recent years with its increasing commitment to both regional and
network programmes.
Much more significant, however, is that for the first time the Board of
Governors will be required to consult the National Broadcasting Council for
Scotland on matters of programme objectives, the allocation of funding, and any
proposals which would have a significant effect on BBC Scotland's resource
base. A senior official at BBC Scotland described the proposal as a ``step
forward'' because it gave the council a much more defined role.
Mrs Bottomley also confirmed yesterday that the BBC's transmission services
would be privatised, with the revenue from the sale being returned to the
corporation for re-investment in new digital production technology.
Commenting on the draft Charter and Agreement, she said: ``The BBC is a
national jewel. It is internationally recognised as the leading broadcaster in
the world. The BBC has a justifiable reputation for making quality programmes.
``The draft Charter and Agreement demonstrates the Government's commitment to
building on the BBC's proud tradition of public service broadcasting, while
freeing it to meet the challenges of the multi-media, digital future.
``The new charter will make the BBC more clearly accountable to licence-fee
payers. There should be dialogue, understanding, and accountability between the
BBC and its audiences.''
She pledged that the corporation's independence was enshrined within the new
agreement but editorial independence required editorial responsibility. Viewers
expected information and stimulating debate.
``They have the right to expect that the assumptions and motives of all those
who enter the arena of political debate will be challenged and questioned in a
sensible, constructive way. The new Charter and Agreement provides a framework
for this to be achieved,'' she added.
BBC Chairman Marmaduke Hussey welcomed the Heritage Secretary's draft
proposals. ``We are delighted that the all-party support given to the BBC when
the White Paper was published last year is fully reflected in these new
documents. This vote of confidence in the BBC, and those who work for it at all
levels, represents the fruits of many years' labour to prepare the corporation
for the challenges of the next century,'' he said.
The draft Charter and Agreement will now face its passage through the Commons
and the Lords. The current BBC charter runs out at the end of next year.
Allan Laing reports on the Government's scrutiny of the BBC's standards
</TEXT>
