<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Whisky association backs Spain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159421</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEARING an erosion of standards across the European drinks industry, the Scotch
Whisky Association has thrown its support behind a Spanish complaint against
English brandy made from cider.
The association set out its views in response to a Ministry of Agriculture
inquiry, asking whether ``cider brandy'' was a recognised term within the
drinks industry. The UK is examining the issue in response to a Spanish
complaint to the European Commission about Somerset Cider Brandy Company's use
of the word ``brandy'' to describe distilled cider.
Julian Temperley, the managing director of the small six-year-old company,
called the whisky association's response ``bad policy, incompetent and
treacherous.''
``We are somewhat surprised and hurt to be attacked by people who are supposed
to be our colleagues,'' Mr Temperley said. ``It doesn't do anybody any
favours.''
Campbell Evans of the Scotch Whisky Association said his group was not
interested in changing the regulations, merely clarifying them. He said the
association was concerned that the ``knock-on'' effects of widening the
definition of brandy would set a damaging precedent for whisky.
``We fight all over the world against passing off spirits which do not meet the
definition of whisky as being such,'' Mr Evans said. ``If exceptions are
allowed in one area, they can spill over into other areas - like Scotch
whisky.''
The Scotch Whisky Association outlined its position to the Ministry of
Agriculture in a letter dated November 10. Part of that letter, which was
obtained by Somerset Cider Brandy, reads as follows:
``Spanish spirits producers have long objected to the use of the term `brandy'
for a product which is not wine-based. We understand that, initially, it was
only the English (mis)translation of (European Union) Regulation 1576/89 which
caused them problems.
``Since brandy is defined by Regulation 1576/89 (and is understood by consumers
worldwide) as being a spirit drink distilled from wine spirit, the terms
`cherry brandy liqueur,' `cider brandy' and `grain brandy' are contradictory
and misleading. We would definitely not wish to see the term `whisky' used on
spirits produced from raw materials other than cereals.''
Mr Temperley said this rationale did not make sense because European Commission
definitions did not exclude wines made from fruits other than grapes. If wine
can be made from apples, then cider brandy is a legitimate label for distilled
apple juice, he argued.
``If whisky was produced from one type of grain maybe you could support the
Spanish,'' Mr Temperley said in a letter to the whisky association, ``but by
allowing the production from any cereal can only support our case that brandy
can be produced from any fruit.''
The dispute comes up for the European Commission's consideration in January.
Mr Temperley said he expected strong support from French producers of Calvados,
another spirit made from apples.
</TEXT>
