<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Old Bailey judge shows leniency to single mother indulging `selfish wish' Woman who left baby to die is freed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159422</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER whose six-month-old daughter died when she was left in a flat alone
for 30 hours without food or water was allowed to walk free from the Old Bailey
yesterday.
Single mother Antoinette Campbell, 23, was indulging her selfish wish ``for a
bit of freedom'' when she left her baby, Desrae, to spend time with her
boyfriend.
However, the court heard how doctors could not agree on the cause of the baby's
death and how she could have fallen victim to cot-death syndrome within hours
of being left.
Campbell was put on probation for three years on condition she lives at a bail
hostel and attends a probation centre.
The judge told her: ``This is an opportunity the court will not be able to
repeat but it's an opportunity you need now and which the court wishes you to
have now, so I hope there will be no need for you to come before a court ever
again.''
He said it was clear from numerous reports that people wanted to help Campbell,
and the court wanted to help her too.
Campbell had admitted child cruelty at an earlier hearing and had been remanded
for reports.
Her plea of not guilty to the manslaughter of her baby was accepted by the
Crown after Mr Mark Dennis, prosecuting, said doctors could not agree on the
cause of death.
Although a pathologist had found signs of dehydration and starvation, two
paediatricians disagreed that these factors were the cause of death.
They decided the baby girl had died only a few hours after her mother had
abandoned her at her newly-acquired council flat in Kilburn, north-west London,
either from cot death syndrome or a metabolic disorder.
Mr Dennis said it was impossible to quantify how much the stress of abandonment
had had on these natural causes of death.
He told the court that, before the incident in January this year, Campbell had
complained to her mother that she felt lifeless.
She asked her mother to look after the baby for a couple of hours. On several
occasions, she returned much later than arranged, telling her mother ``it feels
good, it's some freedom''.
``In other words, without the child,'' added Mr Dennis.
When the baby died, Campbell left her early on Friday evening and went to visit
her boyfriend, the baby's father.
She pretended to him and his family that her mother was looking after Desrae.
Campbell stayed the night and did not return to her own home until late on
Saturday night.
Mr Dennis said that, while Campbell was at her boyfriend's home, she appeared
perfectly normal and not at all distressed.
She stayed all the next day but then she said she missed her baby and wanted to
pick her up from her mother's. En route, she called at a friend's and did not
get home until late on Saturday night. She found Desrae dead.
Campbell left the baby's body wrapped in a shawl and went to her mother's house
without revealing what had happened.
The baby was found by her father, who became concerned at a phone call he had
received and climbed into the flat.
Campbell appeared later accompanied by counsellors from the Samaritans, whom
she had contacted, and a doctor.
Campbell admitted to police she had abandoned her baby. She said she had only
intended to stay for a while at her boyfriend's because he had complained in
the past about her bringing the child and not getting a babysitter.
She had not left Desrae with her mother because she did not want her to think
she was ``taking liberties''.
``When she (Desrae) wasn't there, it was providing her with a bit of freedom, a
bit of space, a bit of thinking time. She admits it was no excuse and that she
was being selfish in all she has done,'' Mr Jeremy Dein, defending, told the
court.
</TEXT>
