<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Canadian leader woos Quebec</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>FOREIGN DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975159423</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Canadian leader
woos Quebec
OTTAWA: Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien yesterday announced three
measures to try to mollify Quebec separatists, including a parliamentary
resolution recogizing that Quebec is a distinct society.
But the resolution fell short of demands of the separatists and proposals by
Chretien's own Liberal colleagues in Quebec for insertion of a clause on a
distinct society in the constitution.
Tamil appeal
COLOMBO: The leader of Sri Lanka's Tamil rebels admitted yesterday the army
might take his stronghold of Jaffna but said the door to peace would be closed
so long as troops occupied the town. He appealed for fresh recruits to join his
guerrilla forces as the military blasted through the town's booby-trapped maze
of streets with tanks.
Taking over
PARIS: Algeria's newly-elected president Liamine Zeroual was sworn in yesterday
and urged all political groups in the fractured country to engage in dialogue
and respect the law. But, in a much anticipated speech, he avoided committing
himself to negotiations with Muslim militants fighting the government or to
specific dates for parlimentary elections.
Nastase move
BUCHAREST: Former tennis star Ilie Nastase entered has entered a new ball game,
politics, becoming a leading member of Romania's ruling party. Nastase, 49, the
world's No 1 player in 1973, has been elected to the national council of the
centre-left Social Democracy Party, said party spokesman Ilie Petrescu in
Bucharest.
Fraud retrial
BERNE: A Swiss court yesterday completed a posthumous retrial of a police chief
convicted of fraud in 1940 for helping Jews fleeing the Nazis and said a
verdict would be announced on Thursday. Former Jewish refugees who attended the
hearing said they were confident a sentence on Paul Grueninger, who died in
1972 aged 80, for falsifying entry documents would be cancelled and that he
would be fully rehabilitated.
Green look
COPENHAGEN: Danes packed a provincial museum to glimpse a 10-week-old kitten
born with fluorescent green fur, apparently from a genetic defect. Newspapers
carried pictures of the cat's owner, Kristinne Bischoff, five, holding her pet,
Miss Greeny, during an appearance at Aarhus Natural History Museum, on the
Jutland peninsula. Investigators appear convinced that the cat's fur is not
dyed and are analysing blood samples to find the genetic reasons for its colour.
Market inferno
DHAKA: Soldiers were called in to help firemen put out a devastating fire that
destroyed nearly 2500 shops yesterday in one of Dhaka's largest markets.
Witnesses said hundreds of soldiers joined the fight after Bangladesh Prime
Minister Begum Khaleda Zia and opposition leader Sheikh Hasina visited the fire
scene.
Good spirits
SINGAPORE: Former Barings Bank trader Nick Leeson appeared in good spirits in
his maximum security prison in Singapore yesterday, his lawyer told reporters.
``He seemed cheerful,'' lawyer John Koh said, emerging from Tanah Merah prison
after spending nearly an hour inside. His next court appearance is on Friday.
</TEXT>
