<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fixture dates may solve club or district dilemma.  SRU to meet Accies over Sole outburst</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Derek Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159424</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE former Scotland captain David Sole is to appear before the Murrayfield
authorities tomorrow as the investigation continues into his comments after
Edinburgh Academicals' premiership clash with Melrose when he was reported to
have declared that the performance of referee Colin Henderson had been
``tantamount to cheating.''
Academicals' coach Sole was upset by a string of penalty awards against his
side - subsequently relegated to Division II - who were beaten in the final
minute and, at the time, plunged deeper into the relegation mire by the defeat.
Yesterday, Academicals' media spokesman Magnus Moodie said: ``The delicate
balance between freedom of speech and maintaining the rugby ethic will be put
to the test on Wednesday when David Sole, president Charlie Jackson, and Ken
Lauder will have a meeting with the SRU on the subject of David's comments. The
invitation to the meeting was very friendly and sympathetic to our recent
difficulties.''
SRU chief executive Bill Hogg said yesterday: ``We have been in discussion with
Academicals about the reported comments by David Sole and we want to discuss
the matter with them personally rather than conduct a correspondence.''
Hogg, who said at the time of the incident that any action taken against Sole
would be handled under the catch-all ``bringing the game into disrepute,''
declared yesterday that the sanctions available to the union were the same as
those when a player was involved.
q THE SRU expect to be a step nearer making the crucial decision on whether
club or district sides represent Scotland in the European Cup next season after
a meeting in Dublin today, when the organisers will hammer out fixture dates
for the 20-team tournament.
The inaugural championship, involving 16 sides from Wales, Ireland, France,
Italy and Romania - but not England or Scotland - is currently under way.
Ireland are represented by provincial sides and current thinking at Murrayfield
is that Scotland should follow suit, either with recognised districts or with
hybrid sides comprising the best players available.
The clubs versus districts issue is potentially divisive, with some of the top
clubs determined that they, and not districts, should fly the Saltire in Europe.
Yesterday, at a Murrayfield media briefing, SRU chief executive Bill Hogg said
that discussions were ongoing with the Premier League Clubs Association, but
only after the format of the tournament was known would it be possible to
resolve the issue.
``We hope that a consensus will emerge. The alternatives will be put to the
clubs. Ultimately the SRU committee will decide but, hopefully, that decision
can be reached in agreement with the clubs,'' he said.
Hogg added that the ideal scenario would be to play the club championship, then
the European ties - which the SRU hope will be at weekends and not midweek, as
they are just now - and then move on to the Five Nations' tournament. The hope
was that the inter-district championship could still be fitted into the
equation.
The situation is further complicated because of ongoing discussion about the
premiership format next season. The possibility of 10-team divisions is still
being discussed but, said Hogg, if the premiership divisions were increased
from eight to 18 clubs, then there was ``no way'' that the inter-district
championship and the European ties could be fitted in.
q FINAL decisions on the contract issued to the international squad now await
the outcome of legal advice sought by the players. The SRU said yesterday that
there were now no unresolved issues of principle, so far as they were
concerned. The chief executive said that it was not the intention to make
public the value of the contract - which other sources put at a maximum of
around #22,500 for the season - as it was a private matter between the union
and the players.
q THE SRU is not insisting that premiership fixtures which have no bearing on
the title chase or relegation should be played on December 9 and 16. Hogg said
yesterday that the Gala v Heriot's FP fixture did not need to be played on
December 9 and the Union was recommending to the clubs that the Heriot's FP v
Stirling County game, which does have a bearing on the championship, should be
played on December 9 rather than a week later as currently scheduled.
q PROFESSOR Michael Garraway, of Edinburgh University, is to receive #16,000
funding from the SRU for further research into injuries suffered by players.
His initial investigation into the causes and outcome of rugby injuries in the
South of Scotland will be followed up.
q THE Scottish Claymores gridiron side will no longer use Murrayfield for
training. Their decision means a revenue loss of some #10,000 to the SRU.
</TEXT>
