<HEADLINE>Armstrong agrees terms for January move to Newcastle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159425</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GARY Armstrong, who makes a guest appearance for Newcastle-Gosforth tonight as
the Tynesiders entertain the Transvaal provincial side from South Africa, has
agreed a financial deal with Sir John Hall's super-club, and expects to make a
permanent move in January.
Armstrong, capped 30 times, and fellow Borderer Doddie Weir have been involved
in negotiations with Sir John and Newcastle's rugby director Rob Andrew for
some time.
The Scottish guest will play in the second half at Newcastle tonight.
Yesterday, Armstrong declared: ``I've now agreed the cash side of the deal.
There are other bits and pieces to sort out, and the contract is with my
lawyer, but, if there are no last-minute hitches, then I don't envisage any
problems.''
The Jed-Forest, Scotland, and British Lions scrum half was initially offered
around #150,000, plus fringe benefits, for a three-year deal. He declined to
say yesterday whether negotiations had led to an increase in cash.
``The contract will be for three years and four games. Rob wants us down in
January so that we can play in the final four league games. It's crucial, of
course, that Newcastle remain in Division II.
``Everything that I have seen at Newcastle has impressed me. Their facilities
are fantastic, and both Rob Andrew and Sir John have great vision for the
future. They want to make Newcastle the biggest club in the country and they
are determined that we will play in Europe,'' he said.
The Jedburgh lorry driver added: ``Of course, it will be a wrench to leave
Jed-Forest, but I won't have to leave the town, and the club have said that I
go with their blessing. Of course it's a gamble, but it's a gamble that I'm
willing to take. I really couldn't walk away from what they are offering me.
``They have said that they will train me as a sales rep if I want to. The club
has a link with Scottish and Newcastle Brewers through the football club, but I
don't know yet whether I'll take them up on that. Maybe, I should just
concentrate on the rugby initially.''
Weir, who will not play today for Newcastle because of Melrose's crunch
premiership match with Gala on Saturday, added: ``I'm in much the same position
as Gary. The contract is with the lawyer and I have to speak to my boss here at
Carlsberg-Tetley, because I would like to keep on my job as a sales rep in the
Borders.
``There are still things like that to sort out but if all goes to plan, then I
expect to be at Newcastle next year as well.''
q.A GARY Armstrong try gave South, under the guise of the Edinburgh Borderers,
a 5-3 half-time lead over the home club in an exhibition match to mark the
switching on the new Peebles RFC floodlights last night.
Two tries from Hawick winger Keith Suddon, and one from Graeme Aitchison, took
the South clear in the second half. Kelso full back Aitchison added two
conversions as South won 24-3, Peebles stand-off Rab Wilson having kicked his
side's only points in the first half.
</TEXT>
