<HEADLINE>Applicant for asylum wins #3000 after detention</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159426</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BANGLADESHI Hindu seeking political asylum in Scotland has won damages from
the Home Office in what is thought to be the first successful legal challenge
of its kind.
Mr Bizan Bhattacharjee, who is living in Fort William, won #3000 for being
wrongly detained after he had been arrested for breaching bail restrictions.
The settlement has been agreed out of court and will be rubber-stamped at the
Court of Session on Thursday when the case is concluded formally. The Home
Office does not accept liability.
Lawyers acting for Mr Bhattacharjee said it was believed to be the first
successful claim in Scotland against the Home Office under the 1971 Immigration
Act. Only a handful of actions are thought to have been successful south of the
Border.
Mr Bhattacharjee, 36, said he was relieved at the result and now hoped his
application for asylum would be accepted so that he could start a new life in
Fort William.
The single man arrived in the UK four years ago after facing persecution from
the majority Muslim population in Bangladesh. He also claims his father was
killed by extremists in the country.
He was detained on his arrival into the UK but granted bail while his case was
investigated. An immigration adjudicator said he had to remain at a London
address and pay a surety of #2000.
After an argument with one friend in London, Mr Bhattacharjee looked up another
contact in Fort William and began working in a restaurant there. He was aware
he had breached bail conditions but felt he had no alternative.
In January this year, he was arrested by police and immigration officers and
taken first to Fort William police cells then to Greenock Prison. The
authorities failed to bring him before an adjudicator within the stipulated 24
hours, waiting five days before a hearing went ahead.
He was sent back to Greenock for a month before being granted interim
liberation, pending a decision on his asylum application.
His lawyer, Mr Dilip Deb, explained that the #3000 damages was for the extra
period he spent in prison awaiting a hearing before an adjudicator.
Mr Deb said: ``Greenock is an ordinary prison where my client was locked up for
most of the day and then forced to mix with other inmates, criminals, and
people awaiting trial. He had to wear prison clothes and eat Western food.
``It is unusual for the Home Office to detain someone illegally and that makes
this an even more important result.''
Mr Deb said his client had been made a fair offer which he would accept.
Mr Bhattacharjee said his first days behind bars had been the most frightening.
He said: ``I was very upset when I was taken away from the restaurant in
handcuffs but prison was frightening. I felt as if I was being treated like a
murderer.
``I have never been in prison in my life and I was constantly afraid. I
suffered verbal abuse and once someone tried to grab a chain from around my
neck.
``It was God's blessing that I was released from jail. I love this country and
now I want to stay. I hope the Government will grant me asylum. I have forgiven
and forgotten those involved in my prison ordeal.''
Mr Deb said his client's application for asylum should be dealt with in the
coming months.
A spokeswoman for the Home Office said: ``We are not accepting liability. It
was an out-of-court settlement and we believe it represents the best public
interest.'' It is understood the Home Office was not prepared to spend public
money on a costly trial.
Greenock's governor, Mr Damiel Gunn, said it was not mandatory for untried
prisoners to wear prison clothing. He added that everything was done to meet
the needs of inmates detained under immigration legislation. Greenock is the
main holding centre used by immigration authorities in Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lord Provost warms to link with Benidorm</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159427</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORGET the arithmetic. Glasgow may already have three twin cities but it won't
deter the city from adding a fourth - Benidorm.
The twinning was proposed yesterday by the Mayor of Benidorm, Mr Vicente
Perez-Devesa, at a private meeting with Glasgow Lord Provost Tommy Dingwall.
Mr Perez-Devesa was in the city on the first leg of a glad-handing visit which
will take him to Edinburgh today, and Newcastle tomorrow, to bang the drum for
what is already Spain's number one holiday destination.
When it was first mooted that he should meet the lord provost, Mr Perez-Devesa
was told that a full diary precluded such an encounter.
However, it appears that Mr Dingwall is an aficionado of Spain. So much so that
yesterday's meeting at the City Chambers which had been scheduled for 15
minutes ran over to 90 and saw the lord provost tie a tartan tie round the
mayor's neck. It would appear that the idea of twinning Glasgow with the costas
was not simply a Spanish notion.
One of the six strong Spanish delegation, Mr Juan Ruiz, director of tourism in
Benidorm, said that they had just beaten Mr Dingwall to the punch.
Glasgow already has three twin cities - Nuremberg in Germany, Dalian in China,
and Rostov-on-Don in Russia, while Benidorm has a similar hat trick of Bad Ems
in Germany, Vina del Mar in Chile, and Le Cannet in France. But this it appears
will not stop the cities from adding a fourth. Through an interpreter Mr
Perez-Devesa told The Herald: ``For twinning to be a good idea there has to be
a contrast.''
And what better contrast could he hope for than Glasgow, where the sun mainly
shines from Mr Happy's mouth, and the city where it shines constantly from the
skies. The idea mooted is just that. Mr Perez-Devesa said he had been assured
that Mr Dingwall would take it further - once certain Glasgow District Council
officials had returned from an unconnected trip to Spain. He said that Benidorm
was in confident mood after the success of this summer's season. ``Although the
industry is predicting that next year will be a difficult one we are looking to
maintain our market share and attract about 100,000 visitors from Scotland.''
To maintain its number one position the resort has spent more than #20m
improving facilities and upgrading hotels rather than allowing new ones to be
built. With the completion of the 52-storey Hotel Bali in 1997 (which will
become Spain's tallest building) no new hotels are being built.
While he found Mr Dingwall to be a fervent admirer of Spain, the mayor saw
nothing wrong with the idea of Spaniards coming to Scotland for a holiday.
``Many Spaniards go on ski-ing holidays to the Pyrenees so I don't see why they
should not come to Scotland.''
He had, however, one complaint about our November weather. Too cold? No, just
the opposite. It appears that the Spanish delegation had come to Scotland
burdened with heavy jumpers and heavy boots in anticipation of the cold weather.
``We had been looking forward to it,'' said the mayor.
However, it would seem that frosty receptions are a thing of the past in
Scotland as far as the Spanish are concerned.
</TEXT>
