<DOCNO>GH951128-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Single currency.  Chancellor sets perfect tone</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159428</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor of the Exchequer's approach to Europe and to the planned
introduction of a single European currency is finely judged and entirely
sustainable. He is determined to keep Britain's options open, which means
refusing to rule out the possibility of taking part in a single currency if it
is to Britain's advantage. Similarly, he manages to ensure that the
negotiations on a single currency are not allowed to prejudice Britain's
interests through sins of omission or commission on the part of our more
enthusiastic European partners.This is an interesting balancing act and one
which must always take into account the views of the Tory backwoodsmen, ever
ready to seek out signs of weakness on the Government's part or malevolence on
the part of the Europeans.  Such an issue surfaced yesterday in the form of the
first chance to discuss seriously the German proposal to penalise those nations
which take part in a single currency and then allow their inflation rates and
budget deficits to get out of control.  At first glance this is a subject
tailor-made  for the frothing tendency in the ranks of the Eurosceptics.  It
smacks of German arrogance (how dare they suggest fining other nations) and of
European designs on national sovereignty (the commission is believed to favour
it).
There is, of course, a quite different agenda involved in all of this.
Public
opinion in Germany is not wholly enthusiastic on the subject of a single
currency, not because its theoretical advantages are doubted but rather because
Germans fear that the bad habits and weak currencies of other nations might
drag down their own economy.  In an attempt to bolster flagging public support
the German Finance Minister, Mr Theo Waigel, proposed a "stability pact" for
enforcing budgetary discipline among member states taking part in monetary
union. The idea has been well-received in Germany for the obvious and intended
reasons, but it has also found support in other European countries.  At one
level it is one of those "good things" which it is difficult to argue against;
after all, what could be wrong with budgetary discipline?  Mr Clarke is aware
of this but has thankfully avoided the temptation to indulge in a little ersatz
indignation.  He dismissed the subject lightly by saying that it does not
constitute much of a threat to British sovereignty, which is true, and that in
any case Britain is set on an economic course which would not incur penalties.
The last point remains to be proved but the tone set by the Chancellor was
perfect.
More serious is the reminder from yesterday's meeting of Finance Ministers
that the Madrid Euro summit is next month and at that meeting the Prime
Minister will come face-to-face with the subject of the single currency. This
will give objectors on the Tory back benches ample opportunity to scrutinise Mr
Major's Eurosceptic credentials.  He may feel the hot breath of the
anti-European extremists on his neck, but he can hardly forget that the biggest
survey of British business opinion ever taken on the subject of the single
currency found solid support, either for participation or for maintaining the
option to join.  In any sensible world the opinion of British businessmen
should outweigh the opinion of the extremists, but Mr Major does not inhabit a
sensible world; he is the leader of the Tory Party.  The role model which he
should adopt is that of his Chancellor.  Yes, it is a balancing act, but it is
also pragmatic and leans to the positive side.  If Mr Major truly puts nation
above party next month he will do the same.
</TEXT>
