<HEADLINE>Proof of a fair cop</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Douglas Thompson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159429</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Author Raymond Chandler, with his wisecracking cop Philip Marlowe, has joined
America's giants of literature. Douglas Thompson investigates the man and his
lethal .38 epigrams
She had a lot of face and chin. She had pewter-coloured hair set in a ruthless
permanent, a hard beak and large moist eyes with the sympathetic expression of
wet stones. There was lace at her throat, but it was the kind of throat that
would have looked better in a football sweater.
- from The High Window.
RAYMOND CHANDLER, the loner's laureate, believed style was the best investment
a writer could make for posterity. He elevated himself from pulp fiction to use
the genre for his own artistic ends.
His work, just seven novels and a handful of short stories and screenplays, was
in a voice-over world of cool blondes and stiff whisky and vice versa. The
spiritual and emotional questions of his times he tackled on the streets.
To walk them he created his tarnished knight, Philip Marlowe, who used
wisecracks as a shield to - among other ``weaknesses'' - disguise his soft spot
for making other people's troubles his own. Marlowe was no brain-boiler like
Sherlock Holmes or cavalier James-Bond type. He was first named Mallory - a nod
to Le Morte d'Arthur - and Chandler saw him as sensitive and strong: ``He is
slightly over six feet tall and weighs about 13 stone eight. He has dark brown
hair, brown eyes, and the expression `passably good looking' would not satisfy
him in the least. He can be tough.
``Almost any sort of cigarette will satisfy him. He will drink practically
anything that is not sweet. Certain drinks, such as Pink Ladies, Honolulu
cocktails, and creme de menthe highballs, he would regard as an insult.
``He is a late riser by inclination, but occasionally an early riser by
necessity. He has not, and never has had, a secretary.
``He started out with a Luger automatic pistol. He seems to have had Colt
automatics of various calibres but not larger than a .38 and when I last heard
he had a Smith and Wesson .38 special.''
Here we had the private eye and public conscience.
``Cops are just people,'' she said. ``They start out that way I've heard.''
Chandler thought Cary Grant would be perfect to play his ``shop-soiled
Galahad'' in the movies.
It seems that everybody but Grant has but it was Bogart in The Big Sleep who
pulled that trench coat belt tight and put a patent on the image.
The bespectacled, pipe-smoking Chandler, meek, shy, and uncertain, provided the
poetry with five o'clock shadow, the arsenic idealism. His was unique material
which he also developed in screenplays for Billy Wilder (the classic Double
Indemnity) and Hitchcock (Strangers on a Train) but under financial duress.
His view of Hollywood was this: ``The making of motion pictures is an endless
contention of tawdry egos, almost none of them capable of anything more
creative than credit stealing and self promotion.''
Chandler was no self-publicist. He was reluctant even to release photographs of
himself, afraid that readers expecting a macho-man author might be put off by
his owlish look. He made no public appearances. Cinema's infant, television,
held no attraction for him (a Philip Marlowe series ran one season in 1959, the
year of his death) and he stayed at home. He spent his time drinking. And
writing. But letters as well as detective novels. The price of a stamp could
entice a few thousand words of Chandler in reply.
His letters make as fascinating reading as his ``work''. Now, more than a
century after his birth in Chicago in December, 1888, they have been gathered
along with the out-of-print screenplay of Double Indemnity and his novels and
short stories into two volumes.
Yes, many authors have been ``collected''. But not by the Library of America,
which is the resting place for the nation's giants of literature. It's a sort
of Booker Prize-type of tomb. You don't have to be read to get there.
Chandler is not only the first detective writer to be inaugurated but the first
pop-star wordsmith. The only other practitioner holding vaguely his view of the
world on the library's list is Edgar Allan Poe. The two Chandler volumes (2275
pages, $35 each, Library of America) don't take up much space on the shelf but
they are gems in the hands. Every page has some magic. The Library of America
volumes - they are modelled on the portable French Pleiades editions - take
Chandler's oeuvre, the work of a man who prided himself on being an inside
outsider, into the Establishment.
Style eventually delivered posterity in spades.
And you must spin a coin in the air about whether quality or influence are the
most important. Chandler has - apart from Hemingway - inspired more parodies
than any writer this century. He's also been a posthumous mentor to novelists
and film-makers from the worldwide film-noir crowd to Tarantino.
He's a novel in himself. His mother took him to England after her divorce. He
went to Dulwich College (as did P G Wodehouse) and it was all Greek and Latin
for him. After the First World War he returned to America, California and the
oil business. He went on booze binges and watched the shady deals going on.
He was on his way to the executive suite when his mother died and he met Cissy
Pascal. He was so obsessed with her that he didn't realise - or care - that she
was 17 years older when they married.
Love trapped him. Her health failed and in a string of lonely houses throughout
southern California he made the tea for her and a strong drink for himself. He
would take her for drives. For four hours a day he would shut himself up and
write. He never plotted - it shows - and for every 30,000 words he would edit
down to about one-sixth of that. He wrote about something he knew - Los Angeles.
The fiction was Marlowe or the men like him. When he was stuck he said his way
out was always to have a man come through a door with a gun in his hand.
There was a small knocking on wood. It was a blonde. A blonde to make a bishop
kick a hole in a stained-glass window.
Chandler had been amused at the antics of middle-class snobs in England, while
at the same time delighting in British eccentricity. When he returned to
America he felt socially superior. He didn't play on that but he did on his
intellectual arrogance. It was power, but he had no self-confidence that he
could be a writer and that ``saved'' him from the literary treadmill.
Writing detective stories were Erle Stanley Gardner and Dashiel Hammett, while
Hemingway and Scott Fitzgerald were dazzling readers.
Chandler decided to take them all on.
He wrote his own rules, including the harnessing of your language to a
descriptive style that could be understood by a boy of 14 and appreciated by a
emeritus professor who revered the merits of clear, immaculately punctuated
English. It was a lonely struggle. His marriage, Cissy, ruled his life. His
escape was the typewriter and the bottle. As his wife lay slowly wasting away
in the next room he worked handicapped by the taxman's demands and his doubts
about his talent. He sipped and gulped his drinks and tapped away.
Fitzgerald died by the bottle. Hemingway blew his brains out. Chandler kept
writing. He never shot anyone - even himself. He botched his suicide attempt.
Cissy died in 1954 and Chandler might as well have gone with her. He survived
another five years but they were maudlin months and his work efforts were
despairing.
Unlike all the jet-setting authors of today who ``do'' research, Chandler just
wrote about what he knew - California and the money and excess he'd witnessed
in the oil business, the complications and compulsions wealth can bring even,
or maybe especially, in the sunshine. To Hollywood he imported foreign
substances with him from Europe - irony and morality. He used the simile like a
sword. Nothing was itself. Everything was like something else.
She smelled the way the Taj Mahal looked by midnight.
The Library of America titles would have irked Chandler. They are: Raymond
Chandler: Stories and Early Novels and Raymond Chandler: Later Novels and Other
Writings.
He got annoyed at those who refused to believe that the private-eye/detective
genre has both craft and style.
``A writer who hates the actual writing, who gets no joy out of the creation of
magic by words, to me is simply not a writer at all.
``The actual writing is what you live for. The rest is something you have to
get through in order to arrive at the point. How can you hate the actual
writing? How can you hate the magic which makes up a paragraph or a sentence or
a line of dialogue or a description of something in the nature of a new
creation?''
Strangely, his decades-ago world of Los Angeles doesn't seem, to me, that
different from today. It's populated by missing persons, runaways, gigolos,
snoops, remote-control punks, gold diggers, and ``the kind of lawyers you hope
the other fellow has''. Chandler wrote about abortionists, Dr Feelgoods, gurus,
and porn merchants before other writers - or most people including the police -
knew they existed. Marlowe really did walk ``mean streets''.
Chandler's insight provided a university of writing. But for all the telling
novels it is in his letters - his thoughts on paper - in these landmark
editions that you find the man who hated critics, despised Hollywood, suspected
Jews, adored his wife, and loved his cat.
He writes on everything.
On Hemingway: ``Hemingway, with his eternal sleeping bag, got to be pretty damn
tiresome but at least Hemingway sees it all, not just the flies in the garbage
can.''
Scott Fitzgerald: ``Nothing but the best will do for him. I think he just
missed being a great writer and the reason is pretty obvious. If the poor guy
was already an alcoholic in his college days, it's a marvel that he did as well
as he did.''
Sir Arthur Conan Doyle: ``Found a two-bit edition of Hound of the Baskervilles.
God, what tripe. It looks to me as if Lincoln was wrong. You can fool all of
the people all of the time.''
On the English: ``There is a touch of aggressiveness about the working classes
and the non-public school types which I think is something new and which I
personally do not find all that unpleasant. The real public school types, or
many of them, with their bird-like chirpings, are becoming a little
ridiculous.''
On women: ``I find it impossible to respect a woman who lives with a man. She
can sleep with him all she blame pleases and with whomever else she pleases and
in whatever place she pleases but the tawdry imitation of domesticity gets me
down.''
On himself: ``I am standoffish with strangers, a form of shyness which whisky
cured when I was still able to take it in the requisite quantities. I am
terribly blunt, having been raised in that English tradition which permits a
gentleman to be almost infinitely rude if he keeps his voice down.''
They call it Chandleresque. Or Chandler-style. That's when other people do it.
But no-one plugged the famous or the Establishment with such lethal .38
epigrams as the real Raymond Chandler who now has been officially recognised as
a literary giant.
She gave me a smile I could feel in my hip pocket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
