<HEADLINE>MP with designs on changing the face of Westminster</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975159430</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``WHY don't we pull the whole wretched thing down and start again?'' stormed Mr
Tony Banks (Newham North-West - Lab.). Had Tony been a Byzantine MP, say for
Trebizond West, in the eighth century, he would have been a big man in the
Iconoclastic Party.
He was referring to the Mother of Parliaments, which he cheekily though not
wholly erroneously described as ``a cross between a gentlemen's club and a
public school''.
Down with it even unto the ground, he foamed, like a latter day Cato. Mr Tony
Newton, Leader of the House, defended the work of Sir Charles Barry and
Augustus Pugin as a fine building - which indeed it is - which deserved to stay
put.
It is hardly the fault of these eminent Victorians and the architects who
restored the bombed-out Commons in their image if it is sometimes the scene of
``banal questions and pathetic answers,'' as Mr Banks contemptuously dismissed
events up until his eruption.
A compliment from Transport Minister Steven Norris on his attire - a natty
black suit and shirt which, in the Sketch's opinion, made him look like a small
but deadly Mafia hitman - had failed to sweeten his jaundiced view.
One facility which Sir Charles and Augustus omitted to provide for their
stately creation was toilets for the disabled. There were, of course, plenty of
disabled people around in the nineteenth century, but they were not then in the
habit of mounting mass lobbies of parliament.
The disabled are treated better these days and, if they come to lobby to be
treated even better, access to a cup of tea and a lavatory is the least they
should expect. So argued several Labour MPs anyway.
Mr Alan Beith (Berwick - Lib. Dem.), whose good tempered and well-informed
replies to questions addressed to him as chairman of the House of Commons
Commission which runs the building, shows what we have lost through his party's
inability to form or even take part in an administration for half-a-century.
While the Palace looks magnificent there is less vacant space inside than one
might imagine, and it appeared that a cafeteria for visitors, disabled or
otherwise, in Westminster Hall only could be provided by flinging out the staff
who currently use it. Temporary disabled toilets too look likely to be almost
permanent for the foreseeable future.
Sir Peter Viggers (Gosport - Con.) said some demonstrators had ``unreasonable
expectations'' that they would be able to enter into a dialogue with their MP.
It was unreasonable because the Commons, though large, does not have the space
for several thousand demonstrators to enter into Socratic discussions with
their elected representatives.
Mr Newton and his equally pleasant Shadow, Mrs Ann Taylor, continued their
love-in which is slowly modernising Commons procedures so that it may well
enter the first half of the twenty-first century adequately equipped to deal
with the problems of the middle of the twentieth.
However, Sir Anthony Grant (Cambridgeshire South-West - Con.) suggested that
boxes might be left at the exits into which grateful visitors might put
voluntary ``donations'' which could go towards providing better facilities for
their successors.
Mr Beith turned this down succinctly. ``They feel they are paying for this
place out of their taxes and they are entitled to have a look round.''
Mr Harry Greenway (Ealing North - Con.) was concerned that the one opera hat
which a Member must wear seated if he or she wishes to raise a point of order
during a vote, was not enough. A second should be provided, he urged.
Although visitors to the public gallery have a fair chance of sampling the
ridiculous, the opera hat must come high on the scale of absurdities, but, in
fairness to the British constitution, one should say that an alternative is not
so easy to devise as might be thought. In this respect, the opera hat resembles
the House of Lords.
The Sketch suggests that Members should be allowed to raise points of order in
a hat of their choice. This would pose no problem for the Tory ladies, while
Labour's lurch to the right has been sartorial as well as political, so the
female comrades might produce fancy plumage too. As for Mr Banks, given his
rig-out yesterday, a natty black fedora would be just the job.
</TEXT>
