<HEADLINE>Only one problem left for England</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159431</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRICKET
ENGLAND are heading off for Thursday's second Test having solved all but one of
their problems after their two matches against Orange Free State.
Graham Thorpe scored an undefeated century and Alec Stewart hit top form with
innings of 110 and 81. Dominic Cork shook off the rust while batting and
bowling impressively and Mark Ramprakash did enough to suggest England are
right to stand by him.
That just leaves Devon Malcolm, whose one hope now would seem to rest on the
pitch at The Wanderers. If it looks quick and full of life, he just might sneak
into Thursday's line-up ahead of spinner Richard Illingworth.
Meanwhile, there are no plans for extra security measures for England's
cricketers following yesterday's fatal shooting during a Cape Town boxing
match, where armed robbers killed a cashier.
England's cricketers are en route to Johannesburg - one of the world's most
dangerous cities - but the players have been accompanied by two or three armed
guards from the VIP Protection Unit since arriving in South Africa.
q GLOUCESTERSHIRE fast bowler Mike Smith, who hurt rib ligaments in England A's
first match, will return home later this week.
Warwickshire seamer Tim Munton, who arrived in Pakistan on Friday as cover,
will stay on for the remaining three weeks of the tour but will not play in
Thursday's second Test against Pakistan A in Rawalpindi, where Dean Headley and
Ed Giddins will form the new-ball attack.
The three-day match against a Patrons' XI petered out into a draw yesterday.
Scores:
Tour match. England A 298-6 dec (N V Knight 107, J C Pooley 100no) and 130-4
dec; Patron's XI 187-9 dec (Azwar Mahmood63 no; T A Munton 5-54) and 88-3. In
Lahore. Match drawn.
</TEXT>
