<HEADLINE>Diverse dialects</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159433</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAVING read John Hodgert's essay (November 25) and recalled our time spent at
Dalry High School and in the 1st Dalry Co BB (his older brother Lindsay once
skelped our ears on parade for cheek!) I am rather reluctant to take issue with
his mission to promote the so-called ``Scots'' language.
Yet it has to be said that there is no chance of unanimity of pronunciation in
our country given the wide range of dialects currently in use.
The best example is demonstrated by the 2-nil football score which is ``twae
up'' (as in ``way'') in the New Cumnock area, ``twa up'' (as in ``wall'') in
the Ayr area, and ``two up'' (as in ``loo'') in the Kilbirnie area.
If we can't achieve unanimity in one county, what chance does Scotland have?
John F Crawford,
74 Drumsmittal Road,
North Kessock,
Ross-shire.
</TEXT>
