<HEADLINE>Taylor boxed in by Doherty</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159434</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNOOKER
A DISGUSTED Dennis Taylor found himself back in the commentary box sooner than
he had hoped after a crushing 9-1 third-round defeat by Ken Doherty at the
Royal Liver Assurance UK Championship in Preston last night.
``If I had too many matches like that I'd pack it all in,'' said the 1985 world
champion. ``At times it was embarrassing.''
Doherty now prepares for a repeat tomorrow of last year's UK final against
champion        Stephen Hendry.
The Dubliner set the tone with an excellent run of 94 to take the first frame.
Breaks of 41, 74, 37, 113, and 59 took Doherty 7-0 in front, and in four frames
Taylor managed just six points. He broke his duck in the final frame of the
afternoon but last night Doherty sealed his quarter-final place in just 41
minutes.
Ronnie O'Sullivan also built up a 7-1 first-session lead will take it into this
afternoon's session against struggling Scot Chris Small.
O'Sullivan has struggled in the first few months of the          season, with a
couple of first-round exits. But the 19-year-old from Essex has grown in
confidence at Preston.
World No.3 O'Sullivan made the perfect start, racing into a       5-0 lead with
breaks of 61, 63, and 94. Edinburgh's Small, world-ranked No.62, appeared ill
at ease on a rare outing before the television cameras.
He eventually got on the scoreboard with a run of 61 to clinch the sixth frame.
But O'Sullivan resumed normal service in the final two frames, with breaks of
55 and 80.
Devon left-hander Andy Hicks, a semi-finalist in this year's world
championship, staged a great comeback to establish a 5-3 overnight lead against
Thailand's James Wattana. World No.17 Hicks trailed 2-0 and 3-1 but, helped by
a break of 100, he responded to the challenge to take four frames in a row with
further runs of 65 and 97.
</TEXT>
