<HEADLINE>Clarke relaxed over moves for EU pact</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Murray Ritchie, European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159435</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke last night described German moves to fine EU member
states which break the rules for a single currency as ``rather draconian''.
However, he denied that the Germans - pivotal players in the run-up to monetary
union by the end of the century - would be interfering with Britain's national
sovereignty.
Pro-European Mr Clarke was speaking to reporters in Brussels after meeting
other EU finance ministers to discuss technical moves towards the proposed
single currency.
They will report their findings - and possibly a name for the new coinage - to
the EU's summit next month in Madrid.
The talks were dominated by a suggestion from Germany's finance minister Theo
Waigel that there should be a so-called stability pact among EU states opting
to join monetary union - leading to a single currency - by 1999.
Those in the pact would enforce budgetary discipline, including the possible
use of fines for member states who did not obey the rules.
Mr Clarke said: ``I don't believe these are a great threat to national
sovereignty.''
Britain still would have freedom to take its own decisions in all necessary
areas such as taxation policy.
He added that Britain had little to fear from the idea of such a pact because
the United Kingdom agreed with the Germans that there had to be lasting
stability in EU finances before and after the single currency.
``These ideas don't pose a great difficulty for the Government,'' he said.
``The policy of the British Government is to work towards having a balance in
the medium term. Our policy towards the single market has been to achieve
stable working conditions.''
He described Mr Waigel's call - which has caused alarm in some EU states
struggling to meet the economic conditions demanded by Maastricht for the
single currency - as ``simply the beginning of a discussion about economic and
monetary union.''
Only Belgium, Austria, Holland and France have so far indicated that they can
support the Waigel proposal, which would effectively force member states to
apply German standards of rigour to their economies.
Although Britain supports budgetary discipline, Mr Clarke made it clear there
was a limit.
``Theo Waigel has always been as clear as I have that the setting of tax is for
national governments, the setting of public expenditures is for national
governments. The kind of Budget I have tomorrow will always continue,'' he said.
``In so far as he is pressing for European governments all to concentrate on
keeping their deficits down and keeping their countries out of debt that I
agree with, but the details require an awful lot of talking about,'' he added.
</TEXT>
