<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New school of excellence aims to ward off council cutbacks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EXCLUSIVE By BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159436</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S biggest university and its associated teacher training college are
to establish a centre of excellence in education which aims to safeguard
projects threatened by local government reform.
The Glasgow School of Education will bring together expertise in Glasgow
University and St Andrew's College to provide lecturers, teachers, education
managers, and researchers with support and greater opportunities for career
development.
The school will comprise the college, Scotland's Roman Catholic
teacher-training institution, and two of the university's departments.
The university has been concerned about local government reform jeopardising
its ability to combat social exclusion. One of its initiatives, for instance,
is the innovative summer school. This gives potential students from
disadvantaged backgrounds who do not have conventional qualifications for
university entrance the opportunity to experience higher education and secure a
place on a course.
It is one of several projects funded by Strathclyde region but the authority's
demise could result in Glasgow experiencing a shortfall of about #30m in the
budget the new city council believes it needs for education.
The cost of maintaining projects such as the summer school and others which
expand educational opportunities could amount to about #350,000 a year.
University and college officials hope that inter-institutional developments
such as the new school will guarantee their future. A Scottish Higher Education
Funding Council review has placed a further question mark over Government
financial support for continued education.
The school will seek to exploit opportunities for in-service teacher training.
The smaller unitary councils are likely to be unable to offer the service.
In recognition of the increasingly competitive education marketplace, the
school will seek to provide cost-effective courses designed to meet the needs
of the new authorities and their schools.
It also plans to build on the research bases in both institutions, at a time
when the emphasis on research is growing.
Glasgow University vice-Principal Professor Andrew Skinner said the school
would focus on areas such as leadership and management training for teachers
and educationalists; in-service staff development; special educational needs -
one of the college's strengths; parental involvement in education; postgraduate
courses; work-based learning; community education and supporting a social
strategy; and research.
Professor Bart McGettrick, Principal of St Andrew's College, said the centre
would mean ``better support for educational professionals such as teachers and
lecturers''. Most importantly of all, he said, that meant ``the provision of
more effective education for students and pupils in the classroom''.
</TEXT>
