<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP's fantasies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159437</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN his front-page exclusive (November 25) Robbie Dinwoodie reveals that the
Nationalists, after 61 years of deliberation, are finally to tell us what their
separatist parliament would consist of. At last we are to know its membership,
voting method, powers, and relationship with England, Europe, and the world.
How extraordinary that it has taken all this time to come up with plans for a
parliament. It is significant to note that over the same timescale the SNP has
the poorest electoral record of all Scotland's political parties.
The hard fact is the Scots do not support the SNP in anything like the numbers
that would make them a viable choice at the next election. Whatever they tell
us on St Andrew's Day has little relevance to the real debate between the
Tories and Labour as only one of these two parties will win the General
Election.
Robbie Dinwoodie says the SNP dipped in The Herald poll last month after a
summer of mounting success. What mounting success? The success or otherwise of
political parties is measured by election results.
The most recent elections were the unitary authority elections last April which
saw another dismal performance from the SNP. In my own constituency they were
reduced to two seats out of 15 - their worst result in 28 years,
The SNP are entitled to their dreams and fantasies. That is what they shall
remain. All available evidence drawn from real elections and opinion polls,
including The Herald's polls, points to a Labour victory.
The Scottish Diaspora in England and elsewhere should be encouraged to mak
siccar by voting Labour for a Scottish Parliament. The SNP should tell us if
they are prepared to recommend that action to exiled Scots. It would be more
useful and practical than their spoiling exercise scheduled for Thursday
Norman Hogg MP,
House of Commons.
</TEXT>
