<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nothing to fear, much to gain</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159438</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT could be argued that never before in the field of human politics has so much
been read by so many into the views of so few. The Scotland on Sunday survey,
published on November 26, found 15 company bosses who said they would quit
Scotland in the event of a Scottish parliament being established. This out of a
total of 300 polled.
The result of the recent survey of views by the Scottish Chambers of Commerce,
which has been so widely picked over by all the political parties, was in fact
the views of only the 650 members who bothered to respond.
A response rate of only 19.1% seems to indicate more a lack of interest in the
great debate than any great enthusiasm for either independence or the status
quo. And who can blame them? Running a small company or indeed any company in
the present economic climate leaves little time for political considerations.
Certainly if business people felt really threatened by any of the proposals
then more would undoubtedly have taken the time to respond. This clearly did
not happen.
It would have been interesting if the present chambers' survey had put the same
question as was posed in the chambers' August 1991 survey. This asked ``Do you
support the establishment of a Scottish parliament with defined economic powers
including the ability to adjust income tax by up to 3p in the pound?''
This option, which is what the Scottish Constitutional Convention are
proposing, received 28% support from the 400 business respondents. (Perhaps
surprisingly this 1991 survey also had a 28% positive response to the question
``Would you support the case for a Scottish parliament with independent
representations in Europe?'')
It is not clear what those answering the present questionnaire read into the
term ``devolution with tax-changing powers'' - one suspects most assumed that
this referred to powers to vary company as well as personal taxation.
Future surveys by the chambers of commerce will probably be more specific and
it is likely that once it is clear that the devolution option only related to
power to vary income tax by 3p in the pound and not corporation tax, then the
percentage support for the convention's devolution proposals will rise
dramatically.
It is a shame that the same small number (15) of ``leading Scottish
businessmen'' who rallied to the defence of the (Conservative) Union in 1992,
are again coming out of the woodwork to threaten to quit Scotland if there is
any change to the status quo (or at least any change not sanctioned by
Conservative Central Office).
Against the possible loss of these 15 company head offices must be offset the
much larger number of companies who will decide to move into Scotland to take
advantage of the benefits which the convention's parliament will help create.
For a Scottish parliament with the powers proposed would be good for business
in Scotland.
l Business people will enjoy better and closer links with politicians. The open
structure of government which will be established will ensure that business
views will be heard and will be listened to. The policies which emerge will be
made in Scotland for the benefit of Scotland.
l Links with Brussels will be greatly strengthened. Hamish Morrison of the
Scottish Council Development and Industry has described a Scottish parliament
as a ``Whitehall bypass''.
l The psychological boost which the formation of a Scottish parliament will
give to the Scots will result in a real boost to the Scottish economy. People
of ability who have been put off from becoming involved in politics by the
sterility of the present set-up will stand for election. With proportional
representation no one party can dominate the new parliament.
l Company taxation will remain with Westminster so business has no need to fear
it could be disadvantaged in any way by the new set up. Indeed a Scottish
parliament would seek wherever possible to use its powers to encourage existing
businesses and to encourage inward investment. Training policies, for example,
will be established and streamlined to suit the needs of the Scottish economy.
In short, business in Scotland has nothing to fear and much to gain from a
Scottish parliament as proposed by the Constitutional Convention. Scottish
business does not need Westminster to protect it from the Scottish people.
Tom McGregor,
McGregor McMahon &amp; Associates,
Consulting Engineers,
4 Bellman Way,
Donibristle Industrial Park, Fife.
</TEXT>
