<HEADLINE>BBC governors to be given more control</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159440</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE BBC is to be told to listen to its audience and make clearer its
obligations to licence-fee payers, the Government announced yesterday.
A ``statement of pledges'' outlining what audiences can expect is one of the
main demands of the draft new BBC charter and agreement.
Governors are to be given tighter and ``explicit'' control of the running of
the corporation, and it has been told that its cherished editorial independence
must be matched by editorial responsibility.
The draft of the new 10-year charter laid to rest rumours that the Government
planned to break up the BBC when its current charter expires at the end of next
year. But National Heritage Secretary Virginia Bottomley, announcing the draft,
also disclosed a decision to privatise the BBC's transmission services.
The Department of National Heritage said the plan would provide ``a flexible
framework'' building on the public service tradition while allowing the BBC to
meet the challenges of the twenty-first century.
Corporation chairman Marmaduke Hussey welcomed the draft as a ``vote of
confidence in the BBC'', and said it justified the sometimes painful policies
pursued by top managers under Michael Checkland and John Birt.
Shadow Heritage Secretary Jack Cunningham said he welcomed the new charter's
explicit statement of the BBC's public service objectives.
But he questioned the transmission privatisation, which could result ``in
another unaccountable private monopoly''.
Mrs Bottomley said: ``The BBC is a national jewel. The BBC is internationally
recognised as the leading broadcaster in the world.
``The BBC's editorial independence is enshrined within the new agreement.
Editorial independence requires editorial responsibility. The BBC is recognised
as the cornerstone of British broadcasting. Often, where it leads others
follow. This places a responsibility on the BBC to ensure that standards are
maintained in a multi-media future.''
The charter has to be approved by Parliament.
