<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour challenges SNP over Scots exiles' votes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>politics in brief</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975159441</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNP LEADER Alex Salmond was challenged yesterday by a Labour MP to back Labour
in England at the next General Election.
Cumbernauld and Kilsyth MP Norman Hogg has written to Mr Salmond demanding to
know if he will recommend that Scots living in England vote Labour for a
Scottish parliament.
Mr Hogg said: ``Salmond has to come clean. He wants independence but we all
know he has nothing like the votes needed to win a majority of Scottish
constituencies.
``Will he tell exiled Scots to vote Labour for a Scottish parliament? If
Salmond refuses to do this, he will confirm what a lot of us think - he wants
another Tory government.
``He hopes to benefit from the aftermath of a Labour defeat, but more important
he knows that a strong Scottish parliament screws his party's long-term
prospects.''
LESSONS from Scotland on how young people are dealt with by the legal system
are to be studied by Labour nationally. Shadow Home Secretary Jack Straw said:
``Over the coming months, I shall be considering the working of the Scottish
children's hearings, as well as the experiences of other countries in Europe,
to see what lessons they hold for those dealing with offending by children and
young people.''
MAJOR changes in the blood service in England, saving #10m and costing 300
jobs, were announced yesterday by Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell. He told the
Commons that every hospital would continue to have its own blood bank and two
new centres would allow emergency supplies to be delivered in just two hours. A
new computer system would allow stocks to be managed on a national basis.
Administrative work now carried out at 13 centres would be concentrated on
three - in Leeds, Bristol and London. Shadow Health Secretary Harriet Harman
condemned the scrapping of processing and testing work at certain centres as a
``false economy.''
THE Earl of Gowrie has advised parents to wash their children's hair in whisky
if they have head lice. However, crossbencher Lady Saltoun of Abernethy
wondered in the Lords if surgical spirit would also do the trick. However,
junior health Minister Baroness Cumberledge replied: ``I think these are a lot
of lousy suggestions!''
</TEXT>
