<HEADLINE>English disdain for the Union</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159443</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAY I respond to John Bisland's letter on the misuse England instead of Britain
(November 24)?
The answer to his question is: No he is most certainly not alone in harbouring
resentment; but the sad news is that it will never be any different while the
London-based media mandarins continue to pander to English nationalism by going
along with these fallacies.
The morning following the Panorama broadcast by the Princess of Wales, I
purposely tuned my radio into English-based stations to find her often referred
to as the future Queen of England, and the Prince of Wales being referred to as
a future King of England.
Those stations who invited phone calls from listeners provided a real insight
into the English disdain for the Act of Union - the British monarchy was
non-existent.
If, after nearly 400 years since the Union of the Crowns, so many English
people cannot see themselves to be British how will they ever come round to
being European?
John Inglis,
15 Cambridge Road,
Renfrew.
JOHN Bisland is not alone in his feelings (November 24).
Have you noticed that for a long time new contestants on most TV competitions
have been introduced as ``A from Birmingham, B from Liverpool, C from
Portsmouth, D from Bath, and E from Scotland''?
Perhaps they really do think that Scotland is a town in the north of England.
R McGoldrick,
135 Balshagray Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
