<HEADLINE>Ex-Labour leader stirs Europe row and Chancellor rules out threat to Britain from German `fines' plan. LINE>Kinnock opens rift on single currency</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159444</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEIL KINNOCK was at the centre of controversy last night after he exposed a
deep rift in the European Commission over the proposed single currency and EU
enlargement.
Mr Kinnock broke with the commission's tradition of collective responsibility
when he said monetary union in 1999, as scheduled, was ``unrealistic''.
He also said that granting EU membership to ex-communist states in eastern
Europe would take longer and cost more than is officially estimated.
Commissioners in Brussels have spent months denying they have serious doubts
about these issues, which are the two biggest political challenges facing the
EU as it prepares to renegotiate the Maastricht treaty next year to cope with
enlargement and the expanding single market.
Mr Kinnock, who became transport commissioner after relinquishing the Labour
Party leadership in the wake of the last General Election, was talking to a
closed business seminar in Bracknell, Berkshire, on Friday.
His speech, described by the commission as ``private'' for a group of 200
businessmen, was not distributed routinely, but his comments were reported by a
French news agency. Copies of the speech - in which Mr Kinnock said he was
speaking as a commissioner but not as the commission - were suddenly
unavailable from his press service.
Mr Kinnock later discussed his remarks with commission president Jacques Santer
amid denials that he had been carpeted. ``Mr Kinnock was quite happy to explain
to Mr Santer what happened. It was not a speech for public consumption,'' his
spokeswoman said.
An indication of the split in the commission came earlier yesterday when EU
finance commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy said in Paris there was no
question of delaying the introduction of a single currency beyond 1999.
``We would have to renegotiate a new Maastricht treaty,'' he said.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke, leaving Brussels to put finishing touches to today's
Budget, described Mr Kinnock's comments on the single currency as ``somewhat
sweeping''. Mr Clarke, a Cabinet pro-European, said the timetable for the
single currency was ``still too soon to call''.
In his speech to a forum, sponsored by Siemens, Mr Kinnock said Britain had the
choice of being part of economic and monetary union (Emu) or being dominated by
it.
``Geographical, financial and trading realities make that obvious to everyone
who isn't foaming at the mouth over `losing the Queen's head' or `conceding
monetary power','' he said.
Mr Kinnock added: ``Even when that is understood, however, the prospect of
monetary union (not in 1999 by the way - that is still unrealistic in my view
just as 1997 has been) should not, of course, be approached fatalistically.''
He said there should be a ``real debate'' on Emu which he described as
inevitable and desirable.
Mr Kinnock is believed to be in a minority in the commission on the chances of
some EU member states joining in monetary union by 1999. However, he is thought
to be in a majority who doubt privately that the EU can be expanded to 25 or 30
members in the early years of next century, as supporters of fast enlargement
claim.
He reminded his audience that applicant states had to show they could meet all
economic and political conditions required by the EU before they joined. There
was ``continual repetition of promises'' of membership and continuing dialogue
on the issue.
``Frankly, I think that this approach must be reconsidered,'' Mr Kinnock said.
``Continually holding out the prospect of enlargement whilst not doing enough
to make it really feasible produces the worse of both worlds.
``I believe that we should say honestly to the eastern and central European
countries that the prospect of membership is very distant and then tell them
that we would like to implement a different approach - one that has rather less
rhetoric and rather more substance.''
</TEXT>
