<HEADLINE>Laser offers better eye treatment for diabetics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159445</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEW machine offering the latest laser treatment for the biggest preventable
cause of blindness was launched in Edinburgh yesterday.
The #70,000 laser can operate on several wavelengths and treat a wider variety
of diabetic retinopathy conditions than existing models. Edinburgh Royal
Infirmary's eye pavilion is the first NHS centre in Britain to buy one.
Funding for the US-built machine came from the infirmary's diabetic treatment
trust.
About 140,000 people in Scotland have diabetes and as many again may have the
disease but do not show symptoms. Of those diagnosed, 80% are liable to develop
eye disease from their diabetes within 20 years.
Associate specialist in ophthalmology Dr Kenneth Swa said it was essential that
diabetics followed their treatment and underwent regular eye checks.
``There is no point in having the best laser if the right patients are not
coming to this department. It is essential that diabetics have their eyes
examined properly and be referred to us. Screening is absolutely critical,'' he
said.
Laser treatment is the only way of preventing blindness through diabetic
retinopathy and, if used early enough, can be effective in 90% of cases. It
works by removing blood vessels which form on the retina.
Mother-of-two Mrs Muriel Darling, of Duddingston Grove, Edinburgh, a diabetic
for 31 years, is one of the first to benefit from the new machine. A routine
eye test picked up her condition in 1991 and she is now undergoing a course of
laser treatment on her right eye.
``Those people with diabetes who don't come for checks may later find there is
something wrong but by then it's too late. I can see perfectly but there are
some little growths and blood vessels which need to be treated.
``There is a dull ache when undergoing the treatment but I think it's worth
putting up with to be able to see for the rest of my life.''
</TEXT>
