<HEADLINE>Mailmen tackle backlog</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159446</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE than 5000 postal workers in Scotland were back at work yesterday to help
move a backlog of 12 million items which piled up during their week-long
unofficial industrial action.
The Royal Mail reported that, apart from a ``blip'' in Dundee and Perth caused
by a communication problem, work on the backlog, which will take at least a
week to clear, was going very well.
A settlement in the dispute, which began in a delivery office in Portobello,
Edinburgh, over duty changes and spread to other parts of Scotland, was reached
at the weekend.
A 14-point peace plan, including the promise of a review of delivery services,
was accepted by workers at meetings on Sunday in Edinburgh and Glasgow. Talks
between the two sides are set to continue until mid-January.
Meanwhile, the Communication Workers' Union has agreed to suspend plans to
ballot members on taking official action.
More than 200 workers on Tayside yesterday voted unanimously to go back to work
at meetings in Dundee and Perth which approved the same deal put to workers on
Sunday.
They had stayed on strike until union leaders in the area could organise a vote
on the package.
Mr Joe Malone, CWU Tayside branch secretary, said there had been some confusion
over whether workers should return to work after the voting in Edinburgh and
Glasgow.
``The package was not officially accepted until votes had been taken in Dundee
and Perth.''
The Royal Mail said it was disappointed and puzzled that it had taken the
Tayside staff an extra day to return.
Workers at Hamilton who had taken official action last week also voted
overwhelmingly yesterday to return to work.
However, after a noisy two-hour meeting, Mr John Keggie, CWU divisional officer
for Scotland and Northern Ireland, spoke of staff anger and frustration over
the way the Hamilton office had been treated.
He said workers had spent 16 weeks enduring additional supervision and close
monitoring as management cut back on second deliveries of post.
He said the feeling was so strong that if the underlying matters were not
solved between now and December 23 there could be further developments.
</TEXT>
