<HEADLINE>McKinlay hopes for second time lucky</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Johnson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159447</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WOMEN'S GOLF
MYRA McKinlay, the former Curtis Cup player from Scotland, will be making her
second attempt to earn her card for the American Express Tour in the 72-hole
qualifying school tournament which begins over the South course at La Manga
Club in Spain today, writes Bill Johnson.
McKinlay failed on her first attempt over the same course last March and played
in only nine tournaments this year. Her position of No.100 on the final merit
table enforced a return to Spain.
It has been a disappointing season for the Scot, who made an encouraging debut
as a professional when she finished eighth in the English Open at Tytherington
last year before making the cut in both the Dutch and Spanish Opens.
Only the top 40 and ties in the field of 92 will earn their cards for next
season and McKinlay, Morag Wright, Karin Ross, Lindsey Irvine, and Tracey Craik
are the five Scots in the field.
Karrie Webb, the British Open champion from Australia, came through the first
qualifying school in March and went on to win this year's Rookie of the Year
award.
This performance has encouraged six other Australians to play this week.
Much will be expected from Kristel Mourgue d'Algue from France, who reached the
British amateur championship final this year, 12 months after her mother
Cecilia also lost in the final. Earlier this year Mourgue d'Algue shared ninth
place in the Evian Masters.
With Annika Sorenstam dominating women's professional golf this year, it is no
surprise to find 16 Swedes in Spain this week.
