<HEADLINE>Famous first words of the pally Prime Minister</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159451</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``WELL, who would have thought it?'' Besides famous last words there are famous
first words, and these are the words spoken five years ago tomorrow by John
Major when he presided over his first Cabinet meeting as Prime Minister. Or,
perhaps he said - ``Well, who would have thought it!'' Either way, they were
far more memorable than anything else uttered in the succeeding five years.
The trouble with anniversaries, as Lady Thatcher found out to her cost, is that
they remind people how long the celebrant has been around, in politics, as in
life, not necessarily a good thing.
The Major years began after I had stopped reporting Parliament, so my
experience of him as close to first hand as you ever get to Prime Ministers,
even as a lobby correspondent, is slight. I do remember a distinctly
ill-at-ease Foreign Secretary at the Kuala Lumpur Commonwealth Heads of
Government meeting being condescended to by the might of the diplomatic
correspondents, not the least of his worries, because She Who Must Be Obeyed
stabbed him in the back over a deal he had cobbled up on South African
sanctions.
Then there was a remarkably pally Prime Minister at the Harare CHOGM ruffling
the hair of the man from Today, which had just published a fawning interview.
If ever there was proof that he was not the man she thought he was that was it.
I suspect it was not out of character and the man-of-the-people image is real.
When I interviewed him, during his time as Chief Secretary to the Treasury, he
helped me into my coat as I left, and then sent a thank-you note saying I had
put it far better than he had done. It suggests he really is a nice man,
although I have two thank-you telemessages from Barbara Cartland, hung in the
obvious place. But they are patently the work of her secretary. The Major note
was hand-written.
What, I wonder, will his last words be? And when will we hear them? Must we
wait another five years? As we know a weak is a long time in politics. Or will
today's Budget do the trick? We live in interesting times. It will also be
interesting times when MPs reveal their remuneration for outside jobs to find
what the Tory who advised the BBC on The Final Cut got for selling duff
information.
The last instalment of the Not Written By Michael Dobbs political trilogy was
utter nonsense in its portrayal of parliamentary procedure and the ease of
access to Prime Ministers it implied. Some of the errors were so glaring that
even the most occasional watcher of the Commons proceedings on the telly could
not have failed to spot them. Did they matter? Some were clearly to allow
eyeball-to-eyeball confrontation between Ian Richardson and Paul Freeman, and
simply dramatic licence. But to suggest that an MP could cross the floor, which
means quitting his party and resigning the Whip, but still contest the
leadership was going too far.
Changing the subject completely, but variety is the spice of life. One of the
brighter wheezes the makers of Goldeneye, the new James Bond film, had was to
make ``M'' a woman. One can just imagine the self-satisfied chortles at the
script conference when they dreamt that one up.
It was a means of bringing this dated saga into the nineties, the real-life
``M'' being until very recently Mrs Stella Rimmington, quite apart from the
fact that Bernard Lee, who stamped his personality on the role, was no longer
available, having gone to the great central casting in the sky.
I reckon while they were at it they should have turned Moneypenny into a man,
since there are loads of male PAs around these days, as it would have given the
relationship with Bond a whole new meaning. But maybe that would be going too
far, except that while they have found in Dame Judi Dench a suitably acerbic
``M'' the replacement for the divine Lois Maxwell is pure plastic. Nothing
dates like a wheeze. On the day the film premiered it was announced that Mrs
Rimmington is to retire and be replaced by a man. Let us hope Dame Judi has a
nice watertight run-of-the-series contract, or she could lose what must be a
nice little earner, especially should she, which Heaven forfend, be reduced to
opening supermarkets and gas stations.
Returning to anniversaries - logical thought was never one of my strengths - in
one of his fifth-anniversary interviews Mr Major revealed that his political
views had been shaped by what he had seen as a boy in Brixton, ``the
paternalism of the nanny state writ small, with very well-meaning people
seeking to help, but not the help one really wanted''. Politics was largely
about tolerance, he said, not necessarily about imposing what you happen to
think right upon other people.
Admirable sentiments, but surely not on the day Virginia Bottomley announced
new guidelines for the BBC to protect viewers from having to watch sex and
violence on television and listen to bad language. This must mean they can
never show Shakespeare or recite the works of Burns on the box.
The thing about television is that the viewer is not a victim. The viewer is in
charge. The viewer can switch the set off and settle down with a good book
instead. After all, if a guest in your home behaved in a manner you considered
unacceptable, would you not ask them to leave? Or would you write to your MP
and say the Government must do something about it?
</TEXT>
