<HEADLINE>THOM DIBDIN visits a dance venue in the former Munich airport where techno has taken off in a big way Airport is all the rave</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Thom Dibdin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159453</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REIM Airport, Munich. Here it was that Chamberlain arrived when he visited
Hitler in 1938, returning with a piece of paper announcing peace in our time.
Here, too, it was that the ill-fated Manchester United team, Busby's Babes,
crashed in 1958.
The aircraft have moved on to bigger and longer runways, but the empty airport
buildings remain. Lego-sized, they are a child's idea of an airport. Now,
however, instead of reeling to the sound of jets, they throb to the sound of
techno.
Among the commercial pop arenas there is one space which is known across the
continent: Ultraschall, or Beyond sound in English. Here they play
technological music of an innovative persuasion. And here it was that DJs
Twitch and Brainstorm, residents at the Edinburgh club Pure, were recently to
be found, displaying their prodigious DJ'ing talents.
In clubbing terms, Pure is an institution. Over five years it has gained the
reputation of being Scotland's premier night of techno and trance. Yet Twitch
and Brainstorm are only now making their first international tour. All two
dates of it.
It's 4am and in Scotland most clubs would have been finished for an hour but
Ultraschall won't close until 10am. Brainstorm, resplendent in his
international DJ'ing haircut - shorn close and dyed with a leopard-skin print -
drops a brand-new tune: there hasn't been dancing here this manic for all of a
week.
Ultraschall is only one of several dance arenas at the airport. The week before
they had all been brought together for a massive rave, Tribal Gathering, for
which the tribes came from all corners of the North Bavarian plain. From across
the Alps, from Italy, France, Switzerland, and Austria. Fifteen thousand turned
up. More would have been there if the first blasts of winter had not sent the
temperature plummeting to minus seven and deposited six inches of snow across
the land.
You couldn't design a better rave venue than Reim if you tried. The departure
lounges and baggage reclamation halls make a warren of huge arenas. The
international departure lounge which once echoed with deals being made by
businessmen on their way to Berlin was turned into Planet Erotica, a
strictly-house zone where women in skin-tight rubber dresses or clad in nothing
but body paint danced with men in minimal leather bondage gear on the stage.
But the main sound was a truly Teutonic techno. Warlike and pulsing with a
relentless four-four beat, it filled the halls. Situated slightly apart from
the main halls, in the old kitchens of the airport, the Ultraschall offered
music plus much more. Every storeroom and vacant corner had been put to use.
Turn one corner and you found a cafe. Turn another and enter a pitch-dark room,
humming with the sound of the sea sucking on the beach. Plunge into an unmarked
corridor and you would end up in a tiny room filled with smoke, strobes, and
people cavorting to the sinuous sound known as acid.
Small wonder the club has earned itself such a reputation. As Twitch and
Brainstorm spun their records on the main dancefloor, Glasgow's DJ Mingo Go
played easy listening in the back room. Henry Mancini's Little Elephant Walk
mixed effortlessly into Esquivel and Jimmi Tenor.
``My mission with this club is really to keep the people ahead,'' says Peter
Wacha, one of the four-strong team who run Ultraschall. ``I don't like to use
`techno' any more. So now we do electronic listening and dance music.''
Wacha's first memories of music are of late-seventies punk: Throbbing Gristle,
the Pop Group and the Birthday Party. ``It really gave me a kick,'' he says.
``That is also the point of this club: I'm old now, 33, and there are a lot of
young people who are in the situation that I was. If you go out in Munich you
mostly get really shitty music, so I wanted to give them the same kick as I
got.''
Sadly, commercial interests with a bigger clout than Wacha's have their eyes on
Reim. The infrastructure is just too good to throw away on mere hedonism and
the buildings will be demolished next May to make way for an international
conference centre. But until then, if you want no peace in your night-time in
the form of innovative music from dance's cutting edge, you know where to go.
n Twitch and Brainstorm play at Pure at the Edinburgh Venue every Friday. A
double-pack of Pure classics is due out soon on T &amp; B Vinyl with a mix CD to
follow next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
