<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Starring in a light show near you . . .</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159455</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE only reindeer herd in Britain will be travelling to Northern Ireland for a
festive procession - if owners the Reindeer Company at Glenmore near Aviemore
can cut through the red tape.
Thirty reindeer were loaded on to three specially adapted lorries yesterday
heading for the ferry across the Irish Sea to Dungannon - but before embarking
they must get import licences and veterinary clearance.
Ms Janet Stewart, of the Reindeer Company, said: ``We are still very hopeful of
making the short ferry crossing with them. It will be the first time that
reindeer have been ever harnessed to Santa's sleigh in the Emerald Isle . . .
apart from on Christmas Eve.''
She added: ``We have bookings from one end of the country to the other . . .
They will be appearing in processions in places as far apart as Wales,
Liverpool, London, Dorset, and Thurso.''
Two reindeer pull Santa's sleigh followed by three others in parades to mark
the switching on of the Christmas lights in towns and cities across Britain.
The reindeer return to the Cairngorms in the new year.
The Reindeer Company is owned by Elizabeth and Alan Smith, who go out on the
road with them. Ms Stewart is left to tend the remainder of the herd of 120.
Reindeer were introduced to Scotland by Laplander Mikel Utsi in 1952 to be bred
for venison, but the company now derives its income from tourism, sales to
theme parks, and Santa's sleigh-rides.
</TEXT>
