<HEADLINE>Robertson in rematch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159456</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOWLS
THE showpiece of the indoor season gets under way in Coatbridge this afternoon,
with the Scottish Masters being fought out over two days, while the semi-finals
and finals of the CIS Insurance national singles championship wrap up the
bonanza on Thursday.
The opening match in the #4000 eight-player Masters is a repeat of last year's
final, holder John Price from Swansea taking on Graham Robertson.
Each is bidding to become the first man to win the title for a third time and
the winner will meet the survivor of the clash of the Commonwealth champions -
Richard Corsie and women's gold medallist Margaret Johnston.
Tonight brings together the two world indoor champions - Andy Thomson and
women's title-holder Joyce Lindores - and completing the action is the clash
between Scottish champion Paul Conlan and the man he succeeded, Bainfield's
Alex Marshall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surgeons save man's hand after Samurai sword attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159457</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SURGEONS have sewn back a man's hand which had been cut off by thugs wielding a
Samurai sword.
Mr Leslie Harding, 37, was attacked on Sunday night by ``skinheads'' outside a
public house in Leeds.
Mr Harding, of Chapeltown, Leeds, is black and police are investigating whether
there was a racial motive.
He was attacked after he left the Travellers public house in Selby Road,
Halton, Leeds, to remonstrate with the gang, who were smashing windows with
bricks and baseball bats.
One of the gang sliced off his right hand with the sword before fleeing but a
doorman picked it up and packed it in ice. Mr Harding was taken to St James's
Hospital, where consultant plastic surgeon Simon Kay operated.
He said: ``He was remonstrating with somebody and saw a flash of steel and felt
his hand go numb. Looking down, he found it had vanished and was lying on the
ground.
``It was completely severed just at the level of the wrist.''
Mr Kay said it was unlikely he would get the full use of his hand back and it
will be around a week before it is known whether the operation has been a
success.
He added: ``The first hurdle is getting the hand to survive. It looks at the
moment as though it is going to be okay.''
One female customer at the public house said there had been trouble earlier but
those involved had left, returning around closing time.
She said: ``There was a lot of screaming and shouting outside and the gang of
lads was smashing the windows with baseball bats.  I was standing in the
doorway watching and I heard one of them say `I'm going to cut your hand off'.
``One of them had a big mach-ete and he just chopped it off.
``Some of the staff were crying their eyes out. It was gruesome.''
A police spokeswoman said Mr Harding, who is unemployed, was too ill to be
interviewed about the incident. His wife is at his bedside.
The spokeswoman added: ``A racist attack is one of several possibilities that
we're looking at. It's very early in the investigation and until we speak to
him we won't know any more about why it happened.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nothing Scottish</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159458</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAMES Freeman, in his article (November 23) about the trial of Rosemary West
headlined ``Why she should have gone Scot free'', states, including her husband
Fred in this opinion, ``They would literally have walked away scot free out of
legal reach because of the Scottish requirement for corroboration and the basic
requirement of fairness''. That is, of course, if they had been tried in
Scotland.
The erroneous, possibly unintentional, implication here is that there is some
connection between ``scot-free'' and Scotland.
There is no such connection. ``Scot-free'' means ``without harm, loss or
penalty'' and comes from ``scot and lot'', which was a municipal tax that was
abolished by the Reform Act of 1832.
David MacPherson,
51 Cresswell Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159459</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Trades Union Congress general secretary Campbell Christie joined
pensioners' groups, local authority leaders and church representatives
yesterday at an eve-of-Budget protest at the door of the Scottish Office.
Mr Christie handed in the STUC's own Budget submission and a four-ft-long tax
demand addressed to Chancellor Kenneth Clarke and Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth.
During his address to about 70 supporters, Mr Christie told of his fears about
today's Budget announcements.
Mr Christie said he was alarmed that the Goverment may be about to cut taxes
for what he described as short-term partisan electoral advantage.
He said: ``The people of Scotland should realise he has a choice of improving
public services, creating jobs, helping the least-well-off or trying to buy
votes for the Tory Party through tax cuts.
``When people digest details of his Budget, they should realise he had that
choice.''
Turning his attention to Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth, Mr Christie added:
``He has warned that this will be the harshest public spending round in living
memory.
``We think that is both unacceptable and unnecessary.
``The Government should be investing for the long term, not cutting welfare
benefits, eroding vital public services and freezing capital spending to find
pre-election tax bribes.
``We want to demonstrate to the Government that there is public opposition to
cuts and support for an alternative, including an emergency jobs package, a
planned boost to public investment and a restoration of decent benefits to
all.''
Concern also was raised by pensioners' leaders who were worried that any cuts
in social services would affect them directly.
President of the Edinburgh branch of the Scottish OAP Association, Mr Tom
Mellors, said: ``We have the second lowest level of pensions in Europe at
#58.75 a week. It is lower than anywhere apart from Greece.
``Pensioners throughout Scotland are very concerned at what will be included in
the Budget and that possible cuts in public spending to help pay for tax cuts
will affect people like us.''
Vice-president of the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities, Mr Keith
Geddes, said Cosla officials would be meeting tonight to scrutinise the Budget
and work out its impact on services north of the border.
Councillor Geddes said the Chancellor should not offer more tax bribes and
invest more in jobs and public services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Short screen test</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>william russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159460</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO weeks in another town lie ahead for two Glasgow film makers under the First
Film Foundation's New Directions programme. The other town is Hollywood, the
film makers Patrick Harkins, who worked in the prop department on films like
Shallow Grave and Hear My Song, and Angus Lamont, producer of Muriel Gray's The
Snow Show and The Golden Cagoule.
They are among eight film makers picked to meet the moguls and show their
wares. They have all made short films which will be screened at Bafta, Los
Angeles. They will also visit New York where the films will be screened by
Columbia-Tristar and at Robert De Niro's Tribeca Centre. It is hoped that
during the two weeks they will be able to find the backing they need to embark
on a first feature.
First Film Foundation, a charity, was set up in 1987 to provide training,
guidance, and development support for young people wishing to make a career in
film or television, and the New Directions programme is sponsored by the film
camera company, Panavision.
Ivan Mactaggart, foundation director, said the eight represented the best new
talent in the country. ``There is not much for Americans to look forward to
between Thanksgiving and Christmas, but we are changing all that,'' he added.
Patrick Harkins scored a big hit at the Edinburgh Film Festival with Nightlife,
his witty and sinister film, starring Jane Horrocks, about strange goings on in
Kelvingrove Park, made for BBC Scotland. His The Last Ten Minutes, which
starred Robert Carlyle, went out as the supporting feature with Shallow Grave,
and he also made the award-winning short, Narance.
Angus Lamont's short film for the BFI, Joyride, was shown at Cannes this year,
and he has a thriller, Shotgun Wedding, in development with Jim Gillespie which
is said to be ``Speed plus''. His work is said to be entertainment driven, not
always the case with first feature film aspirants, and the pair have made a
trailer to help boost their chances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Company plans Highland seaplane factory</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159461</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN AUSTRALIAN businessman plans to manufacture twin-engined amphibian planes in
Ross and Cromarty.
Mr Kenn Heeley, 46, has set up the Ross Aircraft Company to begin making his
seaplanes close to the Cromarty Firth, which has a long history of seaplane
operations since before the First World War.
``I must emphasise right away that I'm no John DeLorean,'' said Mr Heeley
yesterday, who is aware that his venture sounds almost too good to be true.
He is being supported by the Scottish Office, Highlands and Islands Enterprise,
and Ross and Cromarty Enterprise, who see the potential for perhaps hundreds of
jobs.
Mr Heeley said the vast bulk of the aircraft would go to North America and the
Pacific Rim countries, although the Highlands and Islands themselves would be
ideal for the specially adapted 10-seater seaplanes.
A fifth-scale model of the aircraft has already been tested in secret at
Kilbirnie Loch, near Glasgow, and it exceeded all expectations.
The plane is based on the Pilatus Britten Norman Islander but incorporates a
design development which enables it to take off and land on water.
Mr Heeley said he was particularly keen for the project to be based in Ross and
Cromarty: ``The downgrading of the oil industry in the area, although very sad,
has left a fantastic infrastructure and highly skilled people.
``There is a long history connected to seaplane training and maintenance during
both world wars, and I came to know the area very well as I used to take
classic motor-cycle tours of 10 to 20 bikes at a time up to Ross and Cromarty.''
Once production is firmly established, Mr Heeley would like to open Britain's
only seaplane museum as well as provide a parcel and passenger delivery service
throughout the Highlands and crew and pilot training.
Manufacture of the planes could be at different places. ``There is no reason
why the tail and fin sections, for example, could not be made on Skye, the
undercarriage in Ross, and then have final assembly in, say, Invergordon,'' he
said.
The highly profitable Islander aircraft, once fitted with the seaplane
adaptation, would be a much cheaper alternative to existing seaplanes, he added.
The Civil Aviation Authority has given its go-ahead to the development
programme and full production of 20 seaplanes could be achieved within five
years.
Mr Heeley's designer is Mr David Thurston, of Thurston Aeromarine Corporation,
Maine. Other experts who are backing him include his commercial director, Mr
John Colley, and Mr Derek Wilson, ex-Rover and British Aerospace, who is
production director.
</TEXT>
