<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bridge toll report `a PR exercise'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent and KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159462</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GOVERNMENT transport watchdog has told Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
that some people living in Skye or Kyle should not have to pay any more than a
#1 to cross the Skye Bridge, although it believes the imposition of tolls on
the bridge is logical and reasonable.
Campaigners have dismissed the report as nothing more than a public-relations
exercise for the Scottish Office.
MP Charles Kennedy described it as timid in the extreme and said it provided
camouflage for those still trying to defend the tolls.
Mrs Kathleen MacRae, treasurer of the Skye Bridge Appeal Group, said: ``It
really is pathetic that they have come out with this at a time when the
momentum is growing for the complete abolition of the tolls and for the
introduction of a system of shadow tolls, whereby the Scottish Office would pay
for each vehicle crossing.
``Their suggested concession to local car drivers does nothing for the people
of the Western Isles or for the vehicles that provide us with our goods and
services. It is just PR for the Scottish Office.''
The watchdog body, the Railway Users' Consultative Committee for Scotland,
denied that its report was a public-relations exercise. Its chairman, Ms Helen
Millar, said: ``This has nothing to do with the Scottish Office and we have
nothing to do with the Scottish Office. We will be sending a copy of the report
to them but we have not consulted them in any way.''
The Caledonian MacBrayne Users' Consultative Committee - as the Railway Users'
Consultative Committee for Scotland calls itself when considering ferry matters
- held a public meeting in Kyle of Lochalsh last month and found a clear
perception among local people that the Skye Bridge had been foisted on them.
The committee accepts that the majority of people indicated they wanted a
toll-free bridge but a substantial minority had stated they would not object to
paying a reasonable toll.
The committee's broad conclusion was the tariff of tolls was fair but there
were two groups excepted from this.
``We believe that for the people whose main residence is on Skye and for a much
smaller group around Kyle (who have to cross for work or medical treatment), a
concessionary level of toll should be applied recognising their status as local
residents.''
The committee recommends a toll of #1 for these cases.
The report also argues that no impediment or excessive charges should be put in
the way of any credible operator wanting to run a ferry in competition to the
bridge.
A Scottish Office spokesman said last night that Ministers would read the
committee's conclusions and recommendations with interest.
q Traffic levels on the Skye bridge have exceeded expectations in the first
month of operation, according to operator, Skye Bridge Ltd. It says about
36,000 vehicles used the bridge in the first full month since it opened on
October 16.
</TEXT>
