<HEADLINE>SNP to counter tax cut with plan for low-paid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159463</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CUT of 2p in the basic rate of income tax, as widely mooted at Westminster,
will be the subject of an immediate challenge by the SNP, which will move
instead its own Budget proposal for a new lower tax band of 15p.
SNP leader Alex Salmond claimed yesterday that his party's plan to bring in a
new rate for low-earners would cost exactly the same - #3bn - as cutting 2p
from the basic rate, and he used a poll carried out last weekend to demonstrate
that 86% of Scots would prefer to see a change which targeted help on the
less-well-off.
Party activists carried out more than 1100 interviews with Saturday-morning
shoppers in 13 towns and cities across Scotland, and claimed to have received
widespread support for tax cuts aimed at the poor (86%).
Mr Salmond said yesterday: ``Given this weight of Scottish opinion and the fact
that there is no difference in cost to the Exchequer, if the Chancellor
suggests cutting the standard rate by 2p, we will immediately move our
counter-proposal targeting tax cuts on the less-well-off.''
Labour joined the chorus demanding a Budget for jobs and investment, paid for
by a windfall tax on private utility profits.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said the Prime Minister's desire to
scrap capital gains tax and inheritance tax would cost #4.5bn and benefit the
privileged few.
``The average Scottish family has now seen 21 Tory tax rises since the last
election, and is now paying more than #800 a year extra in tax,'' he said.
``The Tories promised tax cuts year on year at the last election. They lied.''
The survey by SNP canvassers at the weekend found 86% in favour of targeting
tax cuts on the less well off; 93% in favour of cutting the National Insurance
burden on employers to encourage job creation; 90% in favour of abolishing
means testing for residential care for the elderly which often enforces the
sale of homes; 85% supporting a cut in the tax on whisky; and 94% backing the
return of the Skye Bridge to public hands and the cutting of tolls.
``There is massive support in Scotland for the kind of mainstream policies
which the SNP published in our budget earlier this month,'' Mr Salmond said.
``Every one of the measures backed by Scots in our suvey has in important place
in the SNP's four-year-economic strategy for an independent Scotland.''
He pointed out that the abolition of means-testing for those admitted to
residential health care would cost #500m in the UK - just half of the cost of
abolishing capital gains tax which would help the very wealthy.
The SNP said that the survey had produced interesting results in some parts of
the country. Eastwood, for example, returns Tory MP Allan Stewart, and yet of
127 people questioned there 119 wanted tax cuts to be aimed at the
less-well-off and 124 supported scrapping the seizure of homes of the elderly
taken into care.
</TEXT>
