<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legal threat to film of `spy camera' clips</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159464</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A VIDEO compilation of ``spy camera'' clips - including a couple having sex in
a lift - was threatened with a legal ban yesterday amid claims that it had
included one police sequence without permission.
Carlton TV's lawyers demanded that Caught In The Act! should be withdrawn
immediately from high street stores or face an injunction, because it had
allegedly used material owned by its Inside Crime programme.
City of London Police said they were ``furious'' the clip from their traffic
cameras had found its way into the tape.
It came after MPs attacked the #10.99 video and called for legislation to halt
such videos.
A Carlton TV spokesman said: ``Our lawyer has sent a letter calling on the
producer Barrie Goulding to undertake to cease distribution of the video
immediately with our copyright material in it.
``Failing that, our lawyer has no hesitation in seeking an injunction to
restrain further distribution.''
The clip, showing a suspect car fleeing through a shop front, had been released
only to Inside Crime, a programme about surveillance cameras, he said.
A City of London police spokesman said: ``We are furious at the unauthorised
use of our material.
``We think the film raises the fear of crime, is salacious and invasive of
people's privacy.''
There was no immediate response from the video makers last night to the threat
of legal action.
Meanwhile, Strathclyde Chief Constable Leslie Sharp yesterday repeated a vow
made earlier this year never to release CCTV footage for public entertainment.
A police spokesman said last night: ``Under no account would the chief
constable release that sort of footage for public entertainment. We operate
under very, very strict guidelines.''
</TEXT>
