<HEADLINE>Grandfather, 92, stabbed to death Call for hospital inquiry after killing by ex-patient</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159465</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN architect, who was convinced there was a Moonie conspiracy to kill him,
stabbed his grandfather to death with nail clippers.
Nigel Gatt, 38, believed James Gatt, 92, and several friends were plotting to
murder him, the High Court in Forfar heard yesterday.
Gatt, who was suffering from religious and persecutory delusions, has been
diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic. He was ordered to be detained at the
State Hospital at Carstairs.
At least twice between 1987 and 1994 he was admitted as a patient to Royal
Cornhill Hospital, Aberdeen, and was pulled from Loch Ness last year. He was on
medication at the time of the attack.
Last night, there were calls for an inquiry into the case.
Mr John McAllion, Labour's Scottish health spokesman, called for an
investigation into why Gatt had been discharged from hospital.
``The circumstances of the case are tragic and it is obvious someone has made a
mistake, probably Cornhill,'' he said.
Mr McAllion said: ``Any lessons that can be learned from this case must be
learned. It underlines the need to maintain beds in hospitals, rather than
closing them down.''
Gatt's aunt, Gilbertha Gatt, said: ``I feel anger at the hospital and the
system that this could ever have been allowed to happen.''
She added: ``Nigel is a schizophrenic - he's not a violent murderer, he's just
ill. He needed help and we feel he was let down by the whole system.''
Dr Richard Scorgie, Grampian Healthcare medical director, said: ``I am
satisfied he received the best possible treatment. I fully support the judgment
of the clinicians in this case based on the facts available.''
Mr Scorgie added that an internal review into Gatt's case had been carried out
and a report submitted to the Mental Welfare Commission.
Detective Inspector Alan Smith, who led the inquiry, said after the case that
Gatt had told police officers that he believed it was a case of kill or be
killed.
``The battle is over. He has died. He fought bravely,'' said Gatt who, at 6ft
and weighing 15 stone, physically dominated his relative.
Gatt has been held at the State Mental Hospital at Carstairs since the murder
in the early hours of Monday, August 14.
Gatt's marriage of nine years broke up in the late 80s because of his ``mood
swings'' and he returned to Aberdeen to live with his grandparents, James and
Elizabeth.
Gatt was raised in the family home at Hollybank Place, Aberdeen, where the
killing took place.
His mother now lives in London but has been told of what happened by her family.
Police had had a number of dealings with Gatt in the hours leading up to the
death but nothing alerted them to what was to follow.
Gatt phoned them at 5.38am to say his grandfather was dead. Officers found Gatt
naked, shouting and screaming, with his victim lying in the bathroom.
In court yesterday, Gatt denied murdering his grandfather, claiming he was
insane at the time and not responsible for his actions.
The Crown and Gatt's legal team agreed that he assaulted his grandfather by
repeatedly punching him on the head and body, forcing paper into his mouth, and
repeatedly stabbing him.
They also agreed that Mr Gatt Sr died as a result of the attack and that his
grandson was suffering from paranoid schizophrenia at the time.
A psychiatrist's report, which was read to the court, said: ``He believed that
his life was in danger from the Moonies.
``Gatt did not appreciate the wrongfulness of what he was doing,'' added Mr
Thomas White, a consultant forensic psychiatrist at Carstairs.
Another pyschiatrist from Carstairs, Ms Janice Duncan, said that Gatt had
``dangerous and violent propensities'' and both specialists recommended he be
cared for at the state hospital.
Lord Gill instructed the jury to acquit Gatt on the grounds of his insanity at
the time and ordered that he be detained at Carstairs.
</TEXT>
