<HEADLINE>Government's student loans scheme comes under attack</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR, Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government's plans to allow private-sector financial institutions to enter
the student loans system came under attack last night.
Plans for banks and building societies to be allowed to compete with the
Glasgow-based Student Loans Company were criticised by MPs, who claimed the
exercise was Treasury-driven and would not benefit access to higher education.
Under the Student Loans Bill, which came up for its second reading in the
Commons yesterday, subsidies would be paid to chosen financial institutions to
enable them to make loans to students on the same preferential terms as the
existing company. Up to four institutions might be chosen through a competitive
bidding exercise.
Education and Employment Minister Eric Forth insists that students will get a
convenient and comprehensive service through access to lenders' branch
networks, and that choice will be improved, but his stance was criticised by
Scottish Labour MPs and other Opposition members.
Mrs Maria Fyfe (Glasgow Maryhill - Lab.) said students had been forced into
loans because their grants had been cut, to which Mr Forth responded that the
Government had wanted to switch the burden away from 100% reliance on grants
into loans.
Later in the exchanges, Mrs Fyfe came back at the Minister, claiming that
Citizen's Advice Bureaux in Scotland had had students coming to them asking for
help because they could not afford to buy food.
Mr Forth said he visited a number of campuses and was ``always impressed by the
number of students occupying the beer bars and enjoying the benefits of higher
education.'' He added: ``The vast majority of students run their money
responsibly and get by very well indeed. We must give support to those who
cannot, but it is wrong to suggest that all students are in hardship. It is
about how individual students manage their finances.''
Mr Tony Worthington, Labour MP for Clydebank and Milngavie, demanded to know
what the contact had been between the Chancellor and the Department for
Education and Employment to get student loans out of the public sector and
thereby help to lower Government borrowing.
Mr Forth insisted: ``Contact is close, harmonious and fruitful as ever.''
Former Scottish Minister Allan Stewart (Eastwood) said that the advantage of
using banks and building societies was that it provided them with the
opportunity, through their branch network, to build up a relationship with
students covering all their financial needs.
q.Liberal Democrat Education spokesman Don Foster told the Commons that
financial worries and fears of unemployment have led to a big rise in stress
and suicide among university students.
He had carried out a survey during the summer ``and the results were very
worrying''. He said that 72% of the 117 universities in the UK had responded to
his inquiries.
``The survey showed that, with rare exceptions, universities reported a
significant increase in the number of students seeking some form of
counselling.''
Replying, Mr Forth voiced reservations about some of the figures in the survey,
and dismissed Mr Foster's claim that drop-out rates were rising because of
stress.
Banks reject offer.................11
</TEXT>
