<HEADLINE>Libel court hears of a Tory, his spouse, the doctor, and a `nightmare' on Christmas Eve MP accuses wife of sex taunts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159467</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TORY MP told a court yesterday of his ``nightmare'' Christmas when his wife
shouted ``poofter, poofter'' at him as he prepared salad with a male friend.
Mr David Ashby told the High Court in London that his wife called him a
homosexual as a ``standard insult'' on many occasions during their 28-year
marriage. However, he said he had never had any homosexual tendencies.
Giving evidence in his libel action against the Sunday Times, Mr Ashby, 55,
said he left his wife, Silvana, in the autumn of 1993.
Mr Ashby said he had bought a flat in Putney, London, above Dr Ciaran Kilduff,
with whom Mrs Ashby became convinced he was having an affair.
Mr Ashby described a Christmas Eve in 1993 when his wife came to visit.
He and Dr Kilduff were in the kitchen washing salad when he heard a voice from
below saying ``poofters, poofters''. He went downstairs and found his wife
shouting through Dr Kilduff's letter-box.
Police arrived. His wife was still hysterical but their daughter, Alexandra,
27, managed to calm her down.
He also told the court of his friendship with Dr Kilduff. He said he started
chatting to Dr Kilduff when he viewed the flat and later booked on the same
flight to the US, where they were both heading on different trips, after Dr
Kilduff put him on to a cheap ticket agency.
During the nine-hour flight, the two talked and became friends.
``I confided in him about my life, my marriage, how I was, how I felt,
generally my unhappiness.
``It helps tremendously to talk about yourself to someone. I'd recommend it to
anyone.''
Asked by his QC, Mr Geoffrey Shaw, if he had many close friends at the time, Mr
Ashby said: ``I can honestly say I had none.''
Mrs Ashby, who had listened to much of her estranged husband's evidence with
her head in her hands, left court as he continued: ``I'd spent my life being
isolated - from my family because of Silvana's attitude. I had no close
friends, no-one to confide in.''
His daughter, who has sat at her father's side throughout the case, wiped away
tears as he said: ``I could have talked to my daughter but you can't burden
your daughter all the time. It's wrong.''
Asked if he had any homosexual inclinations at the time of his wedding, Mr
Ashby replied: ``Most certainly not. I never had then and I never have had.''
Dr Kilduff, he said, ``was and is a good friend''.
He denied ever making any admission to his wife or daughter that he was gay.
``Most certainly I didn't because to have said it would be untrue.''
Asked if his wife had made suggestions about men other than Dr Kilduff during
their marriage he said: ``Yes, on many, many, many occasions. It's almost a
standard insult actually.''
For the last six years or so of their marriage, they had fought every day, at
least once, maybe twice.
``And the fights were vicious, the language was vicious. I was very, very
unhappy. I was very depressed,'' said the MP for North-west Leicestershire.
By 1992, he had not had sex with his wife for three or four years because of
stress and depression.
His wife did talk about his impotence but not in a way to lead to discussion.
``She would say `you're no good' and that sort of thing. It was more `you're a
failure, you are not giving me much of a life'.''
Asked by Mr Shaw how he would react to the suggestion that he and Dr Kilduff
were preparing to set up home together, Mr Ashby said: ``It would be totally
and utterly untrue - and very offensive.''
In a bid to get over his ``rotten'' Christmas, Mr Ashby went to France with Dr
Kilduff. Dr Kilduff booked a room at a hotel and was offered a special rate for
a room which had one large bed.
``I didn't see any great thing about it. What was I supposed to do. Say to Dr
Kilduff `I am not sleeping with you'.''
He said they had dinner together and played cards downstairs and then he went
to the room before Dr Kilduff.
``I went to sleep and he went to sleep. Nothing more, nothing less.''
He said his wife had alleged frequently that he was having an affair with a
pupil barrister in his chambers called David, and a parliamentary research
assistant called Tim.
Mr Ashby is suing over a January 1994 article which said he had shared a bed
with a male friend on a holiday in Goa the previous November.
He says it alleged he was a practising homosexual who had misled Silvana about
the nature of his sexuality; that he had lied to the public about having an
affair with Dr Kilduff during a trip to France early in 1994; and that he was a
hypocrite in emphasising the importance of the family in his last election
address.
Times Newspapers Ltd and former Sunday Times editor Andrew Neil deny libel,
although they accept that Mr Ashby did not holiday with a man in Goa. They
assert that he was and is carrying on an affair with Dr Kilduff.
Mr Ashby said the Sunday Times story was a deliberate attempt to destroy him
and possibly bring the Government down.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
