<DOCNO>GH951128-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Battery-reared' children face increased risk of heart disease Health `time bomb' warning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAR-BASED lifestyles are creating a health ``time bomb'' for the next
generation, a doctor warned yesterday.
Dr Mayer Hillman claimed there could be an explosion in heart disease in 20 or
30 years' time caused by lack of exercise among children to whom society,
during the critical childhood years, had shown ``a careless attitude''.
He told ``The Future of Transport in Cities'' conference in Edinburgh:
``Through an oversight, we are creating a generation of battery-reared children
rather than the free-range children we were.''
Dr Hillman, senior fellow emeritus of the Policy Studies Institute - Britain's
leading independent research organisation undertaking studies of economic and
social policy - said Britain's policy on car ownership and transport planning
was limiting children's freedom of movement.
``Increasingly, the outside world is seen as a place where children are likely
to be injured by a motor vehicle or to be molested or assaulted. We have
created a generation of children denied the benefits of playing a role in life
as autonomous beings.''
He said there was also a decline in the quality of public places for children
to use as informal ``classrooms'' where they could acquire practical and social
skills and play a part in community life.
Dr Hillman said the present generation of children were also often denied the
benefits of playing a role in society's workings such as shopping and visiting,
and walking and cycling as modes of transport among children were in sharp
decline.
Warning of the consequences for their physical development without radical
change in policy, he said: ``We may have a time bomb on our hands which will
explode in 20 or 30 years when the incidence of heart disease rises sharply
owing to the insufficiency of exercise among children during the critical years
of childhood.
``And what about their character and social behaviour, the development of which
has been increasingly restricted during the early years of their lives?''
He called for a number of measures including, at transport level, a reduction
in the attractions of motorised travel and at planning level the discouragement
of longer distance patterns of travel and promotion of local activity in order
to ``re-populate streets''.
``Now that we have evidence of the harm we are doing to our children in this
country it is difficult to believe a civilised society will not wish to reverse
the process which has brought it about.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trial told box shown on video held guns</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A VIDEO recording showing a box allegedly containing terrorist weapons being
loaded into a car was shown to a jury yesterday.
The box, the High Court in Glasgow heard, contained a machine pistol and a
semi-automatic pistol, allegedly en route to the outlawed Ulster Volunteer
Force.
On trial are three Scots, a Liverpudlian, and two men from Northern Ireland.
One of the Irish accused is Lindsay Robb, 28, from Lurgan, who was a loyalist
negotiator during peace talks with the Government at Stormont earlier this year.
The others are John Johnston, 49, of Laurieston, Falkirk, Francis Hives, 45, of
Liverpool, William McArthur, 42, of Bonnybridge, David White, 29, of Airdrie,
and Alexander Davidson, 23, of Lurgan.
All six deny a plot to obtain weapons, ammunition, and explosives to further
the aims of the UVF intending to endanger life or cause serious injury to
property in the UK and Republic of Ireland.
The video film was shown during the evidence of tactical firearms officer
Constable Graham Moody, of Central Scotland Police, who told how he stopped an
estate car containing Mr McArthur, Mr Johnston, and Mr White and seized a box
containing the weapons.
He was shown a police surveillance video film which had been taken outside the
Market Public House in Prescott Road, Liverpool. It showed Mr McArthur putting
a box into the rear of the vehicle and Constable Moody agreed it appeared to be
the same box that he recovered with the guns inside it.
The court also heard about the arrest of Mr Robb at a house in Ferguson Street,
Ayr.
Detective Inspector William Prendergast of Strathclyde Police said Mr Robb was
in bed. He cautioned him and told him he had reasonable grounds to suspect that
he had been involved in the commission of, or inciting, acts of terrorism.
The officer also revealed that he took part in a search of Mr Johnston's home
at Campbell Crescent, Laurieston, where he claimed he found pieces of a handgun
under a pile of bricks in the garden.
Police firearms expert Sergeant Ronald Withers said that, although the machine
pistol had been home made, it was in working order, as was the Hungarian-made
semi-automatic pistol.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Not trams but trolleybuses</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159470</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH the nights drawn in and after I had recently returned from a week's work
in Manchester, thoughts of bringing back trams continue to rattle in my mind.
I am against the return of the tramcar to any of the streets of Scotland.
Imagine yourself in Manchester this month observing the ebb and flow of traffic
and pedestrians, prams and pushbikes. Four rails to negotiate in crossing the
street, long steel-lined holes three inches wide by three inches deep - four of
them!
A trap for pushchair wheels, heels of ladies' shoes, bike wheels, motorbike
wheels, walking-sticks, wee boys' trikes, wheelchairs, sweetie papers. And the
noise.
The teeth-edging squeal of steel wheels doing 90-degree turns and the grind of
steel against steel as the cars accelerate up to speed then grate to a halt
brought memories of being in digs at Mrs McDevit's on Great Western Road and
hearing the late trams whining away from Byres Road, clumping over Kelvin
Bridge, roaring past the digs, and vanishing with a rattle in the direction of
the Cowcaddens.
A sleep-disturbing five minute experience repeated regularly throughout each
evening.
The trolleybus is my answer. For those who do not know what this is, visit the
Transport Museum where by permission of the curator and helped by a voluntary
guide you will see and even board BUT trolleybus No 13 built in 1958. A
magnificent double-decker.
Glasgow Corporation operated a fleet of 194 trolleybuses from 1949 to 1967.
Most were double-decked but 10 were built as single-deckers and operated on the
route from Mount Florida to Shieldhall. What were the problems?
They were too quiet - you've got to be kidding - but no, they caused accidents
because of their ability to creep up on you unheard and when you stepped off
the pavement, wallop.
What are the advantages? They are very roomy; quiet, no noisy steel rails;
easily driven; they can be made in Scotland; they have battery back-up; they
are simple to maintain; no smelly and dangerous exhaust fumes; flexible road
use; can be financed by small bus operators; and have large passenger carrying
capacity.
Mind you, I would prefer a battery-powered bus but this is not feasible at
present. I dislike the thought of once again stringing disfiguring wires along
our streets but I know of no alternative.
Do those who form opinions and motivate decisions have any thoughts about
getting rid of the diesel bus and restoring the trolleybus and clean air to our
city centres?
David Beattie,
7 Hutchison Drive,
Bearsden.
</TEXT>
