<HEADLINE>Unusual share of famous men</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THANKS to Murray Ritchie (November 20) I now understand why Norway did not vote
for joining the EU. It was that obligatory poster on the Brussels Schuman metro
naming the five most famous Norwegians that did it.
If Norway had joined the EU then Vidkun Quisling (who did not have a funny
moustache) had to be on that poster together with Ibsen and Grieg (with just as
much Scottish blood as Norwegian) to make up that list of the internationally
famous Norwegian five.
Murray Ritchie is far too modest when he muses about the names on a Scotland
poster of its famous five if and when Scotland joins the EU.
For Murray Ritchie to exclude Watt from the list of famous Scots is possibly
due to carelessness but why did he exclude Dunlop (pneumatic tyre), Macintosh
(international rainwear) and Mackintosh (architectural fame), McAdam (every
asphalted road is constructed to his design criteria), the 1st Baron of Lister
(whose contribution to medicine and the saving of lives is on par with
Pasteur's contributions to medicine), Lord Kelvin (and his internationally
recognised Kelvin temperature scale), and last but not least James Clerk
Maxwell, the father of the information technology revolution?
James Clerk Maxwell is not a household name even in his native country despite
his contribution to science having been on par with Newton and Einstein. (Is
this a consequence of the Scottish education system that appears to
hero-worship the arty-farty subsidy junkies more than scientific wealth
creators?)
In fact the list of internationally famous Scots is out of proportion to its
population. And I haven't even mentioned the engineering genius Telford or W
Christie, the father of the Norwegian independence/ separatist movement and the
first president of the Norwegian Parliament, or the father of the French
banking system, or the Scot who fathered Japanese technology.
My guess is that Scotland would never join the EU. For a starter whoever is in
charge of the allocation of poster space on the Brussels Schuman metro would
never agree to the poster space required to truly reflect Scotland's
significant contribution to the civilised world.
Secondly, Scots have now lost the ability even to critically analyse why
Norway, with comparable resources to Scotland but struggling to fill a poster
of famous fives, is as an independent country on the top of the economic league
whereas Scotland lingers at the bottom.
K I Jespersen,
23 Ainslie Road,
Girvan.
</TEXT>
