<HEADLINE>Water charges High cost of quality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159473</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Secretary of State for Scotland has moved to ensure that water charges
imposed by the Government's new water boards remain relatively low. In an age
of low inflation a cap of 6% on additional charges is not exactly low but it is
far lower than the 15% which was being talked about until this week. It is
almost certainly a good deal lower than the level the water businesses require
to start funding past under-spending as well as the higher costs anyhow
required to meet the very high quality specifications laid down in the water
directives issued by the European Commission. Water itself is free at the point
of precipitation as rain, but that indisputable fact gives quite the wrong
impression whenever it is considered in relation to its use for everything in
that connection is expensive. Left to itself water flows away. It has to be
collected and the resultant works and waterways are physically significant and
may involve civil engineering works of some scale. Moreover, once established,
such systems need care and maintenance, as the present concern in England about
loss of water through leakage demonstrates. Water for domestic use has to be
clean which may not be its state untreated. Lower standards may be possible for
industry, or where sewerage is concerned, but drinking water achieves a very
high quality everywhere in Scotland - at a cost.
Because such costs are high and because some local authorities had previously
neglected to spend as much capital as was needed to keep the physical systems
at the best level, the Government hoped that privatisation would take the whole
matter out of its hands (apart from the need to implement the directives and
ensure quality but fair charges through formal regulation). At a blow the
industry would receive the money it required, the consumer would be aghast, but
have to pay up, and the very high EU quality standards, on beaches as well as
from taps, would be met. That logic explained the English privatisations but
was blown apart by the way the heads of the new companies operated them. Public
resentment about the outcome of water privatisation south of the Border ensured
that similar mechanisms could not be introduced in Scotland: the distinct
political climate here made that impossible; but it changed nothing about the
need to spend large sums of money in water improvements.
Mr Forsyth's new stance has changed nothing either, though those who actually
pay for the water may be grateful for the fact that they will feel the pain of
paying somewhat less than they might have done. That, at any rate, is the
straightforward political calculation involved in the cap. Consumers will not
be up in arms at double-digit increases on their water bills and so an area of
political awareness which is totally unfavourable to the Government will
steadily lose its salience; even, possibly, Ministers will be viewed as water
users' friends. This is a testament to the power of democracy and the nature of
politics. It need not even mean that the required investment in the water
industry need be abandoned if the Government withdraws its opposition to
borrowing and allows part of the increased charges to be interest payments
rather than capital costs. Alternatively, it merely means deferring spending
which will have to take place one day, the very habit which produced the
under-funding now requiring to be addressed. Today's water payers may thank Mr
Forsyth but their successors may have a very different reaction. In between
lies the next General Election, certain to be hard fought.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
