<HEADLINE>Where Scots feel most at home</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Linklater</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Airdrie is a town which apparently boasts the highest concentration of
Scots-born people anywhere. John Linklater investigates a population phenomenon
AIRDRIE is bemused by its new status as the most Scottish town in Britain.
After decades suffering negative images founded on high unemployment,
sectarianism with its neighbour Coatbridge, and the unhappy accolade of heart
attack capital of the world, it has grown sensitive to unsolicited distinctions
awarded by outsiders, suspecting a catch.
With possible justification. Say something nice to an Airdrieonian and they
will suspect you of trying to get smart. The latest compliment could prove a
highly backhanded way of applying population statistics. Daniel Dorling, of the
geography department at the University of Newcastle, has started something with
research that focuses on Monklands District as boasting the highest
concentration of Scots-born people anywhere. That apparently makes Airdrie, and
Coatbridge for that matter, the most ethnically undiluted community in the
nation.
This is news to Airdrie. At the Weavers Cottages Museum on Frith-Rathad An
Tobair (as Wellwynd has been dual-linguistically signposted since the Mod came
here two years ago) it is gently pointed out there is little historical
justification for the claim. At each stage of the industrial revolution
Monklands attracted huge influxes from the Highlands and Ireland, weavers and
colliers and steel workers. Curator Allan MacKenzie, an East Kilbride man, is
highly sceptical.
Besides, the researchers' figure of less than 4% of Monklands people coming
from outwith Scotland (compared to 8% throughout the rest of Scotland) looks
suspiciously as though it might invite another construction. It could be yet
another form of putdown of Airdrie, implying it is the least attractive place
in Scotland anyone would want to move into.
Local pride will not stand for that. The town is just finishing its
celebrations of 300 years since it received its Market Charter by Act of
Scottish Parliament. The current best-selling video in town is Airdrie: A Brief
History. If you want to buy a copy you will have to wait until new supplies
arrive later this week. The film-maker, Robert Letham, might be able to help,
according to Airdrie Public Library. He lives in Mull. This turns out to be
Mull, the Airdrie housing estate. They don't need any tourists or incomers to
patronise their heritage.
``There are only two kinds of people,'' says 22-year-old Iain Allison, a recent
graduate of Glasgow Caledonian University. ``There are Airdrieonians and people
who want to be Airdrieonians.'' Taking us for the latter, he outlines the
attractions: ``There is unemployment, problems with heart disease and
alcoholism, and not much life. But I'm an ardent Airdrieonian and I walk up the
town with a sense of pride. I will be a very disappointed man if I ever have to
move out of here. I want to die here.''
Barman Gary MacKay had two years in Manchester where he encountered ``the most
ignorant bunch of people I have met in my life''. He came to his senses and
returned to his native Airdrie. The happiest moment in his kindred relationship
with Airdrie was finding a bottle of 12-year-old whisky from the local
Inverhouse Distillery at a service station outside of Milan. He read the export
label, proclaiming Product Of Airdrie, and felt great.
Neither is this the furthest that Airdrie sons have travelled, and felt drawn
back. Bobby Flavell, wartime football star of Airdrieonians FC, was playing in
the same side as Alfredo Di Stefano with the Millianarios of Bogota in
Colombia. ``Bogota was a lot hotter,'' he concedes. But out in his bunnet on
Graham Street, having a good natter with two old fiends, this seems a
superfluous advantage to the warmth of local camaraderie in a town which was
his birthplace in 1921.
``Coatbridge was famous for coal and steel,'' says his mate, John Dougan. ``And
Airdrie was famous for stealing coal.'' There may be a severe lack of pitheads
from which to carry on this local enterprise, and there may be no more
Broomfield at which to admire the skills of latter-day Flavells, but Airdrie
survives undaunted.
The search for an immigrant presence does, however, prove difficult. Lisa
McLaren, who has spent years of her young life in culturally alien places as
Edinburgh, Livingston, and Teneriffe, likes the slow-paced and welcoming
atmosphere of the town. But she is really from Glasgow. At the Big Apple
Amusements arcade we find a lady who once lived in Northampton and couldn't
stand it. There are plenty of folk who make it clear they are not from Airdrie
at all, but from Caldercruix or Chapelhall or Glenboig, anxious to make the
distinction of a few miles.
Finally, we catch up with June McKenna back where we started at the museum. She
came to Airdrie 20 years ago from London. ``It's a better sense of humour
here,'' she explains. ``It's more a Billy Connolly sense of humour than in
London.'' Tell that to the researchers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The New Alliance, Queen's Hall, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159475</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE its political prototype, the ``New Alliance'' is Franco-Scottish, a series
of five Edinburgh concerts by mostly French performers featuring mostly French
music promoted by the French Institute of Scotland. The aims are ambitious, and
Radio Three is recording the results, which last night placed Poulenc's
beautiful, unsettling violin sonata in a not wholly appropriate context of
Richard Strauss and Beethoven.
With instrumentalists as talented as Raphael Oleg and Eric Le Sage, it was to
be expected that Poulenc's characteristically oblique and poetic elegy on the
death of Federico Garcia Lorca would receive a particularly perceptive
performance, and so on the whole it proved. But both here, as in the rest of
the programme, the effect was undermined by a failure to strike a satisfactory
balance between violin and piano tone. Playing with the lid fully open, Le Sage
sometimes swamped his partner.
Yet in a curious way the more virile passages worked better than the
introspective ones, where Poulenc's fine-grained melodies lacked their
essential soft gleam. But the ending, when it came, carried the right sense of
shock, and Poulenc's very French vein of bitter-sweetness contrasted tellingly
with the richer, more self-indulgent sentiment of Strauss's early violin sonata.
Finally, there was Beethoven's Kreutzer in a performance that did not lack
sweep but never came fully into focus. The heavy piano tone, and the pianist's
noisy pedalling, were unfortunate distractions for which the good points of the
rest of the playing never completely compensated.
</TEXT>
