<TEXT>
BRITISH Investment Trust kept pace with its bench-      mark index during the
six months      to September 30 and announced a modest increase in the interim
dividend, writes ROBERT POWELL.
Net asset value of the  #788.5m trust rose 12.4% to 253p.
This was right in line with a 12.4% rise in the MSCI World index in sterling
terms, but a shade less than the FT Actuaries All-Share index, which rose 12.7%.
Earnings per share fell back after being inflated by two large dividends in the
first half of 1994, which were missed in the first half of this year because of
a change in the timing of payouts.
But as a gesture of confidence, the trust raised its interim dividend by 4.8%
to 2.1p and promised to maintain this increase in the final.
The trust, managed by Edinburgh Fund Managers, aims for long-term capital and
income growth. Its largest single investment is an #88m stake in Edinburgh Fund
Managers itself.
