<DOCNO>GH951128-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>People, not profits, are what matter to award-winning Camphill Architects</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>AILEEN LITTLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159478</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Building on natural principles
AT around the age of nine, Rudolph Steiner believed, children should be
introduced to forms of work based on craft and skill, knowledge of materials,
and the environment. He went so far as to advocate a spell of housebuilding.
Recognising the educational value of drawing up plans and calculations,
therefore, the Austrian humanist would have thoroughly approved of an unusual
architectural practice based in a Deeside community run on Steiner lines.
Led by Wolodymr Radysh and David Sutherland, Camphill Architects lies at the
heart of the 145-acre Newton Dee Camphill community for handicapped adults,
five miles from Aberdeen.
The firm specialises in an ``organic'' style of architecture, characterised by
rounded forms, natural materials and colour-washed walls in therapeutic shades,
which bears out Steiner principles. It was one of the first offices of its kind
in the world and, 20 years on, is now the largest in Britain.
Worldwide, there are 80 communities like Newton Dee, with eight in Scotland.
Being in the unusual position of having a large and stable client base in the
British communities (continental ones tend to employ their own architects)
Camphill Architects has never needed to tender for business in the commercial
world - although it does accept mainstream commissions and is in competition
with other architects for work in UK Camphills.
``Between 50% and 70% of our work is with Scottish communities,'' David
Sutherland explained. ``The remainder is split between the rest of Britain,
including Ireland, and eastern Europe. We've also done a care house in the USA.
One of our architects (the practice employs six, plus a mentally-handicapped
adult) recently returned from Israel. We move around a lot.''
Increasingly, this type of architecture is being recognised and valued by the
wider community too. CA was commissioned to design a church for the Christian
Community in Aberdeen. But it is in the realm of caring establishments that its
soothing brand of social consciousness really comes into its own. The #600,000
Blackthorn Medical Centre in Maidstone, for example, was designed for people
suffering from serious or long-term illness, and patients who use it are
shielded from sensory jolts of all kinds.
The success of this building led to a commission for St Luke's Medical Centre
in Stroud. ``We've completed our documentation work and building starts next
year,'' Mr Sutherland said.
Last week, the Royal Institute of British Architects bestowed its White Rose
Award on CA's design for a church at Botton Camphill Community in Yorkshire.
But while such accolades afford satisfaction, CA is not in the business of
accruing profit. Three of its professionals are self-employed and salaried; the
other three receive no salary and are supported by the Newton Dee community
where they live as house-parents. Mr Sutherland is one of them.
``When I go home, I'm caring for the needs of eight handicapped adults. In our
architectural practice and our workshops, all profits are ploughed back into
the community,'' he said. The practice tries to avoid complicated accounting,
charging the same rate for all its work. ``We do lose out on some projects. The
building is of paramount importance - profit isn't our guiding principle.''
Turnover is #165,000.
Since Camphill communities came into existence more than 50 years ago, there
has been a feeling they have remained too isolated from the ``real'' world. Mr
Sutherland, an Australian who practiced in that real world until he was 42 and
has since tutored part-time at the Scott Sutherland School of Architecture,
explained that in some respects integration had been forced upon them.
``With the advent of registration, most of the communities are now licensed
care establishments - we've had to interface with regulations like stipulated
size for bedrooms and fire precautions.''
But external pressures can only help to dispell any idiosyncratic notions
surrounding these communities which were set up to respect human individuality.
A proposed social centre and workshops in the Newton Dee community should build
on this new awareness of society as a whole. CA recently completed plans for a
#630,000 coffee/gift shop accessible to the public.
The natural timber structure in the shape of a crescent reflects its woodland
setting. It will have a clay-tiled roof and express the characteristic
``Steiner'' style - a design for flesh and blood.
``We try to make all forms organic, to make them to relate to the function of a
building,'' Mr Sutherland said. ``We're not averse to the rectangle, but we do
try not to be dominated by it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CHECK-IN</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JANE SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>check in</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975159479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n MILLS &amp; Boon gets saucy this Christmas with a romance revival kit of 365 Ways
To Be Romantic (at #4.99 almost certainly a more economical way of repairing
the parlous state of marriage in Britain than through reform of the divorce
laws) which suggests making love in the bathtub or even kidnapping your lover
alongside sure fire winners like ``Place a flower on her pillow. Just because.
. .''; although the gay abandon of ``Everyone should, at one time or another in
his or her life, go skinny-dipping'' seems a wee bit optimistic even in a mild
November.
n IN preparation for those wild romantic nights, Cutex suggests a daily workout
for the lips to exercise the surrounding muscles and keep them in shape; this
involves pressing a kiss against a finger (preferably your own) held up to the
lips for a count of five; no clenching of teeth or allowing the tongue to press
against the roof of the mouth, however: ``This would just create tension in the
wrong areas.'' French kissing, one assumes, would simply wreak havoc with your
muscle tone.
n BETTER to settle down with a good book; and in the romantic vein, Scottish
Love Stories, published by Polygon on Thursday, looks set to be a bit of an eye
opener. ``Tales of love and desire, lust and passion, romance and a touch of
humour'' are promised from new Scottish authors, gay and lesbian writers and
well-known favourites.
n ON the subject of another form of writing, publicity for Maggie Black's new
Jane Austen Cookbook says the volume features ``dishes which Jane Austen
herself, and famous characters like Mr Darcy from Pride and Prejudice would
have enjoyed''; whereas anyone who saw the delicious Colin Firth bristling away
as Darcy in the recent BBC adaptation would know he had very little stomach for
anything but standing glowering by the fire; indeed, one can hardly imagine him
sitting down to anything like a hearty meal, unless it were a dish of sour
grapes, perhaps, or or a final helping of humble pie.
n EATING features prominently on the new Ryvita publicity campaign; a five-step
guide to health. 1, exercise; 2, eat little and often (ie Ryvita); 3, healthy
breakfast (hello, Ryvita again); 4, stock up on carbohydrate and fibre (guess
what); 5, cut down on fat (I'll spare you the details). In case you're finding
the whole thing rather difficult to swallow you're also offered fun new ways to
enjoy the Ryvita experience, all of which involve a trip down to the deli or
the expensive bit of M &amp; S for salmon and walnut halves. Good try, but you can
have rather too much of a good thing, you know.
n BUT not in the bedrooms of Britain, apparently, where the average frequency
of sex has dropped over the last year, according the Durex Report 1995. Yes,
for those who can remember, it's averaging out at 70 times a year, down from
1994's high of 73. The survey also found that fewer people are worried about
contracting HIV - although the numbers indulging in unprotected sex are slowly
dropping (and that means more condoms sold; good news for Durex, there, one
imagines). And finally, we learn that more than 60 per cent of us buy our
condoms in chemists, although the report draws our attention to the
``significant'' 8 per cent who rely on vending machines - a figure which would
have been far more significant if it had included the thousands of hopefuls who
feed their money through the slot with nary a sign of a packet in sight, being
then too embarrassed to complain to the management.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Now cross dressing assumes new mantle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159480</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Cressida Wilson may dismiss her acclaimed play as simply ``sexy and funny'',
but Sara Villiers discovers a highly-crafted and lyrical work
SHE makes a living out of drama but Erin Cressida Wilson insists her life is
not a dramatic one. Her play Cross Dressing in the Depression won her great
acclaim when it premiered in San Francisco and immediately transferred off
Broadway in 1993, but hers is neither a tale of a starving artist in a
Manhattan garret nor an overnight success.
``It's hard for me to describe my career because the truth is it's always been
very steady,'' shrugs the 32-year-old New York playwright. ``It's never been
horrible and it's never been incredibly successful.''
Renowned in her home country, her work is about to be introduced to a wider
audience. Peter Mackie Burns is to direct the European premiere of Cross
Dressing in the Depression, at the Traverse Theatre in Edinburgh. It is the
story of a man haunted by a childhood of being brought up in a brothel.
Cressida Wilson wrote the drama over a number of years. ``It takes ages to
write a play,'' she says with a self-deprecation which belies the fact she has
written 17 plays over the past 10 years - and originally populated Cross
Dressing with 25 characters.
``It finally dawned on me that with the state of theatre and finance being what
it was, it would never get produced so I changed it, at first to a
two-character play for me and my best friend and then to a three-character
play.''
She reduced the characters by the expediency of playing all the female roles
herself, a task to be undertaken by Molly Innes in Edinburgh, but says although
she originally trained as an actress and always supplemented her play writing
income with spells on the stage and in soap operas she does not normally write
for herself.
``Cross Dressing is the only play of my own that I've acted in and I haven't
acted in every production of it. Each time it's been done, it has been done
very differently but it's always been done very beautifully. There has actually
been some cross dressing productions of the play. New York, the little boy, has
been played by a woman who was wonderful, she was 36-years-old but everyone who
saw it believed she was a 15-year-old boy.
``And there has been a production where the old man has been played by a woman
too, which is fascinating because of the pre-sexuality of the boy and the
post-sexuality of the old man. The energy of the woman is really interesting in
those roles.''
Currently teaching play writing at Duke University, she regards herself as an
uncategorisable writer.
``Well, I'm not writing about popular things - ie I'm not writing about gay
themes which seems to be all that anyone in New York is writing about just
now.''
HER most recent play is Hurricane, which she muses is about ``five people in a
one act play of related scenes on the subject of the war in America on gender,
sex, women and the right to be alone.''
Asked if she is a feminist, she answers with a response typical of her
generation. ``No. Yes. Of course. I was young enough to take that for granted,
but it got shoved in my face so much when I was at college, which was an all
women college, I got turned off.''
She reflects that as she gets older she understands feminism more. ``When
you're in your twenties and doing stuff everyone thinks that you're pretty
cute, you know what I mean? But there really is something that happens to you
when you come 30 and I didn't anticipate that.
``Now I'm not sure about things any more and I think the way I feel is
expressed in Hurricane - about the real honest to goodness need for something
to happen, for things to change. I mean, you realise that the socio-economic
history of women really is a case of rape all the time and I know that sounds
melodramatic but it's true and it's a very big struggle for me in my mind.''
Cressida Wilson is self-consciously ironic about the politically correct
stranglehold on culture in the States. ``There's this big joke in America just
now that the worst thing you can be is a white man and to some extent there's
something in that but basically it's a lot of bullshit.''
She cuts her conversation short with the remark that she hates to theorise
about her own work, summarising that what she has to say is about ``not making
statements''.
However, for all her dismissive comments of Cross Dressing in the Depression as
being simply ``sexy and funny'' it made a big enough noise to be included in a
collection of the best plays of 1993, while the deeply lyrical quality of her
work is recognised to the extent Hurricane is being published in the American
Poetry Review. Cressida Wilson might not like making statements but she's
certainly worth listening to.
n Cross Dressing in the Depression, Traverse Theatre, Edinburgh, December 3-10.
</TEXT>
