<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Striking out against a tide of fear</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sue Innes</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159481</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scottish women are mobilising in an offensive aimed at putting issues of
violence and abuse firmly on the agenda, as SUE INNES discovers
ON Saturday in Edinburgh a group of around 30 women held up traffic in Princes
Street with a banner saying ``Stop Trafficking in Women''. It was the first
direct action by a new group called Feminist Offensive - and they promise more.
The women who set up FO all work or volunteer for Scottish organisations
already involved in day to day support services to survivors of rape and other
violence, and in more conventional campaigning against violence against women.
In that everyday work they see the connections between the kinds of violence
against women and children, and to social and political issues, but felt it has
become less possible to express that.
``We all believe that all violence against women and children is linked, and is
part of a wider societal problem. But in our work you're mainly focusing on
individuals and on single issues, for example you might only be working with
incest survivors. And in campaigning, again you tend to focus on one aspect,
domestic violence, say. There was a gap in terms of an organisation able to
campaign more broadly and in a feminist way. And we wanted to do something,
well, a bit spikier . . .''
The constraints on what organisations can say when they depend on local and
central government funding is also a factor; FO is completely independent.
I spoke to two members of the group, in Edinburgh and Glasgow and, for now
anyway, they think it best to remain anonymous - ``as much because we don't
want the group to be identified with any one individual or organisation. We're
not working that way.''
Their idea is to be pro-active. ``We're always so reactive - whether it's
commenting on legislation, or what- ever - we're responding to what someone
else has decided is important. ``For organisations working against violence -
and also for underfunded feminist organisations - it's all crisis work. You're
responding to a phone call, a woman at the door or whatever. But we realised
that if we wanted a feminist perspective on violence to be in the mainstream we
were going to have to put it there.''
The emphasis at the centre of the group's message is that, as articulated in
the Zero Tolerance campaign, ``male abuse of power is a crime''. ``We live in a
society where men have more power than women. This power is built into the way
the country is run.'' Not all men benefit from it to the same extent, nor all
women suffer from it to the same extent; but some men abuse this power in order
to hold on to it.
``All women live with the fear of male violence, whatever their age, race,
sexuality and ability. It is our experience that in our homes and in our
communities men use emotional, sexual, financial and physical violence to
control women.''
So many women who have suffered domestic violence talk of being battered for
not getting the tea on the table at the right time, or for behaving ``wrongly''
according to varying rules. The belief that what happens behind closed doors is
best kept there and that it is important to keep family secrets is still a
powerful force.
Family violence is presented as unusual by ignoring the evidence for its
prevalence and by identifying it with people who are ``not like us''. But we
cannot, they argue, even talking of extreme cases like the West family, make a
separation between abuse which is enabled by power relationships and social
neglect and abusers who are sick: ``They are one and the same and violence
against children in families is not unusual.''
The more domestic and sexual violence are being paid public and political
attention, they argue, the more it is being seen as pathological, as about
individual aberrance. The debate, they say, is shifting away from seeing it as
a problem of power, and inequality - between women and men, between adults and
children, and of economic power and dependence. ``The response to the Rosemary
West case is an example. It's extreme but it's being talked about in a way that
reinforces a false message that child abuse only happens in dysfunctional
families, or where there is a cycle of abuse - but we know it happens in
`ordinary' families.''
Recent research in Glasgow and London emphasises that although they are seen as
separate, domestic violence, sexual abuse and child sexual abuse can be
strongly interlinked, with domestic violence sometimes used to facilitate and
to disguise child sexual abuse.
Saturday was chosen to start the campaign as it was International Day of
Protest against Violence against Women, with a programme of events in Scottish
cities, and around the world. FO is controversial in the women's movement,
partly because of the military connotations of its name. However, the group's
main concern is to find ways to influence the political agenda, as well as to
counter some of the myths and false messages or emphases in the ``violence
debate''.
Law-abiding events, like conferences and press releases, are not ruled out
either. ``Any effective method, as long as it isn't violent.''
Saturday's focus on the international trade in women and children for
prostitution and pornography was to emphasise that it's a huge problem, and
it's not just ``over there''. There is growing evidence of women from the Third
World being brought to Europe under false pretences and finding themselves
trapped in the sex industry; and sex tourism has become a fact of life.
Research by a coalition formed by Christian Aid and others shows that a high
proportion of those who travel to the Far East for under-age sex are from
Britain. The group are particularly concerned at how successfully the Internet
has added a sinister new dimension and is facilitating international links for
prostitution as well as allowing a massive increase in the spread of child
pornography. ``There's one firm called, if you can believe it, Pimps`R'Us who
offer a four-day package to the Dominican Republic with computer lessons thrown
in to make it tax deductible!''
Advertising Thai, Filipino, Russian and Romanian women for sex and the
explosion of paedophile links through the Internet may seem a distant and
almost intractable problem - ``but it's in Scottish living rooms, perhaps even
schools''. We need to recognise that ``Western money is funding it and buying
it.''
It may seem too huge a problem and remote, certainly from Saturday afternoon
shopping - yet in Princes Street shops you can find ``top shelf'' magazines
with barely-coded advertisements for child pornography. And our refusal as a
society to address these issues is spelled out in that fact that the Obscene
Publications Squad has only 17 officers in the UK. ``Even as feminists we make
excuses, we look the other way. Lots of women and men would be outraged at the
thought that they were condoning rape and abuse - why is it that everyone goes
silent when you talk about porn?''
The use of ``soft porn'' magazines to provide access to more ``specialist''
pornography is a major concern, but also the way that as adult porn becomes
both more acceptable and more extreme, this may be (as the police believe)
fuelling more extreme, bizarre and violent material in the `hard core'. And
``whether it is getting worse is difficult to say - but it is certainly
becoming more available.''
A change in international or country law will not help, they believe, unless
social attitudes and ignorance changes first, until we stop averting our eyes.
</TEXT>
