<HEADLINE>The season for red-nosed pain fears</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Every year experts warn a flu virus will sweep the country. Margaret Vaughan
examines the syptoms but finds accurate prognosis is no easy task
SORE head, shivery, aching, with a cough like a barking seal? Feeling like a
close first cousin of death? Feel in need of some tender care and sympathy?
Tough. It's only flu.
On the other hand, it may not be. If after 48 hours or so you are still hacking
and broiling you may be suffering from microplasma pneumoniae. Never mind. It's
not as bad as it sounds, so buck up.
It could be worse. It might be respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). On the other
hand, it may be no more than a snuffling cold so stop whining, take a
paracetamol and wait until you feel better.
If you think this a flippant response to the predicament of all those tucked
up, groaning, in bed with a raging fever, don't blame me. Just you try talking
to public health consultants around the country, the people you feel should
empathize with your runny nose and wheezy chest and desperate calls for another
hot toddy before it's too late.
Dire warnings from experts that a flu epidemic threatens at Christmas have
become as seasonal as the Queen's Message, if less reliable in delivery. So
will there be, as the Royal College of Practitioners in England predicted
yesterday, a raging epidemic this year? Hard to say. Because, when you analyse
all the figures, digest the statistics, follow the flow charts, and get right
down to it, no-one really has a clue.
The odds are slightly lower than winning the lottery, but not as good as
putting a tenner on the favourite at Kelso.
Dr Charles Saunders, the consultant in public health for Fife Health Board,
says that compared with this time last year, across Scotland there have been
more cases of flu reported by ``spotter practices'', GPs who report on numbers
of flu-like cases.
The strain showing up this year is mainly influenza A, while last year it was
influenza B, the type more commonly associated with major epidemics.
Dr Saunders says:, ``Now, in general, influenza is not a serious illness.
People who have it feel like death but they usually recover within a relatively
short time without treatment beyond fluids, painkillers and rest.
``There are certain people with pre-existing medical conditions who are more
vulnerable to flu, such as those with heart, lung or kidney infections, the
frail elderly, very young children or people whose immune system is not working
as it should. They ought to have been offered a flu jab in October, or early
November to protect them.
``So what you have left are relatively fit adults for whom immunisation is not
recommended, and although flu makes you feel rotten, that's an end of it.''
Major epidemics tend to come when there is a major change in the strain of flu
rampaging around the world: if the strain has mutated, fewer people will have
developed antibodies to it. There is no evidence at all this year that a
mutating flu virus is about to strike . . .yet.
``I can't predict it. All I can say is there are no indications we have a
radical strain of flu circulating at the moment,'' says Dr Saunders.
Feeling better then? Ah but . . . ``The difficulty is that although the experts
know what strains have been around, what they don't know is how many people
have antibodies to that strain. It is a reasonably educated guess. What you
can't do is predict accurately what is going to happen in the future.
In Fife, for instance, reported cases were much higher than last year, but in
recent weeks have gone down. Whether that's because fewer people are calling
out their doctors or whether there are fewer cases around is difficult to
predict.
Dr Saunders confides: ``I would not stick any money on either.''
Why do flu outbreaks always occur around this time anyhow? ``A question I've
often asked myself, and no-one knows - but there is a theory that various new
strains start to spread from the Far East and China.
``It's thought that the virus spreads backwards and forwards between humans and
some animals, particularly pigs. Because, in those areas, humans live in closer
contact with their animals than in the developed world, the theory runs that
the virus goes backwards and forwards between the rural farmer and his stock.
``It just so happens that by the time it reaches Europe it happens to be around
Christmas.
``The other factor is that the virus transmits more readily when windows and
doors are closed and fires are blazing.''
Dr Ian Stewart, consultant in public health medicine for Greater Glasgow Health
Board, says the flu figures were creeping up in November. However, the figures
are not precise, and neither is the diagnosis always accurate. It is a very
rough and ready tally. This can be because the illness is ``flu-like'' as
opposed to flu. The RSV bug which swept the country last year can seem like
flu, as can microplasma pneumoniae. Both respond to antibiotics, because they
are bugs, while flu does not because it is a virus. So how do you know the
difference?
``You can't. You'll have to wait for 48 hours and if you're cough is no better,
call out your family doctor.''
There you have it. A flu epidemic may be on the way. Or it may not not. If your
head is birling, if you feel the urge to lie down, wrap up warm but don't
expect any sympathy. It's only flu.
</TEXT>
