<HEADLINE>Speaker to concentrate on plans to balance budget. Gingrich not to run for president</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEWT Gingrich, Speaker of the House of Representatives, announced today that he
will not run for president next year. The decision leaves Senator Bob Dole in a
yet stronger position to win the Republican nomination.
Gingrich has made no secret of his ambitions, but concluded that 1996 would not
be the year for him.
In a news conference in Marietta, Georgia, in his district office, he said that
he would ``postpone the decision to a long way down the road''. He added that
he could not imagine any new circumstances that might change his mind.
``We've decided that we would explicitly, definitely close the door so there's
no more speculation. I will not run next year for president,'' Gingrich said.
``My intent is to run for re-election to the House and hopefully be speaker
again.''
He said that he had decided to miss next year's election in order to
concentrate on the Republican programme in Congress.
``Looking at the way things are developing,'' he said. ``We are a month behind
where I hoped we would be in balancing the budget.''
He asserted that his legislative programme, of which the balanced budget was
the centre-piece, was the most important in 60 years. He expects to complete it
in the course of the next year.
Gingrich said he thought it would be difficult to be speaker and run a national
campaign for president. ``I agree with my family and many constituents that my
work as speaker of the House is more important at this time as we work on
balancing the budget and renewing the American dream,'' he said in a statement
released by his office.
He told said the budget battle was ``the most important single decision about
the future of our children and grandchildren and it's very important that we
really focus over the next few weeks to make sure we actually get to a balanced
budget that's real, that occurs in seven years and that changes things.''
Clinton and the Republican-led Congress remain divided over tax and spending
priorities and over ways to balance the budget. Their dispute partly closed the
government for six days this month, the longest such shutdown.
He also suggested that the election could be the ``wildest'' in years. He
speculated that there might be five candidates: Republican, Democratic,
moderate Democratic, plus Ross Perot and Jesse Jackson.
A number of departing and former members of Congress met over Thanksgiving to
discuss the possibility of running a candidate. They included Paul Tsongas, who
ran against President Clinton in the Democratic primaries in 1992, Ben Bradley,
Democratic senator in New Jersey who is not running next year.
It was an exploratory meeting, and despite Gingrich's hopes, it does not seem
probable that it will nominate anyone. Tsongas conceded that the group would
not put up a candidate unless he stood a chance of winning, for fear of
siphoning votes from President Clinton and helping the Republicans.
Gingrich had been toying with the idea of running in the Republican primaries
for months, and stirred up constant speculation. His supporters contend that
Senator Dole cannot defeat President Clinton.
On the other hand, all the polls show that Gingrich is deeply unpopular and
would do even worse against the president. He was asked this morning about his
unpopularity, and answered that he was no more unpopular now than was Barry
Goldwater when he won the Republican nomination in 1964.
Gingrich, who is a historian, had apparently forgotten that Goldwater went down
to the worst defeat in modern American politics.
Meanwhile, US Senate Republican leader Bob Dole today won the endorsement of
Wisconsin Governor Tommy Thompson in his front-running bid for the Republican
Party's presidential nomination.
Thompson, who had once been reported to be considering a run for the nomination
himself, said Dole ``stands head and shoulders above the rest of the Republican
field.''
He said Dole ``stood firm in the battle for a balanced budget against Bill
Clinton and his liberal Democratic allies. And when push came to shove, Bill
Clinton blinked. Because of Bob Dole's leadership.......the American people
will have the first balanced budget in a generation.''
Dole named Thompson a national co-chairman of his campaign.
</TEXT>
