<HEADLINE>Gaining Ground, Assembly Rooms, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159484</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AGAIN, we're looking at the results of having a full-time support agency, in
this case Edinburgh's Dance Base, available as a resource not just for
dance-makers but also for programmers. The Assembly Alive! season has
undoubtedly benefitted from the local audience that turns out for Dance Base
events.
Dance Base has, in its turn, been able to present programmes of new works in a
professionally-rigged and well-equipped space - something their own budget
doesn't really run to as often as the team would like. Saturday's double bill
of new work was labelled Gaining Ground.
Whereas the previous night's programme, Springboard, had tended towards the
unfledged end of the spectrum, this package had a more considered, experienced
feel to it even if the works themselves were capable of further thought and
development.
MOR - Brigid McCarthy's solo, an Assembly Alive! commission - confirmed her
interest in the ``mechanics'' of movement: What comes before a fall, what
follows the momentum of a roll? Movement, when taken down into its component
parts can seem just academic to an audience, but McCarthy has a sense of humour
and a breezy kind of confidence that is very eye-catching. The introduction of
middle-of-the-road music after initial silence really perked the piece into
Gidget Goes Minimalist.
There were echoes of early V-TOL in the fast, energised bursts of dance that
punctuated Tears Before Bedtime's foray into inner space, entitled Honest.
Individuals whose lives are hinted at through amplified phone calls come
together but don't really relate - all they seem to share is an occasional
frenzy of isolation.
When it moves, it moves quite purposefully but the framework, like the
phonecalls, stays a shade too indistinct to make us connect with the ideas
lurking somewhere in the atmospheric shadows.
</TEXT>
