<HEADLINE>Gulliver's troubles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack Webster</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
There were many losers in the war for Distillers, but one man refused to stay
beaten. Jack Webster looks at the lives transformed by a takeover scandal
ONCE hailed as Scotland's most successful business figure, the man with the
Midas touch, James Gulliver can relax in his gracious Edinburgh townhouse and
talk philosophically about that high drama of the eighties which changed the
course of his life.
The grocer's son from Campbeltown, who rose to form his massive Argyll Group,
owner of supermarkets like Safeway and Presto, was commonly acknowledged as the
principal victim of the 1986 takeover scandal in which Guinness gained control
of Distillers, Scotland's largest company.
It came to court as the industrial story of the century and ended with the
chairman of the gigantic drinks company, Ernest Saunders, and two other City
figures being sent to prison in 1990 for the methods used in winning that
battle, at the expense of Gulliver's Argyll.
Careers were wrecked and fortunes changed as Saunders, the Viennese-born son of
an obstetrician who came to Britain in 1938, led the trek to jail.
Sentences now served, the matter went belatedly to the Court of Appeal, with
talk of fresh evidence bringing the whole Guinness trial back into the public
arena. But now that appeal has been dismissed.
So what has happened to the various parties involved - from the directors of
Distillers to the men who found themselves as Her Majesty's unwelcome guests?
James Gulliver now plies between his house in Chelsea and the Edinburgh one
where Robert Louis Stevenson would once have been a neighbour.
On the question of yesterday's court decision, he told me: ``I'm delighted the
appeal has been thrown out. Indeed, if it had gone the other way I would
personally have taken legal action against those involved.''
Pondering what might have been, Gulliver says: ``If Argyll had won the takeover
battle we would have been one of the largest companies in Britain. So yes, I
still feel cheated.
``It was very disappointing that we failed to acquire Distillers because of the
malpractice which existed on the other side. I felt a bit cynical after it was
over and decided to leave Argyll and spend more time in Scotland. But you
cannot go on harbouring regret because that is a very unhealthy thing to do.''
Gulliver's place as boss of Argyll was taken by his chief lieutenant,
fellow-Scot Alistair Grant, and the public perception was that his position was
not helped by a revelation, attributed to the ``dirty tricks'' department, that
an entry in Who's Who was untrue.
He was gone and a career which had been hailed as a model to students of
business shrewdness began to lose direction.
He became executive chairman at the home furnishings chain of Lowndes Queensway
but times were bad.
``Interest rates were soaring, consumer spending was drying up and we ran into
difficulties,'' he remembers. ``The banks came up with a re-financing package
but I decided to resign.''
He became chairman of the 200-year-old Edinburgh stationery firm of Waverley
Cameron, with a 30% stake and high hopes for its development. But that too
struck difficult times and they parted company.
Of his London-based interests, City Gate Estates was sold to a Swedish group
and his Broad Street public relations firm went to French owners.
Diverted by the Distillers battle and unable to give full attention to his
vice-chairmanship of Manchester United FC, Gulliver sold his 16% of the Old
Trafford club for less than #500,000, a decision he deeply regrets.
From there it was onwards to a similar post at Heart of Midlothian, where he
was welcomed by chairman Wallace Mercer, but when the Edinburgh property man
moved out and went to live in France, Gulliver relinquished his football ties.
So where does that leave him now, at the age of 65? ``More relaxed than if I
had been running a giant company,'' he smiles. ``We have family property
interest in London and Manchester, the top-quality Lords of the Manor hotel
near Cheltenham and two farms in Fife. I'm reasonably well-off and pretty
happy.''
Outwith the family investments, Gulliver is backing a Crinan company which is
farming scallops on the seabed. And he has taken a financial interest in the
Drum and Monkey pub in the centre of Glasgow, which has also opened up in
Edinburgh.
Just occasionally, he confesses, there is an itch for the bigger-time but he
generally thinks better of it.
So what of the others involved in the saga? John Connell was chairman of
Distillers in that 1980s period when the business view was that he was leading
a fuddy-duddy company which lacked consistent growth and aggressive management.
It had slipped in whisky markets, hit not least by two brands outwith its
umbrella, Bells and the Famous Grouse.
Connell was the classic type of Distillers man, joining the company in 1946,
after Stowe and Oxford, and throwing coal on the fire at the Tanqueray gin
subsidiary, where his father was managing director. From there he climbed the
ladder, sober-suited, unassuming and with an allegedly steely edge.
But somebody needed to prod the giant into life, they said, though who could
possibly buy over Scotland's largest company?
James Gulliver decided to try. He showed his hand in September 1985 but was
hindered by the Takeover Panel from making his bid for three months. Distillers
prepared its defence. The American Bill Spengler was drafted in as deputy
chairman to add strength to the board and Sir Nigel Broackes, chairman of
Trafalgar House, was also brought to the board.
Guinness got wind of events and eyed that glorious portfolio of 60 Distillers'
whiskies, ranging from Johnnie Walker to Haig's, as well as Gordon's and
Booth's gin and the popular Pimms. But they had just taken over Bell's of Perth
and Ernest Saunders said he didn't relish another bruising battle.
From many sides, however, he was being counselled to think about it. The head
of the Guinness family, Lord Iveagh, for example, was feeling it was time they
were restored on the perch alongside the Rothschilds and people of such ilk.
Gulliver made his opening bid of #1864m on December 2, 1985, backed by the
Royal Bank of Scotland - for 100 years bankers to Distillers, who promptly
sacked them. John Connell told Distillers' 104,000 shareholders they were
fighting the bid. If there was to be a buyer at all they clearly preferred
Guinness, who then joined battle with Gulliver.
As that battle raged, Argyll announced they were suing both Distillers and
Guinness over their agreement that the latter's costs in the bid would be borne
by the Scots company. Argyll upped its bid and so did Guinness, the latter
saying they would bring their headquarters to Scotland and appoint as their
chairman Sir Thomas Risk, Governor of the Bank of Scotland.
On April 18, 1986, Guinness won the battle at #2.6bn and James Gulliver's
Argyll bowed out gracefully, selling its holding in Distillers at a profit of
#140m, which did not however cover the cost of their bid.
The battle had been long, bloody and expensive and, for the directors of
Distillers, a pretty humiliating end to a decade of decline.
Within months Guinness stirred anger by reneging on its undertaking to move HQ
to Scotland - and Sir Thomas Risk did not become chairman. Instead, Ernest
Saunders took over the role.
That seemed to be that, until the autumn of 1986 brought the first whiff of
scandal. The high-profiled Wall Street trader Ivan Boesky revealed he had
helped support the Guinness share-price during the takeover, improving its
chances of success. In return, Guinness had been investing in Boesky's business.
All hell was about to break loose, involving the Serious Fraud Office.
Executive chairman Saunders faced charges of theft, false accounting and
conspiracy, the main thrust of the trial being that he and others engaged in a
multi-million-pound support of Guinness shares so that they would look the more
attractive proposition to the shareholders of Distillers.
It was a major business drama, fascinating in its detail if sometimes a
bewilderment to those outwith the world of wheeling and dealing. After six
months of evidence and five days of jury consideration, estimated at #25m plus
investigative costs, four defendants were found guilty.
Ernest Saunders was sentenced to five years, which was halved on appeal.
Property-to-petrol tycoon Gerald Ronson, of the Heron Group, was sent to prison
for a year and fined a record #5m. Stockbroker Anthony Parnes was given a
two-and-a-half year sentence while financier Jack Lyons was fined #3m and
stripped of his knighthood, having escaped jail because of age and ill-health.
Other parts of the case either collapsed or didn't reach court and there were
allegations that the Establishment was looking after its own.
The subsequent story was that Saunders gained release after 10 months, said to
be suffering from a pre-senile dementia akin to Alzheimer's. He has since been
acting as a business consultant and has lectured on the problems facing
businessmen whose conduct comes under question. More recently he has been
enjoying a skiing holiday in Austria. Gerald Ronson served six months of his
sentence and returned to the helm of a Heron company which was suffering
financial problems.
Anthony Parnes was released after 11 months but faced difficulty in finding a
way back to the City, when he was refused a licence to engage in any
stockbroking work.
The ailing Jack Lyons retired from his business career and went to live in
Switzerland.
And what became of the directors who led the Distillers company before it was
taken over?
Chairman John Connell retired to Surrey. His brother David, who had been
managing director of Johnnie Walker, stayed on with the new owners for a time,
became chairman of the Scotch Whisky Association but has since retired to
Surrey, where he pursues his hobby of bird-watching.
Ronnie Martin, who was Distillers' whisky production director, is the only
other member of the board still active in business. He, too, stayed on with
Guinness but retired at 60 in 1991. He then went into business with son Hamish
and runs a drinks company called Inverarity Vaults in Edinburgh. He is also
Visiting Professor of Distilling at Heriot Watt University.
Of the others, Bill Spengler went back to America; David Kerr is secretary of
the Hurlingham Tennis Club; Lord Maclean and Cary Younghusband are dead and
retirement became the option of: finance director Robert Temple, Sir William
Pile (former chairman of the Inland Revenue), company secretary William Elgood,
Peter Whitley, personnel boss William Forrest, John Holbech and David Small,
who was managing director of Dewar's.
In the aftermath of all that, Guinness suffered a tarnished image but managed
to salvage the situation by appointing as chairman the highly-regarded Scots
businessman Sir Norman Macfarlane, later to become Lord Macfarlane of Bearsden.
He in turn brought in another able Scot, Anthony Tennant, as managing director
and the end result of the whole messy business is that the revamped Guinness
has made a notable success of the old Scottish company, now known as United
Distillers.
Looking reflectively from his Edinburgh pad, James Gulliver acknowledges that
success and tells me: ``What Anthony Tennant did was precisely what we were
intending to do.''
Deprived of the opportunity, however, he merely shrugs and moves on to another
phase of an eventful life.
</TEXT>
