<HEADLINE>Scots envoy paralysed after Kenyan shooting</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nairobi, Monday
A SCOTS diplomat shot by thugs in Nairobi last week was in serious condition in
hospital tonight, the British High Commission in Nairobi said.
Mr Graeme Gibson, a second secretary, was admitted to the private Nairobi
Hospital after he was shot in the neck while driving to his home in a suburb of
the capital on Friday night.
Three men in a stolen car trailed him and fired at him after failing to force
him to stop.
Mr Gibson lost control of his four-wheel-drive car - favoured by expatriates in
Kenya and a major target of robbers - and crashed into a gate.
The thieves' car was later involved in a collision, but they escaped after
hijacking another car, police said.
``He is in a serious but stable condition. At the moment he is paralysed,'' a
High Commission spokeswoman said of Mr Gibson. She declined to give any further
details.
Attacks on diplomats have increased sharply in the past year and Kenyan
President Daniel arap Moi last month urged police to move to stem the tide.
Last week heads of the diplomatic corps met Kenyan foreign minister Kalonzo
Musyoka to press their case for improved security.
The minister told parliament last week that diplomats were not ``specifically
targeted'' by thugs but were, like ordinary Kenyans, victims of rising crime in
the East African country.
But he pledged better security for diplomats.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
