<HEADLINE>Russian leader leaves hospital</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow, Monday
RUSSIA'S President Boris Yeltsin left hospital for a sanatorium today after a
month of treatment for a heart complaint, but may be unable to play an active
role in the country's election campaign.
Spokesman Sergei Medvedev refused to be drawn on whether Yeltsin, now under
medical supervision at Barvikha sanatorium, would be fit to take an active part
in the run-up to the December 17 parliamentary election.
``The president will be staying at Barvikha until he is completely well,'' he
said.
Asked if Mr Yeltsin would be in the sanatorium on polling day, Medvedev said:
``That's a question you have to ask the doctors.''
But Itar-Tass news agency said treatment at Barvikha, hidden in woodland some
15 miles to the west of Moscow, could last up to a month.
``If you consider that this time the doctors are insisting on Boris Yeltsin
undergoing a full course of treatment, you can assume that the head of state
will return to his Kremlin office around the end of December,'' Tass said.
Mr Yeltsin was rushed to hospital on October 26 after his     second heart
attack in less than four months.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
