<HEADLINE>Two Dogs provide a boost for Merrydown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MERRYDOWN is as happy as a puppy with two tails - which is not difficult given
the outstanding success of the Two Dogs alcoholic lemonade, writes ANDREW
WILSON.
That is the new drinks sub-sector which has taken Britain by storm and its
market penetration has been such that in three months since its launch in July,
Two Dogs was responsible for perhaps half the improvement in Merrydown's
half-time profits advance from #340,000 to #1.16m.
In the last few weeks, growth has predictably slowed because of the cooler
weather but Christmas could well be a new opportunity.
Sensibly, Merrydown abandoned the making of low margin own label cider for the
supermarkets to create capacity for its new product. That does not prevent an
increase in overall cider volumes although chairman Richard Purdey was
reluctant to give volume figures yesterday, claiming that it would be
commercially disadavantageous.
The cider industry is now dominated as to about 90% by HP Bulmer and Matthew
Clark after the acquisition of Taunton Cider. That should provide opportunities
for the smaller players with some retailers not wishing to become overly
dependent on what is almost a duopoly of supply.
Merrydown is in the fortunate position of now having its Original Cider
distributed by Whitbread through its managed outlets and that has made good
progress despite no promotion as yet.
Analysts are looking for a massive swinground in profitability from a #2.70m
loss into a pre-tax profit of about #2m. That would leave the shares trading at
about 10 times earnings which may be a slight undervaluation.
The interim dividend has been doubled to 2p so that a full-year total of 4p for
a 3.9% yield is on the cards. Dividend cover will remain high to      help
build up balance sheet strength.
