<HEADLINE>Hang on, this is right up my street</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Julia Langdon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Everybody needs good neighbours, but what happens when neighbours become
authors in their own right? Then, finds Julia Langdon, you start to ask pointed
questions after seeing familiar faces peering out from the pages of the novel
ANTONIA Swinson is one of those infuriating people who has had about six
careers before the age of 40. She lived in Italy and taught English to some
distinguished Italians so that she could learn their language and be a singer.
She was a successful actress in Scotland in her twenties. She had a spell doing
very profitable voice-overs for children's products. She was a Fleet Street
journalist, a television critic, a woman's page journalist and then a business
writer.
In the last couple of years, while working for the charity Common Purpose, and
being a freelance singer and doing the odd bit of journalism, and still finding
time to deliver the parish magazine, she has also been raising two small
children and writing a novel. And she never looks other than beautifully
turned-out - not even when she's putting the rubbish out at dawn on Mondays.
She is one of that sort; the ones who make you grit your teeth with irritation
when you read about them. Unless, that is, you know them.
And as it happens I know Antonia Swinson and the backcloth of her novel rather
well, including the day on which her dustman comes to call, because not only
was she until recently a neighbour of mine but she has written a book which is,
at least loosely, all about our street. According to one of the reviews, she
has made ``a landscape of characters who might have been types or cliches into
real people''. Wrong. It is entirely the other way around.
``Well, yes, there is a woman journalist in it,'' she said, when we went to the
caff round the corner to talk about it, ``but honestly, Julia, it's not you.''
There are, however, a couple of actors to be found in the plot and, yes, we
have a couple of them on our block. And we have the famous television
script-writer - he's just opposite, goes to the pub, keeps himself to himself,
you know. And yes, we can also boast what she calls the ``less successful
architects'' - unfortunate professional victims of the recession - and we have
a tree surgeon as well. What's this, on page 97, but a tree surgeon? Now not
every street has its own tree surgeon.
Then there is the desperately snobbish character who notices whether people
have unlined curtains - now who could that be? ``I can hear myself in half a
dozen places,'' one of the neighbours hissed. These are dangerous grounds,
Antonia, on to which you have dared to tiptoe.
She obviously has a relatively clear conscience because she did ask half the
neighbourhood to the launch party. But what about the other half? Were they
invited? Or were they enraged? And there is also the fact that she has now
high-tailed it back to Scotland, out of reach of the tittle-tattle. Could it be
that she is anxious about something? She did have it read for libel now, didn't
she?
She laughs off the back-biting and the bitching. ``There are no neighbours in
the book,'' she insists. ``I have met lots of people who are writers and
gallery owners and they are the sort of people I've written about. It's really
not based on anyone in particular.'' But who is Georgiana, she of the ruched
curtains? And what's all this about loft conversions? She won't say another
word about it. Everyone has a couple of snobby women and, really, she wouldn't
want to offend anyone. She is really very fond of the folk on our block.
Her refusal to be more specific is altogether regrettable. There is high drama
in our street; love and death, laughter and loathing, and just who was it who
dragged those bin bags down the street and left them outside Number 1? If,
however, I set down another word it will be I who gets the lawyers' letters -
or even, perhaps, the bin bags.
The book is set in six weeks in 1990 and is about the life and love of a widow
- in West London, yes, because that is what she knows - and about the
recession. We all know about that, too. At the time she wrote it, Antonia was
nursing her second baby, who was clingy and wouldn't let her out of the room,
and after the years in newspaper offices she felt distinctly isolated. ``The
more grim life became, the funnier the book became.''
She has a considerable literary inheritance. Her father, Arthur Swinson, who
died in 1970, wrote the first few series of Dr Finlay's Casebook. He was a
playwright and a military historian and the author of Scotch on the Rocks, the
story of the S.S. Politician, immortalised by Compton Mackenzie in Whisky
Galore. His daughter went to Edinburgh University in 1976, read English,
Italian and Scottish history - and fell in love with a Scotsman.
This is her husband, Alan Reid, from Ayr, who brought the family back to
Scotland this summer. ``I think I knew we would always come back here,'' she
says. She has a great affection for Scotland after her acting experiences -
even though as Cinderella at the Glasgow Pavilion she got chilblains from the
Glasgow winter and Dandini had the devil's own job pushing the slipper on.
She had learned to tap-dance in her last term at university and got her first
acting job at #75 per week in panto at the King's Theatre, Edinburgh. She was
in Babes in the Wood with Jack Milroy and Rikki Fulton and then landed a part
as a receptionist in the Auchtarn Hotel in STV's High Road. Then it was
Cinderella, with Sydney Devine as Buttons, and lots of glamorous pictures in
the newspapers. She loved it. The fact that she hadn't been to drama school
didn't bother her in the slightest. She had the confidence of youth, an Equity
card and recognition in the streets.
Fifteen years later and she is now in North Berwick, has bought a balaclava to
walk the kids to school and is loving it. And a little note for readers in
North Berwick. She is hard at work on the second novel . . . and this time it's
set in Scotland.
n The Widow's Tale, by Antonia Swinson, Gracewing, #6.99.
</TEXT>
