<HEADLINE>Fresh-air pioneers of yesteryear</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
David Belcher recounts those far-off days when country huts gave Glasgow's
tenement-dwellers the freedom to become someone else
THESE days you can't employ the phrase ``a house in the country'' without
hearing Blur's sneering dismissal of acquisitive homesteaders. Similarly, the
Ramblers' Association is no longer headed by lumpy proles in anoraks and woolly
hiking socks. Instead, it's overseen by Janet Street-Porter, a high-profile
metropolitan media panjandrum with a penchant for expensive Gore-tex
leisurewear.
Yet it all used to be so different back in those far-off days of working-class
solidarity . . . a time when the socialist hutters roamed certain hillsides in
the West of Scotland.
As a forthcoming edition of BBC Scotland's Ex-S documentary series will shortly
reveal, every weekend and for an annual summertime fortnight the hutters would
exchange Glasgow's teeming tenements for their own hand-built wooden refuges,
60ft square, in a two-acre field gifted them by a patrician mansion owner in
rural Carbeth, near Milngavie.
Shoulder to shoulder they advanced in search of fresh air, self-improvement,
and comradeship as proletarian foot soldiers of the Fellowship Camping
Association, an organisation which had its roots in such long-lost causes as
the Socialist Sunday School, the Clarion Scouts, and the Esperanto Club.
Kate Barclay is among the indomitable old-time hutters whose memories form the
bittersweet core of When Summers Were Longer, made for Ex-S under the direction
of Don Coutts by Move On Up, the Cromarty-based independent film company.
``The Clarion Scouts began in the Depression with the motto Bread and Roses,''
Kate recalls. ``They believed that simply providing the unemployed with food
wasn't enough; folk needed beauty in their lives too.''
In consequence, Clarion Scout activities included organising cycle clubs, drama
groups, an art section, and talks from botanists. Ironically, the beginning of
the end came when working-class horizons began to be widened by a greater
measure of personal wealth: although most of the Carbeth huts are still in use,
the FCA disbanded at the end of the sixties when ordinary folk began to acquire
cars.
Recently, a reluctant Kate sold her Carbeth hut to a couple of hillwalkers too
young to recall rambling's birth as a defiant act of mass trespass by the
underclasses; a means of demonstrating their opposition to the land-owning
capitalist oppressors who preferred to keep the oiks fenced out.
Bob Starrett, a veteran of the UCS shipyard sit-in who now paints film and TV
backdrops for a living, provides the programme's political background, having
acquired in his youth an extensive education - ``in all the -isms, from Marxism
to vegetarianism'' - from numerous Clydeside campfire philosophers.
``As a city kid in Stratford Street, Maryhill, we used to watch out for this
legendary joiner in the next street, a guy who used to disappear into a
mystical land every weekend, somewhere called The Country, and when he was out
there, he found the freedom to become someone else. We eventually got to know
someone who had a hut at Carbeth and we, too, went out there on Fridays, taking
a tram to Milngavie and then walking for miles.
``Carbeth was a focus for ex-Servicemen who had come home from the war and were
unable to face the nine-to-five routine, long before hippies were thought of.
They weren't malcontents . . . it was more that they were looking for an
alternative way of life. There was an esprit de corps, a camaraderie . . . it
sounds old, an anachronism now.''
Certainly it's hard to view some of the original 8mm home-movie footage of
Carbeth featured in When Summers Were Longer without tearful regret for a time
when hope seemed universal; when socialist idealism was in the ascendency.
Monochrome depictions of sun-dappled Austin A35s; proud mums in pinnies;
innocent teens twisting al fresco; weans tumbling their wilkies on the
greensward.
Yet the overwhelming mood of the Carbeth veterans, filmed for When Summers Were
Longer at a hutters' reunion, is a joyous one. Hutters look back with
amusement, not regret, recalling such sights as the Drumchapel Outbacker, an
intrepid explorer whose weekends were spent beneath the brim of a ridiculous
hat with corks dangling from it. Hugh Healy, poet and communist, meanwhile,
prefers to look forward to the English accents of his grandweans echoing round
Carbeth.
Maybe the huts provide a fitting metaphor for the spirit of their weekend
dwellers. Some of the huts are fashioned out of redundant boarding obtained
from Clydebank Co-Operative garage. Many of them have walls that are out of
true - a statement which could never be applied to the Carbeth fresh-air
pioneers.
n When Summers Were Longer can be seen on BBC1 next Monday at 10.25pm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quality shopping without a hassle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kate Rafferty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975159491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Kate Rafferty finds a festive package in Ayr which will take the strain out of
shopping around
SHOPPING should be part of the excitement in the run up to Christmas, but all
too often it becomes nothing more than a series of bad-tempered expeditions
where traffic congestion, parking problems, crowds and not knowing where to get
a decent cup of coffee are all unwelcome early presents.
There is a town, which can be reached in less than an hour from Glasgow, which
offers the full range of national retailers as well as many interesting local
shops.
These are just two reasons why Christmas shopping in Ayr makes sense.
Getting there couldn't be easier. For those not travelling by car, the train
station is five minutes walk from the High Street and is served by a
half-hourly service from Glasgow Central. There is also a large bus network
serving the town.
The majority of shoppers will probably arrive by car, however, and they are
more than adequately served with a large choice of on and off-street parking.
The roads into Ayr have signs directing motorists to the car park which suits,
whether it be long or short stay.
Town centre manager Sunil Varu is also pleased at the refurbishment of the
multi-storey car park which is close to the main shopping areas. ``The
multi-storey has been totally upgraded, with about #500,000 spent on it. It now
has extra lighting and closed circuit television, as well as being repainted,
making it much fresher-looking. We've removed what were the perceived problems
so I hope people will consider using it.''
Once the car is parked, Ayr has an added bonus. It is such a self-contained
town centre that shoppers won't have to walk far to enjoy the full range of
shops, entertainments and restaurants.
What Ayr Town Centre Management believes the town offers is a complete package,
a ``quality shopping experience'' and they have produced three comprehensive
guides which help take the hassle out of this time of year, putting some
enjoyment back into gift buying.
One of the guides concentrates on where to park in Ayr. An easy-to-follow map
details where each car park is situated, whether it's long or short stay, and
if there's a charge, how much it will cost.
Another guide tells weary shoppers where they can rest their feet and get some
refreshment. Every eating and drinking establishment is detailed and separated
by category, so whether it's just a quick coffee (or a quick something
stronger), a take-away sandwich or a full meal (the best in Scottish and
international cooking is on offer), a glance at the guide will point you in the
right direction.
Perhaps even handier than this, is the guide to shopping which includes every
shop in the centre. Again the shops are listed by category and it includes
addresses and telephone numbers.
The alphabetical categories run from Art/Picture Framers through to Wine
Merchants. Symbols next to certain shops show whether it offers facilities
which are essential to some, such as mother and baby rooms or automatic door
access.
Each of these pocket-sized guides can be collected from the town's tourist
board or shops throughout the centre.
The town centre management team are constantly researching new ways to help
those who choose to shop in Ayr. Another initiative is launched on December 7.
``We're launching our Shopmobility scheme that day,'' said Sunil Varu. ``This
will allow physically disabled people to park their cars, borrow or hire a
motorised wheelchair or scooter, and do their shopping more independently and
in comfort.''
The range of initiatives by the management team has brought three prestigious
awards to the town, two of which have never been awarded to a Scottish town or
city before.
``These awards are run by various organisations and magazines,'' said Mr Varu.
``The first was a street design competition in which Ayr received a
commendation.
``The second was an award which recognised traffic calming measures, put in
place to reduce road accidents. This was in conjunction with the improvement of
the aesthetic environment of the town The third, which we only received quite
recently, came from the British Council of Shopping Centres. Again it's the
first time the award, which we shared with Hemel Hempstead, has come to
Scotland.''
The final award, said Mr Varu, ``recognises what a lot of organisations locally
have been striving for''. It is given to the town which is judged to have put a
clear strategy for town centre improvement into practice, raising the quality
of not only the provision of shops but of amenities such as parking,
environment, pedestrianisation and closed circuit television (which Ayr has had
in operation for four months).
Strolling along: relaxed shopping in the pedestrianised Newmarket Street in Ayr
</TEXT>
