<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Slaughterhouses may face tighter BSE rules</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Ross</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SLAUGHTERHOUSE operators, already chafing at the cost of implementing anti-BSE
measures, may face a further tightening of regulations, UK Agriculture Minister
Douglas Hogg warned yesterday.
Speaking at the Smithfield FarmTech event, the Minister said it was vital that
the regulations were applied 100% and he admitted that since the summer 17
breaches had been detected.
He ruled out, however, the possibility of the Government putting extra funds
into the industry to cover additional costs.
Mr Hogg said he deplored the damage which had been done to the beef industry's
standing in the eyes of the public by the dispute over who should share the
cost of disposing of specified bovine offal (SBO).
Sir David Naish, president of the National Farmers' Union of England and Wales,
joined the Minister in attacking the public bickering between auctioneers and
meat company operators over the meat companies' attempts to impose a #3.50 a
head levy to cover their SBO costs.
In Scotland, at least, the auctioneers, the meat plant operators and the NFUS
have been able to find common ground.
In a statement yesterday they announced the formation of a working party which
has been charged with devising an all-industry approach to the problems of BSE
and the disposal of SBOs.
It is hoped that the working party will report by mid-January. In the meantime
the meat operators have agreed to withdraw their demand that farmers should
meet half the costs of implementing the SBO measures by paying a levy on each
animal sold at auction.
The announcement of a resumption of trading ``on normal terms'' ends the fear
that markets could be hit by an expansion of direct procurement from farm to
slaughterhouse.
The Scots have made more progress than their counterparts in England. The Meat
and Livestock Commission intends to convene a joint meeting south of the Border
but no date has yet been agreed.
The name-calling in England has been more bitter and the NFU has complained to
the Office of Fair Trading about meat traders acting ``in concert'' to force
auctioneers to accept the levy.
Ian Gardiner, the English NFU policy director, claimed yesterday that farmers
had already absorbed a lot of costs associated with BSE eradication - about #7
an animal. They could not understand why the slaughterhouses felt justified in
seeking a further contribution from them.
Abattoirs could recover their costs in two ways - partly through prices for
meat and partly by a slimming process with one or two operators closing down,
he suggested. The abattoir industry had clearly been under stress before the
SBO arrangements came in.
Farmers attending a discussion forum at Smithfield warned the Agriculture
Minister that fears over BSE could destroy the beef industry. They called for
the Ministry of Agriculture to make greater efforts to reassure the public.
Mr Hogg said that the scientific evidence was positively reassuring that BSE
could not be transmitted to humans and that Creutzfeldt Jacob Disease - which
has been described as the human equivalent - was not contracted by eating beef.
``We do not believe that there is a link between the two diseases,'' he said.
Control measures were aimed at preventing any SBO material from getting into
the food chain - either human or animal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951128-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots reign at Smithfield</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND yet again reigned supreme in the cattle ring at Smithfield with the
overall award going to Donald Bhan, a December 1994 cross Charolais steer from
Ewen MacPherson and Sons, Mill Farm, Oban.
This steer, which weighed 543kg with a daily live weight gain of 1.51kg, was
bred by the MacPhersons and was sired by the 18,000gns bull Simpson's Gregg
which is shared with the MacGregors of Allanfauld, Kilsyth. It is out of a
Charolais cross cow.
For the MacPhersons, father Ewen and sons Donald and Ewen, it was a second
Smithfield triumph, repeating the feat they achieved back in 1989 with The
Bandit.
However, for Donald MacPherson this win was even sweeter. He said: ``It seemed
harder this time and also very nerve-wracking. But I suppose the fact that we
bred this one is especially satisfying.'' Indeed it was, with the MacPhersons
taking the King's Cup for the best beast bred by an exhibitor.
Standing reserve overall was the July 1994 Limousin cross steer Dark Destroyer
from John Yates, Moscow Farm, Derby. This steer weighed 487kg with a daily gain
of 0.98kg.
Commenting on the championship, the judge, John Dawkins, said: ``It was not an
easy job, but today we have seen what is indisputably the best beef in the
world - British beef.
The top two animals have meat in the right place over the loins, rump and
second thigh with no waste. They are near perfection.''
There was also a strong Scottish element in the other championship awards with
the junior heifer title going to Rae Grieve, Carhurlie, Lundin Links, Fife,
with his Winter Fair reserve, the Limousin Peekaboo.
Allan MacGregor, The Binn, Glenfarg, took the junior heifer title, while Tom
and Gavin Scott, Gateside, Linlithgow, won the senior heifer section with Lady
Barbara.
But the overall heifer championship went to a pure Charolais from Mervyn and
Chris Parker, Grange, Duxford, Cambridge.
The heavyweight steer championship was another Scottish triumph with Scott
Watson, Balhousie, Carnoustie, winning with his Limousin cross Angus,
No-Kan-Do, ahead of yet another Limousin cross from the MacPhersons - OJ
Simpson.
The sheep championship went to a pair of pure bred Suffolk ewe lambs from Jack
Bulmer, Great Habton, Malton, York.
This was Mr Bulmer's sixth supreme title and, he said, ``definitely the very
last''.
These winners had Scottish blood behind them too as they were sired by
Lauderdale Lovejoy, which was purchased for 4000gns from James Dun, Colmslie,
Galashiels. The champion sold for #270 to Brian Glaves, a retail butcher from
Brompton in Yorkshire.
The reserve pair of sheep were Beltex ewe lambs from David Gardiner, Knowle
Farm, Derby.
The sheep judge, Allen Eastwood, was much impressed with the overall quality,
commenting: ``The Suffolks had that bit of extra length, but all the champions
were in line with consumer demand and would sell in any market.''
</TEXT>
