<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sad times for Spring Ram</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Chris Stone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES of Spring Ram, the kitchens, bathrooms and furniture group, fell 7p to a
new 1995 closing low of 17p after hitting 15p, as the company warned of
continuing deteriorating trading conditions and said its second-half
performance was likely to be well below market expectations, writes CHRIS STONE.
These had already been badly dented in August when it reported an unexpected
drop in operating profits from #2.2m to #1.5m, while exceptional charges of
#16.7m took the pre-tax loss to #17.3m.
Yesterday the company said that trading conditions in the third quarter
remained extremely difficult in the building materials sector. ``Each of the
group's divisions experienced a further deterioration in trading conditions,
albeit that export sales have moved ahead as planned,'' said the firm.
A significant loss before tax had been incurred during the four months to the
end of October and it was not expecting the situation to improve before the end
of the year. Restructuring to improve costs and cash generation is being
undertaken, but tough market conditions are thought unlikely to improve in the
foreseeable future.
</TEXT>
