<DOCNO>GH951128-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951128-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951128</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tarmac heads up consortium</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<FLAG>business disgest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975159496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION group Tarmac heads up a consortium that has won a contract for the
#90m redevelopment of the Princess Margaret Hospital in Swindon. The project is
the largest so far under the Government's Private Finance Initiative.
The Swindon and Marlborough NHS Trust is expected to gain Government approval
for the plans in spring 1996, which should allow building to start early next
summer.
Financial support for the project is expected from among others The Royal Bank
of Scotland.
New owner
CLUB 18-30 and Sunset Holidays have a new owner, Flying Colours Leisure Group.
The acquisition vehicle has been put together in a #40m deal masterminded by
NatWest Ventures. In addition, Flying Colours has introduced a new product,
Priority Holidays, offering package holidays for those seeking a ``child free''
environment.
Sale confirmed
THE sale of the Olympus sports shops for #15m to former Amber Day head Philip
Green and Scottish sports retailer Tom Hunter, announced over the weekend, was
confirmed yesterday. They will be taking control of 123 retail outlets, 53
in-store concessions and 22 out-of-town stores. Sears' sale of the loss-making
chain will generate #25m in cash flow but there will be a loss on disposal of
#35m.
Roles split
GKN is to split the roles of chairman and chief executive next year in advance
of the scaling back of the duties of the present incumbent of both posts, Sir
David Lees. Aberdeen-born Sir David will reach 60 years of age by December next
year and will become non-executive chairman for three years from the beginning
of 1997.
Internet phone
FIRECREST, whose interests span marketing, publishing and the Internet, has
developed a telephone hand-set for use on the Internet and that will perform as
a normal telephone when connected directly into a computer.
Brunel departure
FINANCE director Alun Hicks has left Brunel Holdings, the construction
equipment and engineering group based at Chippenham, Wiltshire, by mutual
consent.
</TEXT>
