<HEADLINE>Vatican hits back at critics over Irish divorce poll</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PHILIP PULLELLA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975159497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Vatican today said the legalisation of divorce in Roman Catholic Ireland
was not a defeat for the Church but rather one for family and society.
``The result of the referendum.......is not a `defeat' for the Church, as has
been said emphatically,'' the Vatican newspaper L'Osservatore Romano said.
``Logic and conscience say it is a defeat for the family, which loses one of
its constructive values - the unity and indissolubility of marriage,'' the
newspaper said.
The end of a 58-year-old ban on divorce in Ireland by a fistful of votes was
the second international public disappointment for Pope John Paul in a week.
The weekend vote came less than a week after the defeat of devoutly Roman
Catholic Lech Walesa at the hands of former communist Aleksander Kwasniewski in
the Polish presidential elections.
Two of Italy's leading newspapers - Milan's Corriere della Sera and La Stampa
of Turin - today ran front-page editorials saying the two cases pointed to the
Church's waning influence over increasing materialistic European societies.
``It is difficult for the Holy See to swallow two sensational international
knockouts in only seven days,'' the Rome newspaper La Republica said yesterday.
L'Osservatore, in a comment from Dublin, said divorce was merely a ``perverse
mechanism against the family'' that only gendered more divorce.
``Because the stability, the well-being and the harmony of society is based on
the unity and harmony of the family, when it breaks down or is threatened,
those who suffer the most are the children,'' the Vatican newspaper said.
As result, the newspaper argued, all of society suffered, adding that the rise
in petty crime could be traced to the breakdown of the family.
The report from Dublin ended with a challenge: ``Does a secular and consumer
society have the courage to ask itself questions about these values?''
In Ireland, the closest result in the country's electoral history came only
four days after the Pope intervened in the campaign by urging the Irish ``to
reflect on the importance for society of the indissoluble character of the
marriage bond''.
Ireland was a softer blow for the Vatican than Poland because of the slim
margin by which the divorce referendum won. But the defeats came in countries
where the sway the Church held over its faithful was once unquestioned.
Sources have said the Church may have to rethink its methods of appealing to
the people and of trying to exercise political influence in Roman Catholic
countries.
``Ireland and Poland were two cases which showed the evolution of a certain
type of culture into smaller societies that were once closed and have simply
caught up with the rest of Europe,'' one Church source said.
``In a sense both results are anti-Pope and anti-Church because, if he and the
Church identifed with a certain way of thinking, the results showed that this
way of thinking is losing out,'' the source said.
In both cases, Church sources say, some people may have voted the way they did
deliberately to spite the Church because they felt its influence over daily
life was excessive.
The Irish result came on the heels of a poll taken for a conference of Italy's
Church hierarchy. It showed that many Italians considered littering a more
serious sin than adultery, homosexual activity or premarital sex.-Reuter.
John Macleod.............23
</TEXT>
