<HEADLINE>Wet Wet Wet SECC, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain Ross</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975159498</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HUGE barn of a place, the SECC. Normally, you'd expect some variety among an
audience of this size, a few kooky cats with crazy clothes, hairstyles or
behaviour; the loose threads of life's variegated tapestry.
But a Wet Wet Wet concert is different. The audience are uniform in their
ordinariness. Quite disconcerting.
Still, our expectations were high. What bounty of surprises would the Wetties
have in store? Curtain-up and all was revealed: a stage set filched from a
Saturday-night TV variety show special, circa 1975. All stairs laced with
beaded lights, fireworks, and kitsch ostentation. Beautiful.
And there was Marti, resplendent in a black glittery jacket, Tony Blair smile
turned on full beam, launching into hit after hit after hit.
Wishing I Was Lucky, Goodnight Girl, Angel Eyes, even Love Is All Around - they
were all there. Then, in Memphis tribute mode, the boys launched into an Elvis
medley. Surprisingly, when Marti loses the strange affectation that forces him
to use the full length and breadth of his vocal range on each and every word he
sings, Marti does a fair impression of the fat Pelvismeister. Unfortunately, he
can't dance for toffee. This is a man who has trouble walking in time.
In conclusion, the problem with Wet Wet Wet is that, like their name, their
success is premised on the repetition of a single idea.
A torpid haze soon descends, Morpheus opens his arms and you find yourself
falling, falling . . . Huge jets of flame, shooting up from stage-front
funnels, blast us back to consciousness. ``Anybody singe their pubic hair?''
cackles Marti. Top end-of-the-pier humour from a master.
</TEXT>
